WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.400
[Amit Varma]: Why do we read books and watch movies? Part of the reason is to immerse ourselves in the

00:00:09.400 --> 00:00:14.520
[Amit Varma]: heads of other people, experience many lives instead of just our own. But the other great

00:00:14.520 --> 00:00:19.680
[Amit Varma]: reason is not about discovering others, but about discovering ourselves. I sometimes wonder

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:25.040
[Amit Varma]: how much of my own self do I truly know? When I look back on how I viewed myself in my 20s,

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:30.760
[Amit Varma]: I realized that I did not know myself at all. I had a flat, distorted view of who I was.

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:36.220
[Amit Varma]: There were layers to me that I did not see. And what I did see was a misleading outline.

00:00:36.220 --> 00:00:41.040
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure that despite my best attempts at self-reflection, that is true even today.

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.680
[Amit Varma]: How do we get past this? Art is one way. When we read books and watch movies, then through

00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:51.000
[Amit Varma]: the lives of others, we discover parts of ourselves that we did not know existed. I'm

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.880
[Amit Varma]: sure you also felt that shock of recognition when something in a book or a film touches

00:00:55.880 --> 00:01:00.840
[Amit Varma]: you deeply. And it touches you deeply for a reason. The more we immerse ourselves in

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:07.040
[Amit Varma]: books and films, the better we know ourselves. Just as art can increase our empathy for others,

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:26.000
[Unknown]: it can increase our understanding of ourselves.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Jai Arjun Singh, best known as a

00:01:30.240 --> 00:01:35.440
[Amit Varma]: writer on film, but who also writes brilliantly about books and culture in general. I first

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:40.520
[Amit Varma]: met Jai in the heady blogging days of around 2004. I used to blog at India Uncut, his blog

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:45.120
[Amit Varma]: was called Jabberwock, and I immediately fell in love with his writing on films and books.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:50.480
[Amit Varma]: The one quality that I liked about Jai's work is best expressed by Javed Akhtar's favourite

00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:55.600
[Amit Varma]: word, Thairav. I can't think of a precise English translation for it, though I'd describe

00:01:55.600 --> 00:02:01.460
[Amit Varma]: it as a kind of stillness that allows for reflection. In Jai's case, often self-reflection

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:04.920
[Amit Varma]: through the prism of art. That quality was something that you could cultivate through

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:09.600
[Amit Varma]: the form of blogs. Newspapers and magazines did not give you that space of freedom, and

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:14.680
[Amit Varma]: left a writer breathless because of the need to rush through what they wanted to say.

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Jai went on to write books on the film Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro, the director Rishikesh Mukherjee,

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:24.440
[Amit Varma]: and he also edited an anthology of essays on films called Popcorn Essays. I still look

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:28.800
[Amit Varma]: forward to everything he writes, and I absolutely love this conversation. We spoke about the

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:34.000
[Amit Varma]: loneliness of growing up as a film lover in the 80s and 90s, how taste can both shape

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:39.440
[Amit Varma]: and be shaped by the circumstances of your life. What happens when art is viewed through

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:44.360
[Amit Varma]: ideological prisms, as often happens these days. And Jai also coaxed me to revisit Hindi

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:50.040
[Amit Varma]: films of the 1980s, which he says was not such a bad decade after all. Rahul Ravel,

00:02:50.040 --> 00:02:54.480
[Amit Varma]: Zindabad, it seems. We actually didn't cover many of the subjects we wanted to chat about.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:59.480
[Amit Varma]: Three hours is simply not enough. So we'll do future episodes as well. But for now, sit

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:05.120
[Amit Varma]: back and enjoy. And before that, let's take a quick commercial break.

