00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:32.960
[Amit Varma]: Jai, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:04:32.960 --> 00:04:36.960
[Guest]: Thanks. Thanks for having me. We've been talking about doing this for a while. Glad

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:37.960
[Guest]: we're finally doing it.

00:04:37.960 --> 00:04:42.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, in fact, we last spoke about it when I was in fact in Delhi last year, I had come

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:49.080
[Amit Varma]: in February to do a bunch of episodes. I think I recorded some 10 episodes in two weeks in

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.920
[Amit Varma]: an actual physical studio. And I remember you and I met in Saket and we had coffee at

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:57.320
[Amit Varma]: this delightful bookshop where I browsed around and discovered future guests. That's the place

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:02.200
[Amit Varma]: where I first saw Tripur Daman Singh's book, for example. And and yeah, and then we went

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:06.440
[Amit Varma]: to this restaurant and we discussed that we have to do an episode sometime and here we

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:12.000
[Amit Varma]: are and just look what the hell happened after that. What have these last few months been

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:13.000
[Amit Varma]: like for you?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.480
[Guest]: Well, it's been tough like it has been for many people, but of course not not as tough

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:23.040
[Guest]: as it as it has been for the worst affected. Getting along being that, you know, in in

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:28.460
[Guest]: keeping with with what we're going to be talking about, I've actually done a few online sessions

00:05:28.460 --> 00:05:33.680
[Guest]: and courses about cinema, which is something that I that I probably wouldn't have thought

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:38.760
[Guest]: to start if it hadn't been for the pandemic and, and everything that it engendered, got

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:45.680
[Guest]: into the world of, you know, of online sessions and became comfortable with it. And it's it's

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:53.360
[Guest]: been at least that part of it has been going fairly well. Other things, not so much.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:57.960
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's kind of been I mean, I also started my writing course in April last year, and

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:01.880
[Amit Varma]: it was just off a luck where I thought that, you know, would people be interested, I put

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:06.080
[Amit Varma]: out a tweet asking if people were interested and people said yes, and it's still going

00:06:06.080 --> 00:06:11.480
[Amit Varma]: strong. I mean, the 14th cohort is kind of going on now. And it's also interesting, I

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:15.880
[Amit Varma]: was thinking about every time we meet, and we don't meet very often, because, hey, Bombay,

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:20.400
[Amit Varma]: Delhi, though, I must tell you that I meet my Bombay friends less than I meet you, because

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:23.360
[Amit Varma]: you just take it for granted that they're in the same city, right? So you're not fixing

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:27.360
[Amit Varma]: up meetings and going and all of that. But it struck me that we actually met very few

00:06:27.360 --> 00:06:31.240
[Amit Varma]: times in the sense that we of course, got to know of each other when we started blogging.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:36.020
[Amit Varma]: And I'll discuss that period in detail with you also. But so that's, that's when we kind

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:41.800
[Amit Varma]: of came to know each other. And we found this very easy groove to our friendship, as it

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:46.040
[Amit Varma]: were, that every time we meet, we're in the same kind of place. And you know, it's easy

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:50.100
[Amit Varma]: and it's comfortable. And it's almost like a comfort zone thing. And the reason I kind

00:06:50.100 --> 00:06:54.920
[Amit Varma]: of bring this up is I've done episodes in the last few months with people I've known

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:59.560
[Amit Varma]: for about as long as you in the same way as you, friends like Deepak Chinoy, Sonia Falero,

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:03.240
[Amit Varma]: who was in Bombay for a few years, so I did spend much more time with her. But it was

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:08.920
[Amit Varma]: interesting and I was just thinking about how friendships develop and form these kind

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:12.520
[Amit Varma]: of grooves. The easiest way to form a group of friendship is of course, when you're in

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:16.280
[Amit Varma]: school or college with someone and you're spending a lot of time together and you figure

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:20.880
[Amit Varma]: out each other's comfort zones and all of that. And the interesting thing is that, but

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:26.320
[Amit Varma]: that is shaped almost by happenstance because you know, your physical location determines

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:30.200
[Amit Varma]: everything, you are in school or you are in college where you are, you can't choose anything.

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:34.960
[Amit Varma]: And also you change over time. So today I have virtually no friends, one or two maybe,

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:40.760
[Amit Varma]: whom I'm still in touch with from sort of my pre 20 life, but I have plenty of people

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:46.160
[Amit Varma]: who are now my friends who I met in the mid-oughties like you, who you meet them because of a common

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:50.480
[Amit Varma]: interest or a common thing you do. And then you just find a groove and that groove is

00:07:50.480 --> 00:07:56.220
[Amit Varma]: almost kind of always there. And it's said that later in life, you have trouble making

00:07:56.220 --> 00:08:00.860
[Amit Varma]: new friends and both of us are introverts, right? I do find it hard to kind of make new

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:05.880
[Amit Varma]: friends and find these grooves and all of that. And that kind of just got me to thinking

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:10.120
[Amit Varma]: about the nature of friendship and what it is. And because at one level it just seems

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:15.560
[Amit Varma]: so mysterious, you know, sometimes I, in my misanthropic way, I can't figure out why anybody's

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:18.480
[Amit Varma]: friends with anybody. Any thoughts on this?

00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:23.760
[Guest]: Well, yeah, well, you know, you've already said quite a bit about it. So it's, you know,

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:27.320
[Guest]: it's kind of bounced as a question. 17 years. Can you believe it? It's been 17 years since

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:32.000
[Guest]: the since the blogging thing happened. I actually remember the first time we met when you had

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.440
[Guest]: come to Delhi for something after we had been in touch with, you know, through the blogosphere.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:43.480
[Guest]: And I was listening to parts of your conversation with Annie Zaidi a while back. And she was

00:08:43.480 --> 00:08:49.960
[Guest]: also part of the blog meets of 2004-2005 when we were all being introduced to each other

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:57.000
[Guest]: as KnownTurf and Jabberwock and IndiaUncut and so on. What you were saying, you know,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.280
[Guest]: it's interesting, I quite possibly, though this is don't want to get into competition

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:07.440
[Guest]: territory now, but I quite possibly had even fewer friends than you did in my school years.

00:09:07.440 --> 00:09:13.040
[Guest]: In addition to being introverted, I was also very painfully shy. And I know there was a

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:18.040
[Guest]: lot of melancholia, things weren't great on the personal front, there were things, things

00:09:18.040 --> 00:09:23.920
[Guest]: going on, having to be away from school for four periods. And it just struck me that one

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:30.720
[Guest]: of the things that happened, you know, when in the early 90s, when I really got into watching,

00:09:30.720 --> 00:09:35.380
[Guest]: I got into doing the sorts of things that the few friends I had were absolutely not

00:09:35.380 --> 00:09:40.320
[Guest]: interested in at the time, you know, obviously, reading voraciously is one thing that I had

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:45.580
[Guest]: that habit from from an early age, but getting into watching old Hollywood films, then watching

00:09:45.580 --> 00:09:50.240
[Guest]: world cinema, getting into all that as an adolescent. And I went through a period of

00:09:50.240 --> 00:09:55.280
[Guest]: around six, seven years of crippling loneliness. This is in the pre internet period, where

00:09:55.280 --> 00:10:00.040
[Guest]: I was convinced, absolutely convinced that that I would, you know, go my whole life without

00:10:00.040 --> 00:10:05.320
[Guest]: ever having the sorts of friends who shared some of these interests, the specific interests.

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:08.640
[Guest]: And then of course, the internet comes along. And then within a few years, you know, of

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:12.840
[Guest]: course, one thing led to another, I got a journalistic job which put me in touch with

00:10:12.840 --> 00:10:18.040
[Guest]: people with similar interests, then suddenly a blogging, and the world opens up and then

00:10:18.040 --> 00:10:22.080
[Guest]: you know, the people like you are out there, there are people outside India as well, you

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:26.960
[Guest]: suddenly find yourself in touch with who share these interests. And, and suddenly, it's a

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:32.320
[Guest]: very different landscape all around. But yeah, I mean, friendship, I don't know, I just feel

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:38.240
[Guest]: like it's, you know, it's you, you know, one of the cliches that that we're constantly

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:43.240
[Guest]: uttering, and you know, it's, it's, it's completely true, as cliches go, is that all of us contain

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:47.120
[Guest]: multitudes, right? And that we are, maybe we are different things at different points

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:52.480
[Guest]: in our life. In, you know, and, and even at the same point, you can be, you know, different

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:59.280
[Guest]: in one context with one person and, and in another context with another person, I think,

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:03.440
[Guest]: friendships just intersect in so many ways. But, but that being said, of course, there

00:11:03.440 --> 00:11:10.360
[Guest]: are some people with whom you have, you know, far more of a, of a kindred thing going on,

00:11:10.360 --> 00:11:14.720
[Guest]: you know, across across multiple interest areas. And those perhaps tend to be the more

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:15.720
[Guest]: lasting ones.

00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:20.600
[Amit Varma]: You know, when you speak of that crippling loneliness, I kind of identify with that in

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:24.680
[Amit Varma]: a sense. And, you know, there is another kind of crippling loneliness that I think there

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:29.480
[Amit Varma]: is there in today's generation for different kinds of reasons. But in our kind, a part

00:11:29.480 --> 00:11:34.320
[Amit Varma]: of it, of course, was that being in India, firstly, you got exposed to so little of the

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:38.680
[Amit Varma]: outside world, like, unlike today, everything wasn't at your fingertips. Like you said,

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:41.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, you've said elsewhere that once you got into foreign firms, you would go to

00:11:41.480 --> 00:11:46.400
[Amit Varma]: embassies, and you would take, you know, borrow video cassettes from there. And it was just

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:52.160
[Amit Varma]: an effort to get anything of that kind. And therefore, by default, like first, you're

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:55.960
[Amit Varma]: in a poor country where, you know, culture hasn't flooded in, we are not at that stage

00:11:55.960 --> 00:12:00.120
[Amit Varma]: of technology, where everything is on the internet. Secondly, only the very privileged

00:12:00.120 --> 00:12:03.800
[Amit Varma]: like you and me can, for example, see those kind of films, you know, you and me were probably

00:12:03.800 --> 00:12:07.440
[Amit Varma]: watching the same kind of films at the same kind of time, but we are in different cities.

00:12:07.440 --> 00:12:12.200
[Amit Varma]: So there is that physical barrier. And then at a later point in time, that physical barrier

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:17.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of breaks down, which I totally get. So tell me a bit about your childhood years.

00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:22.520
[Amit Varma]: Like, what was it like? What were you reading? What were you watching? How did you kind of

00:12:22.520 --> 00:12:24.520
[Amit Varma]: get drawn to films and so on?

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:29.880
[Guest]: There are no easy answers to those questions. But you know, anecdotally, what I was reading,

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest]: and I know, and this, of course, is true of, you know, this disconnect between the sort

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.240
[Guest]: of stuff that you're reading and the sort of stuff that you're watching. There's something

00:12:38.240 --> 00:12:42.040
[Guest]: that I think Mukul Kesavan or someone else may have written about this, written an essay

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:48.840
[Guest]: about this, a certain type of urban, anglophone Indian, who's sort of grown up in a city whose

00:12:48.840 --> 00:12:52.600
[Guest]: first language more often than not is English, or at least, you know, you're starting in

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:57.400
[Guest]: an English medium school. In my case, my parents spoke with me mostly in English. So so one

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:02.920
[Guest]: is reading Ladybirds and Enid Blyton's and things like that to start with, and then maybe

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:08.720
[Guest]: Amar Chitra Katha comics in English and stuff also. But one is almost exclusively watching

00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:13.040
[Guest]: Hindi films. That's the film culture that you're first exposed to. So it's a bit strange

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.240
[Guest]: really, when you think back on it, that the world of the famous five is intersecting with

00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:22.680
[Guest]: the world of, of the Amitabh Bachchan masala film, which was my preferred movie when I

00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:28.880
[Guest]: was, you know, growing up 6, 7, 8, 9, 10 years old. It sounds like the worst cliche on earth,

00:13:28.880 --> 00:13:34.040
[Guest]: but really Bachchan was my superhero. And the sorts of films I was most interested in

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:38.360
[Guest]: for the for the longest time, I think right up to the age of 12, 13, 14, were like I said,

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:44.520
[Guest]: the masala Hindi films, the Dishoom Dishoom films, the very macho Bachchan movies, or,

00:13:44.520 --> 00:13:48.880
[Guest]: you know, if the film didn't have Bachchan in it, it had to be a multi-starrer with three

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:54.480
[Guest]: or four heroes, you know, the Nagin, Jani Jutha, Dajani Dushman, Rajput sort of movie.

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:58.840
[Guest]: And it's pretty amusing because, you know, a few years ago, as you know, I did a book

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:04.520
[Guest]: on Rishikesh Mukherjee, who was known for the slightly more subdued, gentler, middle

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:08.440
[Guest]: cinema sort of sorts of movies. And when I was working on that book, many people just

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:12.360
[Guest]: assumed that when I was growing up in the single channel era, in the Doodh Darshan

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:18.040
[Guest]: era, like everybody else of my generation, I was besotted by the Rishida movies like

00:14:18.040 --> 00:14:22.360
[Guest]: Anand and Chupke Chupke and Golmaal, Babarchi, you know, watching them over and over as they

00:14:22.360 --> 00:14:27.240
[Guest]: appeared on TV. And that wasn't the case. I really wasn't at that point in my life when

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:32.280
[Guest]: I was when I was a child. I wasn't interested in these boring movies. I only wanted the

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:37.400
[Guest]: most action packed, masala-dar stuff. I didn't even want to see my favourite actors Amitabh

00:14:37.400 --> 00:14:42.440
[Guest]: and Dharmendra in these Bhadralok personas in a film like Chupke Chupke. So there was,

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:47.720
[Guest]: of course, a change in my tastes and a lot of things coming together in subsequent years.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:53.320
[Guest]: But initially, it was just that. One thing I'd like to just point out is, of course,

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:58.840
[Guest]: many of us are movie buffs or movie nerds at a certain age. One of the differences,

00:14:58.840 --> 00:15:03.360
[Guest]: one of the things that distinguishes someone who goes on to become a professional film

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:08.120
[Guest]: critic, writing about cinema is perhaps that from a very early age, I think from when I

00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:13.560
[Guest]: was six, seven, eight years old, I just developed this habit of maintaining a register in which

00:15:13.560 --> 00:15:19.640
[Guest]: I would write, I would just scribble down the titles and the star casts of whatever

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:22.760
[Guest]: films I saw, because of course, at that age, you're principally interested in the actors,

00:15:22.760 --> 00:15:27.680
[Guest]: right? That's what you're interested in. And because you've looked at newspaper, you know,

00:15:27.680 --> 00:15:32.320
[Guest]: reviews and star ratings, you've been influenced by that sort of thing. So I had a register

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:37.280
[Guest]: when I was maybe seven, eight years old, where I'd just be writing down things like, you

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:42.880
[Guest]: know, the titles of all the films that I saw, and giving them these massively exaggerated

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:48.040
[Guest]: star ratings, that would go right up to 16 stars, for instance, and what I was...

00:15:48.040 --> 00:15:49.040
[Amit Varma]: Out of a five star system.

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:54.280
[Guest]: Yeah, instead of the five star system, so you go from the zero star to the 16 star system.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:58.520
[Guest]: And, you know, there'd be different sorts of adjective combinations that I would use

00:15:58.520 --> 00:16:02.680
[Guest]: to describe what a particular rating meant. And I'd use up all the big words I knew. So

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:09.560
[Guest]: a 10 star film might only be a magnificent classic, but a 16 star film like Sholay, or

00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:15.880
[Guest]: whatever, might be a stupendously fantabulous masterpiece or something like that. So I got

00:16:15.880 --> 00:16:20.160
[Guest]: into that habit. And this, of course, is when I'm very small, seven, eight, nine years old.

00:16:20.160 --> 00:16:24.720
[Guest]: A few years after that, you know, when I was in my adolescence, I also became interested

00:16:24.720 --> 00:16:29.840
[Guest]: in rating films, in a perhaps more disciplined and organized way. When I when I got into

00:16:29.840 --> 00:16:33.760
[Guest]: old Hollywood films for the first time, and I bought an enormous movie guide called the

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:39.480
[Guest]: Leonard Maltin movie guide of 1990-91. And I lugged it around with me everywhere to video

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:44.920
[Guest]: shops to flip through, you know, to read the entries and individual films that were available

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:50.420
[Guest]: at the store. At that point, again, I got into the habit of maintaining a perhaps more

00:16:50.420 --> 00:16:55.840
[Guest]: organized register or diary of the films that I was watching. But by that point, I was also

00:16:55.840 --> 00:17:01.320
[Guest]: making little notes like one or two sentence crawls about the film, just something that

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:05.000
[Guest]: struck me about the film, something that I found interesting. And I suppose that was

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.640
[Guest]: really a prelude in many ways to writing more analytically about films, which is something

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:13.280
[Guest]: that would happen years later.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:16.600
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we get back to the personal journey, a couple of questions that come to

00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:21.960
[Amit Varma]: my mind from this. And one is that the moment you force yourself to give a rating for a

00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:25.800
[Amit Varma]: film, I would imagine that it forces you to think a little deeper about the film because

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:29.680
[Amit Varma]: then you have to question, why am I giving it three stars? Why am I giving it four stars?

00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:33.800
[Amit Varma]: What are the parameters? And equally, and a question that I'd really save for later,

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:38.880
[Amit Varma]: but it seems apt now is that does actually formally writing about film like at this stage,

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:42.280
[Amit Varma]: of course, you're doing notes, but later on, you go on to actually write about cinema in

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:48.120
[Amit Varma]: a more formal way. Does that force you to think deeper about films? Because one experience

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:52.000
[Amit Varma]: of a film lover can be that you go to watch a film, and you just sit down and you just

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:55.040
[Amit Varma]: watch it and you enjoy it for what it is, you have thoughts about it, but you don't

00:17:55.040 --> 00:17:59.280
[Amit Varma]: write them down anywhere. There's no structure to your thinking, you're not breaking shit

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:03.200
[Amit Varma]: down, you're not thinking that, you know, you're not necessarily making historical connections

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:07.480
[Amit Varma]: and going deep in all the many different ways that one can go deep, whether we are talking

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:12.640
[Amit Varma]: about the craft or the form or the, you know, where it stands in the director's previous

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:17.440
[Amit Varma]: work and all of that. So does first giving these kind of ratings and to then actually

00:18:17.440 --> 00:18:23.440
[Amit Varma]: writing about cinema, does it force you to engage that much deeper in the sense that

00:18:23.440 --> 00:18:26.880
[Amit Varma]: you have thoughts you wouldn't otherwise have had, and because you have had thoughts that

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:30.680
[Amit Varma]: you wouldn't otherwise have had, you are a changed person, you know, would you would

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:31.680
[Guest]: you say that?

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:34.960
[Guest]: Yeah, no, no, no, of course, it does work that way. It still works that way, you know,

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:39.800
[Guest]: in my in my 40s, you know, after all these years of doing this, the one is constantly

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:44.240
[Guest]: being surprised by something, you know, and of course, it happens. And I know this happens

00:18:44.240 --> 00:18:49.320
[Guest]: with other writers as well, that very often, I'll, you know, sit down to write about a

00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:55.480
[Guest]: film with with only a very basic idea about, you know, of what I'm going to be writing

00:18:55.480 --> 00:19:00.480
[Guest]: and a basic sense of what I thought of the film, the two or three points that I'd like

00:19:00.480 --> 00:19:05.480
[Guest]: to make about it. And then in the process of, of writing about it, when you're sort

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:11.000
[Guest]: of really getting into it deep at a paragraph by paragraph level, you find yourself articulating

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:15.280
[Guest]: thoughts in the process of writing, and making these little connections that you mentioned

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:20.040
[Guest]: in the process of doing that. It's not the case that that everything is cleanly flowcharted

00:19:20.040 --> 00:19:24.480
[Guest]: out beforehand. Sometimes that can happen also, I suspect that can happen when you're

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:27.960
[Guest]: working on a very tight deadline, and you're writing something, you know, for a limited

00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:33.080
[Guest]: word count 600 700 words, you know, you can even while traveling by car or something,

00:19:33.080 --> 00:19:37.280
[Guest]: and you can be making basic structural notes on your cell phone, and then typing the whole

00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:41.880
[Guest]: thing out on the on the computer later. But that is a relatively low investment sort of

00:19:41.880 --> 00:19:46.240
[Guest]: review that I'm talking about. And I'm talking about the really, the fairly long form analytical

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:52.320
[Guest]: essay. That's something it happens routinely with me that I articulate my thoughts about

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:56.880
[Guest]: the film and about perhaps my own response to the film and what that says about my mind,

00:19:56.880 --> 00:20:01.720
[Guest]: or my, you know, personal experiences, or whatever my life experiences, my feelings

00:20:01.720 --> 00:20:06.160
[Guest]: about different things. I articulate a lot of those things to myself in the process of

00:20:06.160 --> 00:20:11.360
[Guest]: writing. Now, one thing I just like to touch on something that you mentioned just now about

00:20:11.360 --> 00:20:16.280
[Guest]: the sort of film nerd, the sort of film buff who engages deeply with the film, but doesn't

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:21.360
[Guest]: really feel the need to write about it or to put one's thoughts down or to put his or

00:20:21.360 --> 00:20:27.480
[Guest]: her thoughts down on paper, or to have it published somewhere. I have to say, I very

00:20:27.480 --> 00:20:32.840
[Guest]: often have a deep envy for that sort of movie buff. I have many friends who are like that

00:20:32.840 --> 00:20:39.040
[Guest]: friends who are quite possibly bigger movie nerds than I am more capable of being articulate

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:45.040
[Guest]: about a film in conversation than I would be, but who have absolutely no impulse to

00:20:45.040 --> 00:20:49.560
[Guest]: write about it, or to sit down and agonize over it in that sense. And I think that's

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:52.520
[Guest]: that's such a wonderful thing. Because you know, I'm always surprising people when I

00:20:52.520 --> 00:20:58.720
[Guest]: tell them this, I don't watch anywhere near as many films as people as as people might

00:20:58.720 --> 00:21:04.920
[Guest]: think I do. And one reason for that is that every time I watch a film, that stimulates

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:09.120
[Guest]: me in some way, it could be a positive way, it could be a negative way, I need to take

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:13.680
[Guest]: a lot of time out to sit down and, and write something about it, even if I even if it's

00:21:13.680 --> 00:21:18.520
[Guest]: being written just for myself, even if it's some scattered fragmented notes, which which

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:23.680
[Guest]: I may or may not use months later in a column, even if it's not a piece that's being immediately

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:28.480
[Guest]: written, I need to sit down and write about it then. And that actually eats into the time

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:34.000
[Guest]: that I might have to watch another film very soon after this. So so it's, it's very, very

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:38.640
[Guest]: rare for me today, for instance, that, that I've watched more than one film in a day,

00:21:38.640 --> 00:21:42.120
[Guest]: that almost never happened. And I have so many friends who you know, will will go to

00:21:42.120 --> 00:21:47.320
[Guest]: film festivals in the pre COVID world, you know, going to film festivals and watching

00:21:47.320 --> 00:21:51.680
[Guest]: four or five films over the course of a day. And that's something that I've never really

00:21:51.680 --> 00:21:56.960
[Guest]: done. Yeah, even at the age of 2021. And I was so enthusiastic about festivals or whatever

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:04.360
[Guest]: it was, it's, I've never really had the mental energy to watch a number of films in a day.

00:22:04.360 --> 00:22:10.240
[Guest]: Because normally just watching one takes up so much of my mental space and I need to sit

00:22:10.240 --> 00:22:16.400
[Guest]: down and think about it, assimilate it, process what I've experienced. I don't know if I what

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:20.160
[Guest]: are the other question you asked? I think I've just gone off on a tangent.

00:22:20.160 --> 00:22:24.480
[Amit Varma]: It was essentially about this about, you know, whether this imperative of having to write

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:28.400
[Amit Varma]: about a film, you know, improves your thinking about the film. And therefore, does that change

00:22:28.400 --> 00:22:31.920
[Amit Varma]: you as a person like, but the drift I seem to be getting from your answer is that you

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:36.240
[Amit Varma]: are that kind of person anyway, who takes time to process things. So you would probably

00:22:36.240 --> 00:22:39.920
[Amit Varma]: or is it a feedback loop where they kind of feed into each other?

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:46.600
[Guest]: No, no, absolutely. But also to perhaps more directly answer what you just asked. Of course,

00:22:46.600 --> 00:22:51.200
[Guest]: it works that way. You know, I can think of numerous cases where a lot of films that I've

00:22:51.200 --> 00:22:57.120
[Guest]: written about over the years, not coincidentally, I think have been films that touch on various

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:02.440
[Guest]: aspects of the parent child relationship. And I feel that there's a lot of writing that

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:07.520
[Guest]: I need to do in the future as well, perhaps not film related writing, just just general

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:13.640
[Guest]: personal essay writing about my parents, both of whom are now gone and I had very different

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:19.520
[Guest]: relationships with each of them. I've often found that, that I sit down to write about

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:25.400
[Guest]: a film without thinking of it as, without thinking that it's going to turn into a personal

00:23:25.400 --> 00:23:29.640
[Guest]: essay at all. And then in the process of writing about it, and of course, I am writing about

00:23:29.640 --> 00:23:34.000
[Guest]: the film as well and about what's going on in the film, the quality of the acting or

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:37.720
[Guest]: the directing or the music or whatever it is, all that is there as well. But in the

00:23:37.720 --> 00:23:43.800
[Guest]: process of writing about it, I realize that possibly one reason why this film meant so

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:50.800
[Guest]: much to me or stimulated me to, to thought or to the action of writing is because there's

00:23:50.800 --> 00:23:57.240
[Guest]: something in it that ties in with my experience with my parents. And then suddenly, you know,

00:23:57.240 --> 00:24:01.960
[Guest]: if one is writing an essay length piece or writing the sort of commission piece for someone

00:24:01.960 --> 00:24:06.000
[Guest]: where you have a certain amount of leeway to do personal writing as well, I'll find

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:11.240
[Guest]: myself writing four or five paragraphs of personal reminiscence about involving my mother

00:24:11.240 --> 00:24:17.160
[Guest]: or my father and tying that in with, with how this particular film affected me. So,

00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:21.800
[Guest]: so that happens a great deal as well. And of course, then then the writing and the film

00:24:21.800 --> 00:24:28.480
[Guest]: analysis also becomes a conduit for perhaps understanding or articulating something about

00:24:28.480 --> 00:24:32.080
[Guest]: oneself about one's personal life.

00:24:32.080 --> 00:24:34.880
[Amit Varma]: And one of your books, you've, you know, mentioned that Pauline Kael was once asked

00:24:34.880 --> 00:24:39.000
[Amit Varma]: about why she'd never written an autobiography. And she pointed to her anthologies of reviews

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:43.960
[Amit Varma]: and film essays and said, I think I have. And that kind of brings me to my next question,

00:24:43.960 --> 00:24:49.560
[Amit Varma]: because it strikes me that people think that a review is, or must be or should be in some

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:54.720
[Amit Varma]: way, some kind of objective thing, right. And you've also spoken at length about how

00:24:54.720 --> 00:24:59.760
[Amit Varma]: the earlier form of the review when newspapers in the 90s and 2000s would give like 600 words,

00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:04.480
[Amit Varma]: 500 words, and what people came to expect would be just verdicts delivered on the movie

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:09.280
[Amit Varma]: that acting is good. Cinematography is good, so many stars. In fact, I used to have those

00:25:09.280 --> 00:25:13.920
[Amit Varma]: Leonard Maltin guides as well. And it is only in retrospect after many years that I've realized

00:25:13.920 --> 00:25:18.720
[Amit Varma]: that to me, that's kind of the wrong way to think about films as if there is a hierarchy

00:25:18.720 --> 00:25:23.280
[Amit Varma]: of merit, so to say, when different films can appeal to people for so many different

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:27.880
[Amit Varma]: reasons. Now, whether I'm reading about books or cinema, or even when I write about those,

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:33.560
[Amit Varma]: what I have realized is that when I'm reading something, what I value is always something

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:38.080
[Amit Varma]: that is in the realm of the subjective. In fact, what I value is always something that

00:25:38.080 --> 00:25:43.280
[Amit Varma]: is coming from the author's personal life and experience and whatever, because that

00:25:43.280 --> 00:25:47.680
[Amit Varma]: is the only thing that can make anything worth reading. Anybody can say Starrcast was good

00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:52.080
[Amit Varma]: and cinematography was this and it's so many minutes long and this is a plot and spend

00:25:52.080 --> 00:25:56.560
[Amit Varma]: 300 words giving the plot. Anybody can do that. What makes an essay on a film or a review

00:25:56.560 --> 00:26:01.480
[Amit Varma]: or whatever stand out will necessarily, in a sense, be autobiography, not autobiography

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:05.400
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that there is a book about parents and you relate to that because you're thinking

00:26:05.400 --> 00:26:11.080
[Amit Varma]: of your parents, not in that kind of direct sense. But there is some emotional resonance

00:26:11.080 --> 00:26:15.240
[Amit Varma]: like in another piece of yours, you mentioned this beautiful phrase by Suni Tarapurwala

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:20.240
[Amit Varma]: where she talks about the spiritual DNA of a film, you know, which I would say could

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:24.240
[Amit Varma]: be the essence of a film. I think this was you were part of a panel on the translation

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:28.840
[Amit Varma]: of books into films. And you were kind of talking about transferring this essence from

00:26:28.840 --> 00:26:33.880
[Amit Varma]: one to the other. So and this is something that I feel is true that everything I write

00:26:33.880 --> 00:26:38.160
[Amit Varma]: about anything and this is of course not true perhaps of my political op-eds or whatever,

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:42.100
[Amit Varma]: but more and more whatever I do, including this podcast, which is kind of my journey

00:26:42.100 --> 00:26:46.040
[Amit Varma]: and the stuff I'm thinking about and the stuff I'm interested in, more and more the things

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:50.320
[Amit Varma]: I find value in and the things I want to do are those things that are imbued with the

00:26:50.320 --> 00:26:54.680
[Amit Varma]: personal. What's your thinking about this? And initially, when you start thinking along

00:26:54.680 --> 00:26:59.360
[Amit Varma]: these lines, is there something holding you back? Is there like a sense of guilt that

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:04.480
[Amit Varma]: there should be no I in this, that there is something objective about everything and you

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:09.440
[Amit Varma]: have to get that across? And because especially as a news reporter, that is of course true,

00:27:09.440 --> 00:27:13.080
[Amit Varma]: that you're just reporting facts and trying to get to the truth, but that's kind of what

00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:18.880
[Amit Varma]: it is. But you know, is that something that you begin thinking about that you begin resisting

00:27:18.880 --> 00:27:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that should I put so much of myself into this? And at what stage do you begin to realize

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:27.800
[Amit Varma]: that this is a dope, this is what I want to do, and so on?

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:31.720
[Guest]: Now almost needless to say, I agree with pretty much everything you said there about the importance

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:38.120
[Guest]: of subjectivity and the interestingness of subjectivity. To answer the last thing you

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:45.080
[Guest]: asked just now, I can say with some pride that I've never felt guilty about the possibility

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:50.120
[Guest]: of putting an I into my writing. What I have felt early in my career, you know, I mean,

00:27:50.120 --> 00:27:55.040
[Guest]: when I was 20, 21, 22 years old, you know, as a journalist, obviously subject to a much

00:27:55.040 --> 00:28:00.480
[Guest]: greater degree to the hegemony of one's bosses, and the things that they expected you to do.

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:06.480
[Guest]: At that point, of course, you did run into the sort of senior editor who would frown

00:28:06.480 --> 00:28:13.040
[Guest]: on the use of an I in a review. And that's something you still have, even today in 2021,

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:16.040
[Guest]: you know, in some mainstream publications, you know, including a couple that I write

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:21.160
[Guest]: for right now, where you will get told by the person who's commissioned the piece, listen,

00:28:21.160 --> 00:28:25.320
[Guest]: so on. So this guy at the top, he's a bit conservative in his thinking, you know, he

00:28:25.320 --> 00:28:30.080
[Guest]: doesn't like the first person. So you know, so you make those little adjustments, if you

00:28:30.080 --> 00:28:33.520
[Guest]: if you feel that that is still worth your time, and you know, the money is worth it,

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:38.760
[Guest]: or whatever it is. And here I'm talking about the very short form sort of review that that

00:28:38.760 --> 00:28:43.720
[Guest]: does not involve a lot of personal investment for me. So I'm okay with with doing an objective

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:48.040
[Guest]: seeming review, structurally objective seeming, though it is, of course, still completely

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:52.240
[Guest]: subjective. And I'm okay with doing that for a certain sort of publication. But generally

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:56.400
[Guest]: speaking, the throughout my writing life, my professional writing life, including those

00:28:56.400 --> 00:29:01.960
[Guest]: earliest years, but the sort of writing I was most interested in was the navel gazing,

00:29:01.960 --> 00:29:07.040
[Guest]: you know, and I'm saying that in a deliberately self deprecating sort of way, there's a sort

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:11.840
[Guest]: of writing that gets described as navel gazing by a lot of people. I just took it as a given

00:29:11.840 --> 00:29:18.560
[Guest]: that anything I write with seriousness of purpose, and with integrity is going to be

00:29:18.560 --> 00:29:22.960
[Guest]: as much about me and the way my mind works as it's going to be about the thing that's

00:29:22.960 --> 00:29:27.400
[Guest]: being written about. I just took that as a given. And I didn't even see that as an arrogant

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:32.640
[Guest]: position. I somewhat similar to what you said that, you know, to me, it was self evident

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:38.440
[Guest]: as a reader as well that, that I would be most interested in review or the sort of work

00:29:38.440 --> 00:29:44.960
[Guest]: of criticism or the sort of essay that provided a glimpse into how a particular sort of mind

00:29:44.960 --> 00:29:48.680
[Guest]: received a particular sort of film or book or whatever it was, that's the sort of film

00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:54.000
[Guest]: writing that I had been very interested in. When I first seriously got into film literature

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:57.760
[Guest]: in my adolescence, around the time that I started watching old Hollywood films, I also

00:29:57.760 --> 00:30:02.760
[Guest]: started seeking out a lot of film literature by people like Pauline Kyle, who was one of

00:30:02.760 --> 00:30:08.120
[Guest]: the obvious suspects, but also a few other writers who had done books on Hitchcock, on

00:30:08.120 --> 00:30:12.840
[Guest]: Howard Hawks, and a few others. And I always found that writing, that sort of personal

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:19.080
[Guest]: writing, very interesting, very stimulating. Now, when I did that Rishikesh Mukherjee book

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:24.160
[Guest]: that I mentioned, I was clear from the start that the book would be as, however arrogant

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:29.040
[Guest]: this sounds to some people, that the book would be as much about my mind as it would

00:30:29.040 --> 00:30:32.960
[Guest]: be about Rishikesh Mukherjee's films. And I really did not mean that in an arrogant

00:30:32.960 --> 00:30:37.840
[Guest]: way at all. And I meant that as a compliment to Rishikesh Mukherjee's films for stimulating

00:30:37.840 --> 00:30:42.560
[Guest]: my mind in a certain way. But of course, what happens then is that, that when you've written

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:48.560
[Guest]: a book like that, and the book has, you know, the publisher has marketed it, you know, to

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:52.840
[Guest]: make it seem like it might be a little more biographical than it is, a little more anecdote

00:30:52.840 --> 00:30:56.800
[Guest]: driven than it is. And then of course, people start reading the book, people pick it up

00:30:56.800 --> 00:31:01.160
[Guest]: on Amazon, and instead they start writing online reviews of the book. I actually have

00:31:01.160 --> 00:31:05.840
[Guest]: a number of one star reviews of that book on Amazon, which say things like, this book

00:31:05.840 --> 00:31:13.240
[Guest]: is not about Rishi, Rishida, this book is about J R Junsing. And an objective book about

00:31:13.240 --> 00:31:18.400
[Guest]: Rishikesh Mukherjee's films would have recognized the brilliance of Anand, but this book

00:31:18.400 --> 00:31:23.640
[Guest]: hardly says anything about Anand. So that sort of thing. And I took that sort of thing

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:28.000
[Guest]: as a big compliment in a way, even though of course, it hurts to have one star reviews

00:31:28.000 --> 00:31:33.840
[Guest]: on online forums. Because really, to my mind, and again, coming back to what you touched

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:41.000
[Guest]: on earlier, at a time when the internet is full of hundreds, maybe 1000s of blog posts

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:46.680
[Guest]: about a high profile film like Anand or Golmaal, a lot of which are basically just saying the

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:51.360
[Guest]: same thing over and over again, providing a plot synopsis, and saying something very,

00:31:51.360 --> 00:31:56.920
[Guest]: you know, very trite, in my view, like, Anand is a film, is an inspirational film about

00:31:56.920 --> 00:32:02.280
[Guest]: a man who teaches everybody that, that death can be conquered, something really obvious

00:32:02.280 --> 00:32:06.760
[Guest]: like that. And once it's been said 1000 times all over the internet, I feel like if I'm

00:32:06.760 --> 00:32:11.240
[Guest]: doing a book about Rishikesh Mukherjee's films, I want to say something about the Anand that

00:32:11.240 --> 00:32:16.560
[Guest]: I experienced, and maybe bring something new to the table that has not been said before.

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:20.560
[Guest]: And if I can do that, honestly, I mean, it shouldn't be a contrived thing, of course,

00:32:20.560 --> 00:32:24.560
[Guest]: it should, it should come honestly, from from my engagement with the film, then that's what

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:29.680
[Guest]: I want to do. I don't want to just write something that you can easily find on Wikipedia anyway.

00:32:29.680 --> 00:32:33.200
[Guest]: So so yeah, so agree with pretty much everything you said.

00:32:33.200 --> 00:32:38.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And also, it strikes me that number one, that whole expectation that there can

00:32:38.200 --> 00:32:42.960
[Amit Varma]: even be an objective book about Rishi Das films, for example, is completely untrue.

00:32:42.960 --> 00:32:47.800
[Amit Varma]: There is no like universal truth to them that is there to capture everybody views it differently.

00:32:47.800 --> 00:32:52.720
[Amit Varma]: Even Rishi Das would have viewed it differently and not gotten that. And I think that, and

00:32:52.720 --> 00:32:56.080
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you that though I can tell it hurts, I can tell the one star reviews hurts.

00:32:56.080 --> 00:32:57.080
[Guest]: Oh, you're...

00:32:57.080 --> 00:33:01.040
[Guest]: If I can just interrupt for a second, what you said there is absolutely true. Because

00:33:01.040 --> 00:33:05.920
[Guest]: you know, if you were to read Rishikesh Mukherjee's interviews over a period of 30-40 years, he

00:33:05.920 --> 00:33:10.520
[Guest]: is contradicting himself all the time, even about his own films, you know, then, you know,

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:14.720
[Guest]: one of the things I found fascinating was the sense of a very conflicted man working

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:19.360
[Guest]: in a mainstream film industry where a certain degree of compromise was required.

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:25.720
[Guest]: You knew what, you know, how mainstream Hindi films tended to be made in the 60s, 70s, without

00:33:25.720 --> 00:33:30.000
[Guest]: bound scripts, often, you know, with with producers dictating things, the star system

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:31.000
[Guest]: dictating things.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.760
[Guest]: In the midst of all that, if you have a director with a certain sensibility of his own having

00:33:35.760 --> 00:33:40.840
[Guest]: to make compromises every now and again, or do things on the fly, of course, there's going

00:33:40.840 --> 00:33:43.720
[Guest]: to be a lot of self-beratement happening.

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:46.960
[Guest]: At the same time, there's going to be defensiveness once in a while, if he gets criticized by

00:33:46.960 --> 00:33:49.480
[Guest]: someone else, he'll stand up for himself.

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:53.920
[Guest]: So if you read his interviews, in one interview, he'll say one thing about Golmaal.

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:57.080
[Guest]: In another interview, he'll say something that sounds very different about it.

00:33:57.080 --> 00:34:02.960
[Guest]: So you know, so the subjectivity as you suggested just now comes in even with the creative person.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:07.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's appropriate that you know, one should have conflicting views on a film

00:34:07.080 --> 00:34:08.640
[Amit Varma]: with a title like Golmaal.

00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:11.680
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that that's not necessarily just true of him.

00:34:11.680 --> 00:34:15.920
[Amit Varma]: It's true, I think of every creator in the sense that you are driven to do certain things,

00:34:15.920 --> 00:34:20.020
[Amit Varma]: you may not yourself know where those impulses come from, and why you're driven to do them.

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:25.560
[Amit Varma]: You tell a story to yourself about them, that story can change as your self image changes,

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:30.120
[Amit Varma]: or as your desire to project a certain image of yourself to the outside world changes.

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:35.000
[Amit Varma]: So it's a sort of constant mishmash of changing narratives inside your own head.

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.800
[Amit Varma]: And I would still say that, you know, then a naysayer would say that, okay, if Jai Arjun

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:44.900
[Amit Varma]: is talking about Rishi Das films from his point of view, or if Amit is pursuing his

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:48.160
[Amit Varma]: intellectual journey in his podcast, why should the rest of us be interested, right?

00:34:48.160 --> 00:34:50.980
[Amit Varma]: It's just personal, you enjoy it, let your friends listen.

00:34:50.980 --> 00:34:53.480
[Amit Varma]: But I think that's just the wrong way around.

00:34:53.480 --> 00:34:56.640
[Amit Varma]: Because I think what then someone like you is doing is if you're exploring a certain

00:34:56.640 --> 00:35:01.260
[Amit Varma]: avenue, and you know what those films meant to you, I think a lot of people are trying

00:35:01.260 --> 00:35:05.720
[Amit Varma]: to figure stuff out, like when I try to figure stuff out through the show, a lot of people

00:35:05.720 --> 00:35:08.900
[Amit Varma]: are on similar journeys where they're trying to figure stuff out.

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:11.680
[Amit Varma]: And your journey is relevant to everybody.

00:35:11.680 --> 00:35:16.400
[Amit Varma]: For that reason, as long as you do it honestly, and you do it in an authentic way, and you're

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:20.860
[Amit Varma]: not just being performative, I think it's of tremendous value.

00:35:20.860 --> 00:35:24.740
[Amit Varma]: For that reason, by the way, I got to tell you that I am one of these people you just

00:35:24.740 --> 00:35:28.720
[Amit Varma]: derogatory said they watch four or five films a day during film festivals.

00:35:28.720 --> 00:35:32.980
[Amit Varma]: You know, and for the last few years while Mami was on, that was pretty much my routine

00:35:32.980 --> 00:35:38.500
[Amit Varma]: during Mami where I'd watch some 28, 29 films in the week that it was on and I would also

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:42.620
[Amit Varma]: kind of live tweet about it almost like not during the film, but after every film, I'd,

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:46.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, have a little bit and I found that it helped because putting a tweet about something

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:50.340
[Amit Varma]: compressing it in so many characters would just force me to think a little deeper about

00:35:50.340 --> 00:35:52.280
[Amit Varma]: why I liked it and why I didn't like it.

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:55.900
[Amit Varma]: I think that kind of sharpens your thinking like going back to what you said earlier,

00:35:55.900 --> 00:35:59.380
[Amit Varma]: like in my writing course, I'll often quote Joan Didion, who once said that, I don't know

00:35:59.380 --> 00:36:01.440
[Amit Varma]: what I think until I write it down.

00:36:01.440 --> 00:36:05.580
[Amit Varma]: So the process of writing is not just a way of Oh, I'm thinking something I got to put

00:36:05.580 --> 00:36:06.660
[Amit Varma]: that on paper.

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:09.140
[Amit Varma]: The process of writing can shape your thinking.

00:36:09.140 --> 00:36:12.020
[Amit Varma]: And in that sense, kind of shape the person you are.

00:36:12.020 --> 00:36:14.400
[Amit Varma]: Let's, let's go back to biography now.

00:36:14.400 --> 00:36:17.060
[Amit Varma]: As you can see, I'm treating you the way you treated Rishida.

00:36:17.060 --> 00:36:25.540
[Guest]: I just wanted to, I wanted to quickly add to that, that Joan Didion quote, Roger Ebert

00:36:25.540 --> 00:36:28.980
[Guest]: had had something along those lines, I don't remember the exact thing, but it was something

00:36:28.980 --> 00:36:35.020
[Guest]: like, like, you know, advice to writers that the muse doesn't come, you know, before you

00:36:35.020 --> 00:36:41.060
[Guest]: start writing, the muse comes while you're writing, when you sit down to write.

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:42.900
[Amit Varma]: Which is why discipline and process is so important.

00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:46.740
[Amit Varma]: Like one of my four webinars in my writing course is just about process, which people

00:36:46.740 --> 00:36:50.660
[Amit Varma]: kind of ignore, people think if you understand the craft, you have an intellectual understanding

00:36:50.660 --> 00:36:54.340
[Amit Varma]: of what a good sentence is, you are covered, no, you're not covered, you still had to get

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:57.300
[Amit Varma]: your ass down and actually write the damn thing.

00:36:57.300 --> 00:37:01.420
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, one thing I was kind of struck by, and I haven't thought about it in these

00:37:01.420 --> 00:37:05.220
[Amit Varma]: terms before, though, you know, the thing about people containing multitudes is actually

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:06.220
[Amit Varma]: a cliche on my show.

00:37:06.220 --> 00:37:10.500
[Amit Varma]: So it's a cliche I'm kind of guilty of, it's so true, but the context in which I'd never

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:14.180
[Amit Varma]: thought of it is how you mentioned that people like us people like you and me, the English

00:37:14.180 --> 00:37:18.400
[Amit Varma]: speaking elite, so to say, in 1980s India, would be reading one kind of thing, but watching

00:37:18.400 --> 00:37:21.940
[Amit Varma]: entirely another kind of thing, though, there also, I was a child of privilege, because

00:37:21.940 --> 00:37:24.860
[Amit Varma]: my dad was a director of the FDII from the mid 80s.

00:37:24.860 --> 00:37:29.460
[Amit Varma]: So I got to watch a lot of world cinema as a matter of course, but in general, there

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:33.820
[Amit Varma]: is this classic disconnect where it's almost like we are one person when we read an English

00:37:33.820 --> 00:37:37.220
[Amit Varma]: book, we are another person when we watch a Hindi film.

00:37:37.220 --> 00:37:43.960
[Amit Varma]: And my question to you is about, when does that sort of shift happen, where initially

00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:47.980
[Amit Varma]: you are reading everything, and you're watching everything, and it's entertainment, and you're

00:37:47.980 --> 00:37:50.500
[Amit Varma]: just enjoying it and all of that.

00:37:50.500 --> 00:37:54.500
[Amit Varma]: But at some sense, there is a shift where, you know, some switch goes off.

00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:57.580
[Amit Varma]: And you're like, you know, you get it, you get art, you get literature, whatever.

00:37:57.580 --> 00:38:02.040
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I know that sounds kind of pompous, but you get it, you get that there's something

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:05.580
[Amit Varma]: else, there's something deeper, like in my case, like I sometimes say it happened when

00:38:05.580 --> 00:38:09.380
[Amit Varma]: I happened to pick up Dostoyevsky's House of the Dead, when I was a 10.

00:38:09.380 --> 00:38:12.220
[Amit Varma]: And I thought it'd be a thriller, zombie horror, whatever.

00:38:12.220 --> 00:38:14.100
[Amit Varma]: And suddenly, you know, my mind is blown.

00:38:14.100 --> 00:38:16.660
[Amit Varma]: And then it's my gateway into that kind of thing.

00:38:16.660 --> 00:38:21.180
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in your essay about horror films, and the great book you edited, Popcorn Essays,

00:38:21.180 --> 00:38:25.580
[Amit Varma]: you wrote about how, for you, that might have been psycho, where you're watching a whole

00:38:25.580 --> 00:38:29.340
[Amit Varma]: bunch of horror films before that, and you're, you know, getting into the genre and really

00:38:29.340 --> 00:38:30.420
[Amit Varma]: loving it.

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:33.900
[Amit Varma]: But it's psycho, which is something else, and you're not scared while watching it, but

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:36.780
[Amit Varma]: other parts of you kind of get activated.

00:38:36.780 --> 00:38:39.280
[Amit Varma]: Is that shift something that you've thought about?

00:38:39.280 --> 00:38:40.280
[Amit Varma]: Is it a gradual thing?

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:41.420
[Amit Varma]: Or is it a one day thing?

00:38:41.420 --> 00:38:47.620
[Amit Varma]: Is there a sort of an exhilaration and a hunger that goes with it that, you know, you discover

00:38:47.620 --> 00:38:48.900
[Amit Varma]: this whole new world?

00:38:48.900 --> 00:38:49.900
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that.

00:38:49.900 --> 00:38:55.420
[Amit Varma]: And tell me a bit about this transition then, from someone who is loving films, to someone

00:38:55.420 --> 00:38:59.340
[Amit Varma]: who begins to appreciate it in deeper ways?

00:38:59.340 --> 00:39:02.300
[Guest]: You know, this is a very difficult question.

00:39:02.300 --> 00:39:06.660
[Guest]: I can tell you, it definitely wasn't a sudden shift.

00:39:06.660 --> 00:39:11.700
[Guest]: If it was a shift, it was a very gradual one, and it's still going on in my 40s.

00:39:11.700 --> 00:39:16.260
[Guest]: I feel like, you know, if I were to spend the next 50 years, you know, writing and thinking

00:39:16.260 --> 00:39:22.420
[Guest]: about films, at the end of my life, I would still feel like I was, you know, just a student

00:39:22.420 --> 00:39:28.020
[Guest]: in the first grade or something, and hadn't engaged the fraction of everything I could

00:39:28.020 --> 00:39:29.460
[Guest]: engage with.

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:34.460
[Guest]: The psycho thing, you know, just to provide context for those who don't know, I'm actually

00:39:34.460 --> 00:39:39.820
[Guest]: in the process of writing a lot of these little personal essays that I'm currently doing just

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:44.500
[Guest]: for myself, or putting versions of them up on the blog or on Facebook.

00:39:44.500 --> 00:39:50.900
[Guest]: Because this year marks 30 years of, you know, from the summer of 1991, which is a very major

00:39:50.900 --> 00:39:53.340
[Guest]: period in my film watching life.

00:39:53.340 --> 00:39:57.700
[Guest]: And probably the period that's closest to the sort of shift that you're talking about.

00:39:57.700 --> 00:40:03.020
[Guest]: Even though I'm personally reluctant to speak in the language of shifts, as if it's some

00:40:03.020 --> 00:40:08.780
[Guest]: sort of, you know, life altering thing, because I continue to maintain that my arc as a film

00:40:08.780 --> 00:40:13.580
[Guest]: watcher has been a very weird one, it's not like it's not something as simple as, okay,

00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:18.220
[Guest]: I was I was watching only masala Hindi films up to the late 80s or the early 90s.

00:40:18.220 --> 00:40:23.860
[Guest]: And then there's a sudden turn into watching old Hollywood and from there getting into

00:40:23.860 --> 00:40:24.860
[Guest]: world cinema.

00:40:24.860 --> 00:40:29.540
[Guest]: A lot of this is also facilitated by the fact that that satellite TV came to us in the early

00:40:29.540 --> 00:40:30.540
[Guest]: 90s.

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:34.260
[Guest]: And, you know, in the mid 90s, star movies had this thing called 100 years of cinema

00:40:34.260 --> 00:40:39.100
[Guest]: where they showed all sorts of things for months on end, there were the embassy video

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:40.100
[Guest]: libraries, etc, etc.

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:42.740
[Guest]: So it's why I had access to a lot of stuff.

00:40:42.740 --> 00:40:46.300
[Guest]: Things changed for me for around 10-12 years, I was completely out of the world of Hindi

00:40:46.300 --> 00:40:47.300
[Guest]: cinema.

00:40:47.300 --> 00:40:53.460
[Guest]: I think I just been so sated by that particular sort of filmic language, that over the top

00:40:53.460 --> 00:40:55.940
[Guest]: hyper dramatic language.

00:40:55.940 --> 00:41:01.700
[Guest]: And because as a personality type, I was very reserved, very emotionally undemonstrative,

00:41:01.700 --> 00:41:08.060
[Guest]: it perhaps also in some small ways became a rebellion against hyper drama, against larger

00:41:08.060 --> 00:41:09.940
[Guest]: than life things.

00:41:09.940 --> 00:41:14.780
[Guest]: And for several years that I got into what, you know, I developed a taste that was almost

00:41:14.780 --> 00:41:21.060
[Guest]: exclusively for the more restrained forms, you know, whether it was old Hollywood, which

00:41:21.060 --> 00:41:26.340
[Guest]: is a little more subdued than mainstream Hindi cinema, or world cinema by people like Bergman

00:41:26.340 --> 00:41:27.340
[Guest]: or whoever.

00:41:27.340 --> 00:41:33.820
[Guest]: But having said all that, then in my 20s, I then returned to the fold of Hindi cinema

00:41:33.820 --> 00:41:38.780
[Guest]: and found myself appreciating a lot of these larger than life hyper dramatic films, you

00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:45.340
[Guest]: know, through new lenses, and finding a lot of emotional resonance in them all over again.

00:41:45.340 --> 00:41:50.660
[Guest]: And today, you know, if there's something that I, that I value in myself as a film watcher

00:41:50.660 --> 00:41:56.980
[Guest]: or as a film writer, it would just be this that, you know, without any conscious effort

00:41:56.980 --> 00:42:02.780
[Guest]: on my part, or some, you know, some deliberate attempt to be a viewer who watches many different

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:08.900
[Guest]: sorts of things, I just developed a sort of egalitarianism as a film watcher, and open

00:42:08.900 --> 00:42:14.980
[Guest]: mindedness to all sorts of forms, all sorts of genres, you know, from the, from the really

00:42:14.980 --> 00:42:21.740
[Guest]: restrained, you know, the mode of kitchen sink realism, to the larger than life, you

00:42:21.740 --> 00:42:25.580
[Guest]: know, language of filmmakers, like, like one of your favorites, Anjali La Bhansali.

00:42:25.580 --> 00:42:32.380
[Amit Varma]: I got to point out to the viewers right here that Jai is being ironic because Bhansali

00:42:32.380 --> 00:42:35.980
[Amit Varma]: is exactly the kind of film cinema I don't like.

00:42:35.980 --> 00:42:42.100
[Guest]: Yeah, well, anybody who's heard your previous podcast already knows that, I suspect.

00:42:42.100 --> 00:42:49.460
[Guest]: But, but yeah, so I'm always willing to say that I am resistant in many ways to, to suggesting

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:54.180
[Guest]: that there is a clear cut evolution as a film watcher.

00:42:54.180 --> 00:42:58.420
[Guest]: Because also what happens, Amit, I feel is that there's two of, you know, whether one

00:42:58.420 --> 00:43:02.100
[Guest]: is talking of cinema or literature, maybe it's just the circles that I move in, you

00:43:02.100 --> 00:43:06.860
[Guest]: know, the sorts of people that I interact with most these days, but I feel like many

00:43:06.860 --> 00:43:14.780
[Guest]: people just view that evolution in terms of, you know, moving from, from the, the escapist

00:43:14.780 --> 00:43:21.100
[Guest]: things you loved as a child, to the more somber things that, that are that are befitting for

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:25.020
[Guest]: you as an adult viewer, when you start, you know, you become more interested in things

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:31.180
[Guest]: like realism or, or whatever, or an understatement or, or authentic pictures of the world around

00:43:31.180 --> 00:43:32.180
[Guest]: you.

00:43:32.180 --> 00:43:34.260
[Guest]: And I don't really feel like I've had that journey.

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:38.620
[Guest]: I think my journey has been much more back and forth like that I today I can, you know,

00:43:38.620 --> 00:43:42.700
[Guest]: depending on sort of mood I'm in when I when I wake up in the morning, or the sort of sort

00:43:42.700 --> 00:43:49.340
[Guest]: of mood I'm in during the middle of the day, I can just as easily watch a gritty, understated,

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:58.540
[Guest]: completely realistic film, as I can watch an over the top, loud, slapsticky, or melodramatic

00:43:58.540 --> 00:44:02.860
[Guest]: film and enjoy it and find some level of stimulation from that.

00:44:02.860 --> 00:44:07.220
[Guest]: But to also come back to the question of shifts.

00:44:07.220 --> 00:44:12.220
[Guest]: What happened with Psycho really was that it became a turning point for me, because

00:44:12.220 --> 00:44:17.740
[Guest]: I watched it, I found it a bit creepy, of course, in some ways.

00:44:17.740 --> 00:44:24.780
[Guest]: But again, I just found this tremendous sadness in it as a film, and I related to it in ways

00:44:24.780 --> 00:44:29.380
[Guest]: that I perhaps would not have been able to articulate back then as a 13 or 14 year old,

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:37.100
[Guest]: but which I found myself making sense of subsequently, you know, as a young boy who was living with

00:44:37.100 --> 00:44:42.860
[Guest]: a single mother with a with a recently divorced mother, having, you know, escaped a house

00:44:42.860 --> 00:44:48.780
[Guest]: that had had unpleasantness and violence in it, and now dealing with the new challenges

00:44:48.780 --> 00:44:55.140
[Guest]: that came with living as you know, as part of this somewhat unconventional family unit

00:44:55.140 --> 00:45:02.180
[Guest]: with my mother and her mother, my nani, who did so much for us, but was also an extremely

00:45:02.180 --> 00:45:08.620
[Guest]: boisterous and extroverted person, the sort of person that I was wary of as a child, as

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:11.020
[Guest]: a very shy, introverted child.

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:15.900
[Guest]: So there are all these conflicts going on for an adolescent, for a 13-14 year old.

00:45:15.900 --> 00:45:20.460
[Guest]: And I found that watching Psycho with its reflections, especially in this beautiful

00:45:20.460 --> 00:45:25.540
[Guest]: scene in the middle of the film, where the Norman Bates character and the Marion Crane

00:45:25.540 --> 00:45:29.380
[Guest]: character played by Janet Leigh, they sit and just talk in the parlor.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:35.140
[Guest]: And for those 10 minutes or so, the film is like, it's like a Bergman film, or a chamber

00:45:35.140 --> 00:45:36.140
[Guest]: drama or something.

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:41.180
[Guest]: And they're talking about loneliness, about things like that, and what it means to love

00:45:41.180 --> 00:45:45.380
[Guest]: someone and to hate that person at the same time, or to feel like you're in your own private

00:45:45.380 --> 00:45:47.660
[Guest]: trap versus being free.

00:45:47.660 --> 00:45:52.100
[Guest]: And I just found a lot of resonance in that, a lot of sadness in that.

00:45:52.100 --> 00:45:57.340
[Guest]: And that was one of the things that led me perhaps to, you know, it came at a time in

00:45:57.340 --> 00:46:04.020
[Guest]: my viewing life when, like I already mentioned, I was starting to get a little tired of, of

00:46:04.020 --> 00:46:07.500
[Guest]: the overwrought language of the Hindi films that I was watching.

00:46:07.500 --> 00:46:13.020
[Guest]: This is also a time when Bachchan is in decline, serious decline, there have been some truly

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:17.900
[Guest]: ghastly films like Toofaan and Jadugar in the late 80s.

00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:23.380
[Guest]: And so it just turned into, it just happened to be a good time for someone like me to start

00:46:23.380 --> 00:46:29.060
[Guest]: exploring new pastures and to get into new idioms of filmmaking.

00:46:29.060 --> 00:46:33.580
[Unknown]: And one thing just led to another and I became a new type of movie nerd.

00:46:33.580 --> 00:46:38.220
[Guest]: Like I said, I was away from the world of Hindi cinema for around 12 years almost.

00:46:38.220 --> 00:46:42.180
[Guest]: That said, there's one little caveat, which might confuse this whole narrative all over

00:46:42.180 --> 00:46:43.180
[Guest]: again.

00:46:43.180 --> 00:46:50.260
[Guest]: In the middle of that 12 year period, I was taken by friends, by the few, you know, friends

00:46:50.260 --> 00:46:55.180
[Guest]: slash close acquaintances I had at that time in the college years, to watch Dilwale Dulhania

00:46:55.180 --> 00:47:00.020
[Guest]: Le Jayenge in 1995, when it just came out on the big screen.

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:03.260
[Guest]: And I really enjoyed it, I enjoyed it thoroughly.

00:47:03.260 --> 00:47:09.580
[Guest]: I'm not sure if I admitted it to myself, or I admitted it to my friends, but I felt stimulated

00:47:09.580 --> 00:47:15.740
[Guest]: by it and I was completely immersed when the song sequences came on, when Shah Rukh does

00:47:15.740 --> 00:47:20.300
[Guest]: that crazy thing on the piano, early in the film, and I found that fantastic.

00:47:20.300 --> 00:47:23.380
[Guest]: It reminded me of some of the Shammi Kapoor films I'd seen.

00:47:23.380 --> 00:47:30.220
[Guest]: So I still, even at that point in my viewing life, I obviously had the DNA that enabled

00:47:30.220 --> 00:47:35.980
[Guest]: me to immerse into language of mainstream Hindi cinema, it's just that it wasn't important

00:47:35.980 --> 00:47:36.980
[Guest]: enough to me.

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:41.820
[Guest]: So after that one DDLJ experience, I didn't go back to watching Hindi films on the big

00:47:41.820 --> 00:47:42.820
[Guest]: screen or anything like that.

00:47:42.820 --> 00:47:47.340
[Guest]: I went back to the sort of cinema that I had been, you know, that I'd become recently interested

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:48.340
[Guest]: in.

00:47:48.340 --> 00:47:51.100
[Guest]: It took a while to get back to Hindi cinema.

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:56.180
[Guest]: But yeah, that's, that's roughly what the journey was like, at that point.

00:47:56.180 --> 00:47:59.940
[Guest]: It also, it also brought a lot of a lot of loneliness with it, because, because the sorts

00:47:59.940 --> 00:48:05.340
[Guest]: of films I was watching, I really did not have any friends, or anyone I could talk about

00:48:05.340 --> 00:48:07.100
[Amit Varma]: them with.

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:08.100
[Amit Varma]: All of this is fascinating.

00:48:08.100 --> 00:48:12.420
[Amit Varma]: And especially, you know, when you when you mentioned Bachchan's bad films, Jadoogar and

00:48:12.420 --> 00:48:15.980
[Amit Varma]: all the other rubbish that came around that time, you know, the thought that comes to

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:20.940
[Amit Varma]: my mind is that today, when people look back on the career arc of a person like him, you

00:48:20.940 --> 00:48:25.580
[Amit Varma]: know, they can just focus on his good films, and, you know, almost a selection bias.

00:48:25.580 --> 00:48:27.340
[Amit Varma]: And they know that there are bad films in that arc.

00:48:27.340 --> 00:48:28.540
[Amit Varma]: But it's a historical thing.

00:48:28.540 --> 00:48:34.340
[Amit Varma]: But there are people who kind of live through these periods, where I think the 80s was,

00:48:34.340 --> 00:48:37.700
[Amit Varma]: you know, not just a bad time for say, Bollywood.

00:48:37.700 --> 00:48:42.260
[Amit Varma]: It was also a kind of horrendous time for Western rock, for example, you had all those

00:48:42.260 --> 00:48:44.020
[Amit Varma]: hair bands and all of that.

00:48:44.020 --> 00:48:49.720
[Amit Varma]: It almost seems like to grow up in that time, I think you and I should get special points

00:48:49.720 --> 00:48:52.100
[Amit Varma]: for surviving all the bad art that came out during that time.

00:48:52.100 --> 00:48:56.700
[Guest]: I have to say, I somewhat disagree with that, when you say 80s is a bad time for Western

00:48:56.700 --> 00:49:01.260
[Guest]: rock, wasn't that the time when, when you had REM and U2 both sort of doing some of

00:49:01.260 --> 00:49:05.740
[Guest]: their some of their major early work, and well, a few others.

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:10.300
[Amit Varma]: I'm kind of thinking more about all the hair bands and the big arena bands and all of that.

00:49:10.300 --> 00:49:15.100
[Amit Varma]: And REM really got into their best phase, I would say in the late 80s, early 90s.

00:49:15.100 --> 00:49:17.980
[Amit Varma]: From that period on my favorite REM work is certainly 90s.

00:49:17.980 --> 00:49:20.060
[Amit Varma]: And YouTube, of course, Joshua Tree was 80s.

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:22.540
[Amit Varma]: But Achtung Baby was early 90s, if I remember.

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:26.860
[Guest]: So also, I would say at risk of again, confusing the narrative or sort of getting our boxing

00:49:26.860 --> 00:49:27.860
[Guest]: gloves on.

00:49:27.860 --> 00:49:34.020
[Guest]: Actually, one of the many things I've changed my mind about a bit and I do this infuriatingly

00:49:34.020 --> 00:49:39.140
[Guest]: often often to the degree that I go back and look at my blog post written 12-13 years ago

00:49:39.140 --> 00:49:43.140
[Guest]: and I find myself disagreeing with everything I've written in a particular post.

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:48.220
[Guest]: But I'm not that sure anymore that the 1980s was was such a bad time for Hindi cinema.

00:49:48.220 --> 00:49:52.660
[Guest]: And I'm not let me clarify right at the outset, I'm not talking about the art movement or

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:53.820
[Guest]: the parallel movement.

00:49:53.820 --> 00:49:58.380
[Guest]: I'm talking about about a lot of other stuff that was happening, which would include it.

00:49:58.380 --> 00:50:02.820
[Guest]: No one's going to suggest that that these films are are interesting from beginning to

00:50:02.820 --> 00:50:08.500
[Guest]: end or really, really, you know, organically well created or anything like that.

00:50:08.500 --> 00:50:13.300
[Guest]: But I still feel like there was some interesting stuff going on in the mainstream done by directors

00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:18.180
[Guest]: like JP Dutta and Mukul Anand and Rahul Ravel, and a couple of others.

00:50:18.180 --> 00:50:22.100
[Guest]: And it's not as bad a time as a lot of us think it was.

00:50:22.100 --> 00:50:27.100
[Guest]: Also, I think with hindsight, I feel like a case can be made that there was a lot of

00:50:27.100 --> 00:50:32.660
[Guest]: a lot more honesty in some of the best of those films, or some of the some of the 80s

00:50:32.660 --> 00:50:37.180
[Guest]: films than there has been in the last two decades, where a lot of filmmakers, including

00:50:37.180 --> 00:50:43.500
[Guest]: the really good filmmakers who deserve to be respected, seem to just be very aware of

00:50:43.500 --> 00:50:49.340
[Guest]: their place in a global world, and constantly having conversations with other international

00:50:49.340 --> 00:50:54.620
[Guest]: cinemas, to the degree that they are, you know, that they almost operating in that idiom,

00:50:54.620 --> 00:51:01.300
[Guest]: in the idiom of what a certain sort of homogeneous, good film, what most cinéastes would describe

00:51:01.300 --> 00:51:05.100
[Guest]: as a good film, internationally speaking, should look like.

00:51:05.100 --> 00:51:10.620
[Guest]: A lot of the indie Hindi films of the last 10-15 years, I feel have, you know, have formally

00:51:10.620 --> 00:51:15.020
[Guest]: modelled themselves on that structure, with very good results.

00:51:15.020 --> 00:51:19.380
[Guest]: I'm talking about films that I've enjoyed a great deal, but I do wonder at times if

00:51:19.380 --> 00:51:23.780
[Guest]: something has also been lost along the way in terms of, you know, moving away from the

00:51:23.780 --> 00:51:28.860
[Guest]: very special language of Hindi cinema as it once used to be, when it was tonally all over

00:51:28.860 --> 00:51:34.820
[Guest]: the place, when when it's masala derivatives sort of came from, as we say, as we as we

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:39.940
[Guest]: know, from the from the Parsi and Sanskrit theatres, and you had a lot of tones, mishmash

00:51:39.940 --> 00:51:42.300
[Guest]: together in the same film.

00:51:42.300 --> 00:51:47.380
[Guest]: I sometimes feel that it's a bit of a loss that we moved away from there as well.

00:51:47.380 --> 00:51:51.980
[Guest]: Or at least that there seems to be no place at all for that sort of filmmaking in today's

00:51:51.980 --> 00:51:55.780
[Guest]: world unless it's done ironically, unless it's meant to be a nudge nudge wink wink

00:51:55.780 --> 00:51:57.140
[Guest]: thing or something.

00:51:57.140 --> 00:51:59.500
[Guest]: I do feel that's a loss.

00:51:59.500 --> 00:52:03.000
[Amit Varma]: So before we get back to your personal journey narrative, I'll kind of double click on this

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:07.420
[Amit Varma]: digression and kind of ask about this itself, that, you know, I get what you're saying,

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:11.400
[Amit Varma]: you're saying that at that time, filmmakers are, they are what they are, and there's no

00:52:11.400 --> 00:52:15.880
[Amit Varma]: pretentiousness that they don't have, like, today, people have, you know, different kinds

00:52:15.880 --> 00:52:20.100
[Amit Varma]: of expectations of themselves and all of that and whatever.

00:52:20.100 --> 00:52:23.340
[Amit Varma]: And we will come to current day cinema a little later.

00:52:23.340 --> 00:52:28.540
[Amit Varma]: But just going back to the 80s, my my conception would be that it wasn't that there was like

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:33.180
[Amit Varma]: almost a deliberate ideological decision that world cinema be damned, this is what we do,

00:52:33.180 --> 00:52:34.700
[Amit Varma]: we'll continue doing it.

00:52:34.700 --> 00:52:38.180
[Amit Varma]: And that therefore, there is a certain kind of purity in that I don't think there was

00:52:38.180 --> 00:52:39.180
[Amit Varma]: something like that.

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:44.860
[Amit Varma]: I think it was a lot of the films that were being made were being made not out of that

00:52:44.860 --> 00:52:49.780
[Amit Varma]: sort of conviction, but just out of, you know, they were, they were just doing what they

00:52:49.780 --> 00:52:53.860
[Amit Varma]: knew, they were just being reactive to what they thought the audiences wanted at this

00:52:53.860 --> 00:52:54.860
[Amit Varma]: time.

00:52:54.860 --> 00:52:58.300
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I understand that there are interesting things happening during this time that we

00:52:58.300 --> 00:53:02.740
[Amit Varma]: do Vinod Chopra made Parinda, but again, he's influenced by a lot of world cinema already.

00:53:02.740 --> 00:53:07.980
[Amit Varma]: So leaving those kind of outliers aside, the Rahul Ravel's and the JP Dutta's and Decoyette

00:53:07.980 --> 00:53:14.820
[Amit Varma]: and all of that stuff, which is kind of happening, but does seem to me filmmakers just focusing

00:53:14.820 --> 00:53:20.500
[Amit Varma]: in a mode of giving the audiences what they want getting a box office hit, so to say,

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:23.980
[Amit Varma]: and nothing and I'm not dissing that you live within your culture.

00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:28.740
[Amit Varma]: And it's perfectly fine if you want to just do that and do nothing else.

00:53:28.740 --> 00:53:29.780
[Amit Varma]: But any thoughts on that?

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:33.980
[Amit Varma]: And specifically, then what are the films that you'd look at during that period and

00:53:33.980 --> 00:53:38.340
[Amit Varma]: say that these are films that we should revisit now, it's not as bad as we used to think it

00:53:38.340 --> 00:53:40.660
[Amit Varma]: was like, I think Mr. India was 80s.

00:53:40.660 --> 00:53:45.460
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure you'd, you know, consider that as part of, but apart from that, what are

00:53:45.460 --> 00:53:48.060
[Amit Varma]: the kind of films which you think we should revisit and why?

00:53:48.060 --> 00:53:54.580
[Guest]: See, there are lots of films, I'll name a few, but then again, it comes with the necessary

00:53:54.580 --> 00:54:00.020
[Guest]: caveat that that many people, maybe you, maybe many others listening to this will not even

00:54:00.020 --> 00:54:03.960
[Guest]: agree with me that these are films worth revisiting for this, we have to, you know, again, come

00:54:03.960 --> 00:54:07.020
[Guest]: back to the subjectivity of all this.

00:54:07.020 --> 00:54:11.260
[Guest]: And one more thing that I'd like to say, which perhaps has a bearing on some of what I'm

00:54:11.260 --> 00:54:15.620
[Guest]: talking about is that, that as I've grown older, as a film buff, one of the things that

00:54:15.620 --> 00:54:22.300
[Guest]: has happened to me is that I've become far more interested, not in films that are interesting

00:54:22.300 --> 00:54:26.380
[Guest]: or well done from beginning to end, or, you know, just just sort of, you know, you look

00:54:26.380 --> 00:54:31.580
[Guest]: at the totality of the beast and say, okay, this is a four star film or a five star film

00:54:31.580 --> 00:54:38.340
[Guest]: to use the reductive language of star ratings, but films that that might even be pretty average

00:54:38.340 --> 00:54:43.580
[Guest]: in some ways, maybe tacky in some other ways, maybe, whatever, whatever word you want to

00:54:43.580 --> 00:54:47.020
[Guest]: use, regressive is the word that gets used a lot when we when we talk about any sort

00:54:47.020 --> 00:54:53.540
[Guest]: of world cinema, but also has points of interest, also has some sequences, some things that

00:54:53.540 --> 00:54:54.540
[Guest]: it does very well.

00:54:54.540 --> 00:55:01.340
[Guest]: Now, increasingly, I found myself finding a lot more time for that sort of thing, compared

00:55:01.340 --> 00:55:06.020
[Guest]: to, you know, this, this assessment driven idea of what sort of film is it on the whole.

00:55:06.020 --> 00:55:11.100
[Guest]: And of course, I'm also speaking with the privilege of being somebody who, who doesn't

00:55:11.100 --> 00:55:15.820
[Guest]: do reviews on a very regular basis, I, you know, in the last few years, I've been writing

00:55:15.820 --> 00:55:21.860
[Guest]: columns, I've been I've been allowed to write these very whimsical personal pieces, where,

00:55:21.860 --> 00:55:25.260
[Guest]: so for instance, two different columns that I've done for two different publications have

00:55:25.260 --> 00:55:32.300
[Guest]: actually been about sequences, about moments in a film. And of course, how those moments

00:55:32.300 --> 00:55:38.540
[Guest]: tie in with the larger animal. So I've had the luxury of doing that, which is not a luxury

00:55:38.540 --> 00:55:44.940
[Guest]: that the regular Friday to Friday film reviewer has. But that is how it's worked for me. One

00:55:44.940 --> 00:55:48.540
[Guest]: of the books that I hope to work on in the future, I don't know if I ever will, will

00:55:48.540 --> 00:55:54.620
[Guest]: be an anthology of moments, an anthology of important moments from Hindi cinema, which

00:55:54.620 --> 00:55:59.060
[Guest]: could be and a moment can be defined as a full length 10 minute sequence, or it could

00:55:59.060 --> 00:56:04.060
[Guest]: be an actor's gesture, just a little gesture or the movement of the head, which seems to

00:56:04.060 --> 00:56:07.860
[Guest]: speak volumes or whatever it is, and of course, it will be very subjective. So I'm saying

00:56:07.860 --> 00:56:14.100
[Guest]: all this also partly to prepare you and your listeners for, for the possibility that some

00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:21.540
[Guest]: of the films that I mentioned will may not really be seen by most film buffs as good

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:26.100
[Amit Varma]: films, capital G, capital B. May I just interrupt and say that you don't

00:56:26.100 --> 00:56:32.860
[Amit Varma]: have to be so defensive. And when I asked you the question, I did it with the actual

00:56:32.860 --> 00:56:36.620
[Amit Varma]: sincere intent of actually revisiting some of this stuff you're talking about to educate

00:56:36.620 --> 00:56:42.420
[Guest]: myself. So but anyway, continue. Well, because this is meant to be about my subjectivity

00:56:42.420 --> 00:56:48.500
[Guest]: as a person. I have to say I am defensive 99% of the time, when I'm talking about my

00:56:48.500 --> 00:56:52.860
[Guest]: tastes. Okay, so just to come back to what I'm saying, you know, just just look at directors,

00:56:52.860 --> 00:56:57.820
[Guest]: the interesting works of some directors. And I think some of Subhash Khai's films, including

00:56:57.820 --> 00:57:03.100
[Guest]: Meri Jang, which has Anil Kapoor and Meenakshi Chaudhary in it, is one of the relatively

00:57:03.100 --> 00:57:08.020
[Guest]: interesting mainstream films of that period. In general, I think you mentioned Mr. India,

00:57:08.020 --> 00:57:12.460
[Guest]: of course, which which I think Mr. India is a is actually a fairly respectable film in

00:57:12.460 --> 00:57:16.420
[Guest]: many ways, I think. And I think I think there are a lot of people who can just see the craft

00:57:16.420 --> 00:57:20.540
[Guest]: of that film and the honesty of that film as well quite easily. But I think this might

00:57:20.540 --> 00:57:25.300
[Guest]: be a good time to talk about how many of us have undervalued Anil Kapoor as an actor and

00:57:25.300 --> 00:57:30.020
[Guest]: he did so much interesting stuff in the 1980s. Of course, it's amazing that he's, he's still

00:57:30.020 --> 00:57:35.340
[Guest]: managed to be relevant in various ways, you know, in the 60s. But, but back then I remember,

00:57:35.340 --> 00:57:39.620
[Guest]: you know, when I when I was a kid, in the 1980s, even though I was surrounded by the

00:57:39.620 --> 00:57:45.940
[Guest]: world of Mr. India, and Tejab and Parinda and this film called Ishwar in which Anil

00:57:45.940 --> 00:57:52.900
[Guest]: Kapoor had a very interesting role and Avargi, you know, a few films like that. Somehow,

00:57:52.900 --> 00:57:56.980
[Guest]: this is something that I that I articulated to myself only years later. Somehow I thought

00:57:56.980 --> 00:58:03.580
[Guest]: of all these films, in terms of other people in the films, Sridevi, Madhuri Dixit, Jackie

00:58:03.580 --> 00:58:09.580
[Guest]: Shroff in Parinda, Nanna Patekar and things like that. Karma, Subhash Khai's Karma in

00:58:09.580 --> 00:58:13.860
[Guest]: which it became became so easy to sort of just see Anil Kapoor playing this buffoonish

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:17.420
[Guest]: character jumping around all over the place. And when you and instead you're supposed to

00:58:17.420 --> 00:58:24.820
[Guest]: be looking at Dilip Kumar and Newton and, and all that. It's only later many years later

00:58:24.820 --> 00:58:30.300
[Guest]: that I realized that Anil Kapoor was was a pretty major part of these films. And he was,

00:58:30.300 --> 00:58:35.780
[Guest]: you know, at the very least, quite good in most of them. And you know, he held his own,

00:58:35.780 --> 00:58:41.140
[Guest]: he did everything that was required of him. And I think certainly his early career, including

00:58:41.140 --> 00:58:45.580
[Guest]: his mainstream career at that time, and of course, there's a slightly not so mainstream

00:58:45.580 --> 00:58:51.020
[Guest]: career, which which includes lower profile films like Chamele Ki Shadi, and Saahib, films

00:58:51.020 --> 00:58:55.660
[Guest]: like that perhaps deserves to be looked at again. There are of course, films which which

00:58:55.660 --> 00:59:01.140
[Guest]: primarily have what one might think, think of as kisshy value or cheesy value, but which

00:59:01.140 --> 00:59:06.020
[Guest]: can also be quite stimulating in its own way, if you are in a certain type of mood. So you

00:59:06.020 --> 00:59:11.260
[Guest]: know, so so I, I remember that, you know, films like the film in which Jackie Shroff

00:59:11.260 --> 00:59:16.580
[Guest]: co-starred with a dog, Teri Meherwaniya, which was, you know, it's a film that even back

00:59:16.580 --> 00:59:21.420
[Guest]: then at the age of seven or eight, when I was watching the songs on Chitrahaar, I think

00:59:21.420 --> 00:59:26.460
[Guest]: even at that point, one realized that that one was watching something that's a bit silly,

00:59:26.460 --> 00:59:31.740
[Guest]: or whatever word you want to use. But again, I watched a lot of that film, not the whole

00:59:31.740 --> 00:59:36.540
[Guest]: thing again, but but I think maybe 80% of the film on TV, when it when it happened to

00:59:36.540 --> 00:59:41.620
[Guest]: be coming around, maybe 10 years ago or something, and I just found myself absorbed in it and

00:59:41.620 --> 00:59:45.500
[Guest]: just watching it. And maybe it has something to do with the fact that, that my own life

00:59:45.500 --> 00:59:51.100
[Guest]: had had become quite dog centric by that point. Also, so you know, so so one is interested

00:59:51.100 --> 00:59:57.300
[Guest]: in certain things and in what the relationship might be like, at its core. If you look at

00:59:57.300 --> 01:00:02.340
[Guest]: it, you know, if you take away the really melodramatic trappings, and just just look

01:00:02.340 --> 01:00:06.420
[Guest]: at the emotional core of it, that there might be something to it. I found that interesting

01:00:06.420 --> 01:00:11.500
[Guest]: as well. JP Dutta's films definitely deserve to be revisited. Unfortunately, to the best

01:00:11.500 --> 01:00:16.420
[Guest]: of my knowledge, there are, you know, major films like Ghulami, for instance, do not seem

01:00:16.420 --> 01:00:20.980
[Guest]: to be available in their complete prints anymore. I think it's a more than three hour long film.

01:00:20.980 --> 01:00:25.180
[Guest]: And I think it's on YouTube or something in two hours, 20 minutes or something funny like

01:00:25.180 --> 01:00:30.140
[Guest]: that. And I don't know how these things even work at times. And Hatyaar, which was another

01:00:30.140 --> 01:00:36.140
[Guest]: JP Dutta film, which I was a big fan of, when it first came out, and, and when I watched

01:00:36.140 --> 01:00:43.500
[Guest]: it many years later, these are all films that broadly use the language of the mainstream

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:50.780
[Guest]: Hindi film of the 1980s. Overwrought, sometimes, you know, embarrassingly dramatic, loud music

01:00:50.780 --> 01:00:55.220
[Guest]: used to used to underline everything. And I know you have a major problem with with

01:00:55.220 --> 01:01:01.380
[Guest]: that use of that emotional cue providing use of music. I don't as a rule, I actually actually

01:01:01.380 --> 01:01:06.380
[Guest]: find find it very stimulating in many contexts. But I would admit that that a lot of the 80s

01:01:06.380 --> 01:01:10.780
[Guest]: films perhaps went over the over the top with it or what you know, it's a bit difficult

01:01:10.780 --> 01:01:15.020
[Guest]: to watch some of some scenes in those films, because of how we've now been conditioned

01:01:15.020 --> 01:01:20.820
[Guest]: by by the slightly more realistic cinema. This is also true, of course, of old Hollywood,

01:01:20.820 --> 01:01:27.140
[Guest]: a lot of the 30s. Last year, when I was hosting these for these film discussion sessions,

01:01:27.140 --> 01:01:32.300
[Guest]: and looking at genres like film noir, and the screwball comedy and genre and looking

01:01:32.300 --> 01:01:38.340
[Guest]: at 1940s Hollywood films, I found myself cringing just a little bit when even in a really, really

01:01:38.340 --> 01:01:42.100
[Guest]: good Billy Wilder film that I love, you know, that that'd be, you know, the music would

01:01:42.100 --> 01:01:47.780
[Guest]: be a little more insistent than felt strictly necessary. But on the whole, I don't really

01:01:47.780 --> 01:01:53.820
[Guest]: have a problem with with that. I mean, I'm, you know, I find it quite stimulating at times.

01:01:53.820 --> 01:02:01.260
[Guest]: But yeah, so JP Dutta, a few of Mukul Anand's films are quite interesting. Rahul Ravel,

01:02:01.260 --> 01:02:06.540
[Guest]: you mentioned a film like Arjun, for instance, which is which is which is an interesting

01:02:06.540 --> 01:02:14.180
[Guest]: mid 80s take on on the angry young man for the unemployment era, that sort of thing.

01:02:14.180 --> 01:02:20.100
[Guest]: There are quite a few others. I'll keep bringing them up over the course of these conversations.

01:02:20.100 --> 01:02:25.180
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, no, you mentioned my sort of distaste for spoon feeding in the sense background

01:02:25.180 --> 01:02:29.100
[Amit Varma]: music that tells you how to feel and all of that. And I've actually been thinking about

01:02:29.100 --> 01:02:33.460
[Amit Varma]: that in recent times. And what I've realized is that, at one level, obviously, I prefer

01:02:33.460 --> 01:02:38.940
[Amit Varma]: a certain kind of understatement, where I am being manipulated as little as possible.

01:02:38.940 --> 01:02:42.940
[Amit Varma]: And you know, what's happening is happening. But then the point is that manipulation is

01:02:42.940 --> 01:02:49.180
[Amit Varma]: inevitable. Because every choice that a director makes within a film has a certain effect on

01:02:49.180 --> 01:02:53.780
[Guest]: the even even even in a documentary, every second of a film, even in a documentary. So

01:02:53.780 --> 01:02:58.620
[Amit Varma]: even when Ozu keeps a still camera in Tokyo story, and people are doing what they're doing,

01:02:58.620 --> 01:03:02.300
[Amit Varma]: he has still chosen to keep it still he's chosen to keep it in a particular place, he's

01:03:02.300 --> 01:03:07.780
[Amit Varma]: chosen to keep it for that bit of dialogue and not some other, all these are choices

01:03:07.780 --> 01:03:12.500
[Amit Varma]: are affecting you. So you're being manipulated. Anyway, people may manipulate you in understated

01:03:12.500 --> 01:03:18.180
[Amit Varma]: ways or they may manipulate you in, you know, more flamboyant and obvious ways. But what

01:03:18.180 --> 01:03:21.340
[Amit Varma]: is happening is what is happening. So even if you look at say the, you know, Lars von

01:03:21.340 --> 01:03:25.140
[Amit Varma]: Trier's dogmy kind of school that we won't have background music, and we won't have this

01:03:25.140 --> 01:03:28.900
[Amit Varma]: and we won't have that. But the bottom line is even those are choices. There's no way

01:03:28.900 --> 01:03:33.780
[Amit Varma]: to kind of get away from the artifice of, you know, the act of creation, whether you're

01:03:33.780 --> 01:03:36.300
[Amit Varma]: telling a story through a book or a film or whatever.

01:03:36.300 --> 01:03:40.260
[Guest]: But you know, you know, that's, sorry to interrupt you. That's, that's, that's a very good point.

01:03:40.260 --> 01:03:44.260
[Guest]: There's also another thing to be said, which maybe we can touch on a bit later about the

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:50.140
[Guest]: personality divide, you know, and what you said just now, actually chimes with with something

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:55.060
[Guest]: that I've had to think about a lot in recent years. And as I mentioned, one possible reason

01:03:55.060 --> 01:04:00.540
[Guest]: why I needed to get away from, from the language of, of the typical mainstream Hindi film as

01:04:00.540 --> 01:04:04.700
[Guest]: an adolescent was because it was just sort of it was, it seemed too connected. And then

01:04:04.700 --> 01:04:09.380
[Guest]: there's something I wrote about in an essay a couple of years back also, and I ended up

01:04:09.380 --> 01:04:14.540
[Guest]: articulating it in the process of writing it, it felt too close to certain other things

01:04:14.540 --> 01:04:21.460
[Guest]: that I was feeling stifled by as a very introverted, very undemonstrative kid, you know, the boisterousness

01:04:21.460 --> 01:04:28.100
[Guest]: of my nani, my grandmother, a woman who loved me a great deal, but also was too loud and

01:04:28.100 --> 01:04:34.020
[Guest]: extroverted for my liking and, you know, and moving away in some ways from her world. And

01:04:34.020 --> 01:04:37.620
[Guest]: you know, when it became possible for me to, you know, to have a videocassette player in

01:04:37.620 --> 01:04:42.900
[Guest]: my room, and to keep my door shut and to sit down and watch Hitchcock and John Ford, instead

01:04:42.900 --> 01:04:50.100
[Guest]: of watching the latest Salman Khan film of 1991. So all that is there, but I've also

01:04:50.100 --> 01:04:53.580
[Guest]: had to think about this a great deal that there are coming back to the multitudes that

01:04:53.580 --> 01:04:58.780
[Guest]: all of us contain. One thing that I've always been a little puzzled about, in you know,

01:04:58.780 --> 01:05:03.900
[Guest]: in my own personality, when it when it comes to how I watch films, or how I respond to

01:05:03.900 --> 01:05:09.700
[Guest]: films is how very often there's, you know, I find myself identifying with a character,

01:05:09.700 --> 01:05:16.300
[Guest]: or really feeling, feeling drawn to a character who on the face of it is completely different

01:05:16.300 --> 01:05:21.660
[Guest]: from me. You know, there's no, you know, connect at all. And the earliest example I can think

01:05:21.660 --> 01:05:25.460
[Guest]: of actually goes back all the way back to my childhood. You know, you're watching Sholay

01:05:25.460 --> 01:05:29.300
[Guest]: for the first time, I think it was probably, you know, when I was five or six or seven

01:05:29.300 --> 01:05:34.260
[Guest]: years old, and Amitabh Bachchan was everything to me, right. And, in this film, Amitabh

01:05:34.260 --> 01:05:39.900
[Guest]: Bachchan is playing a character who has my name, and is playing this very taciturn, slightly

01:05:39.900 --> 01:05:45.020
[Guest]: sarcastic character. And that was pretty close to my self perception as well. And you just

01:05:45.020 --> 01:05:48.820
[Guest]: think that that is the character I'd be most interested in the film. And I can say this

01:05:48.820 --> 01:05:54.380
[Guest]: hand on heart, I can say this, from the earliest that I can remember watching Sholay, and it

01:05:54.380 --> 01:06:02.300
[Guest]: continues to this day, I've always found Dharmendra's Veeru far more interesting, far more stimulating,

01:06:02.300 --> 01:06:05.900
[Guest]: you know, when the two of them are on screen together, I'm always looking at Dharmendra

01:06:05.900 --> 01:06:10.660
[Guest]: and to see what he's doing, you know, to see his, you know, his exaggerated gestures and

01:06:10.660 --> 01:06:15.540
[Guest]: his grimaces and other things he does with those huge hands of his. And that's something

01:06:15.540 --> 01:06:20.300
[Guest]: that it took me a very long time to even make sense of this, because it's completely counterintuitive.

01:06:20.300 --> 01:06:26.700
[Guest]: It makes no sense at all. If you think of, of art or creative works as being things that

01:06:26.700 --> 01:06:31.900
[Guest]: that help you, you know, tap into aspects of yourself, then I think a case can be made

01:06:31.900 --> 01:06:40.100
[Guest]: that maybe there's a closet extrovert in me, some hidden, boisterous Veeru, who got that

01:06:40.100 --> 01:06:44.420
[Guest]: sort of catharsis from watching Dharmendra in that film. And, and there are many other

01:06:44.420 --> 01:06:47.500
[Guest]: examples of that sort I can think of.

01:06:47.500 --> 01:06:50.780
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the example that comes to mind is all the colourful t-shirts and sweaters that

01:06:50.780 --> 01:06:53.900
[Amit Varma]: you wear. So maybe those are also your hidden extrovert.

01:06:53.900 --> 01:07:00.740
[Guest]: No, I mean, that is a very contrived and deliberate way of, of making up for my, for the dryness

01:07:00.740 --> 01:07:04.220
[Guest]: and the boringness of the personality.

01:07:04.220 --> 01:07:09.400
[Amit Varma]: It's interesting you say that because, you know, I remember advice that was often given

01:07:09.400 --> 01:07:12.580
[Amit Varma]: in my poker playing days, that if you're at a table and you're very tight and you're folding

01:07:12.580 --> 01:07:15.860
[Amit Varma]: all the hands, you know, people might notice and exploit that tightness.

01:07:15.860 --> 01:07:20.060
[Amit Varma]: So what you got to do is you got to talk a lot. So people feel you're involved, you know,

01:07:20.060 --> 01:07:22.720
[Amit Varma]: and they won't realise that you're actually folding everything.

01:07:22.720 --> 01:07:27.220
[Amit Varma]: But anyway, that's a boring piece of advice and not relevant beyond a certain stage of

01:07:27.220 --> 01:07:28.220
[Amit Varma]: play.

01:07:28.220 --> 01:07:32.580
[Amit Varma]: Coming back to, you know, what you said about, I mean, I have like 30 questions I have to

01:07:32.580 --> 01:07:35.740
[Amit Varma]: ask from what you have spoken about over the last 10 minutes.

01:07:35.740 --> 01:07:40.260
[Amit Varma]: But I'll go back to your personal journey. And I'm sort of struck by this beautiful quote

01:07:40.260 --> 01:07:42.340
[Amit Varma]: I found in one of your essays.

01:07:42.340 --> 01:07:47.300
[Amit Varma]: And I'll read it out a quote, much of the world cinema I now encountered felt like exercises

01:07:47.300 --> 01:07:49.100
[Amit Varma]: and coolness and restraint.

01:07:49.100 --> 01:07:53.260
[Amit Varma]: Being emotionally undemonstrative myself, I was struck by how there wasn't a need to

01:07:53.260 --> 01:07:57.540
[Amit Varma]: talk all the time, how silences in cinema could be meaningful, stop quote, and you're

01:07:57.540 --> 01:08:02.100
[Amit Varma]: talking about the time you discovered world cinema, as well, where this almost seems to

01:08:02.100 --> 01:08:06.060
[Amit Varma]: mirror that phase in your personal life where your nani is very boisterous, and you are

01:08:06.060 --> 01:08:09.700
[Amit Varma]: quiet and introverted, and Bollywood is very boisterous.

01:08:09.700 --> 01:08:14.340
[Amit Varma]: And then you discover a kind of cinema that indulges in these silences, that has the same

01:08:14.340 --> 01:08:19.460
[Amit Varma]: kind of sceptical attitude towards religion, as it were, as you have, while your nani is

01:08:19.460 --> 01:08:22.140
[Amit Varma]: a believer and Hindi cinema is a believer.

01:08:22.140 --> 01:08:28.260
[Amit Varma]: And and this got me to thinking about how much are our tastes mirrored by or shaped

01:08:28.260 --> 01:08:32.420
[Amit Varma]: by our personalities, because my default assumption has been that our tastes are like hardwired.

01:08:32.420 --> 01:08:36.140
[Amit Varma]: We are what we are, you know, for example, speaking for myself, I like a certain kind

01:08:36.140 --> 01:08:41.500
[Amit Varma]: of minimalistic, understated cinema, though, I can appreciate why people would like more

01:08:41.500 --> 01:08:45.300
[Amit Varma]: maximalist cinema, I can appreciate them at an intellectual level.

01:08:45.300 --> 01:08:53.060
[Amit Varma]: But what really appeals to me is more understated, but like certainly in your arc, and it's obviously

01:08:53.060 --> 01:08:57.020
[Amit Varma]: not a clear cut arc and all of that, but whatever little I can make out through your writings,

01:08:57.020 --> 01:09:04.220
[Amit Varma]: it seems that there is this initial distance that you feel between yourselves and say,

01:09:04.220 --> 01:09:09.720
[Amit Varma]: family or nani or whatever, and you turn away from Bollywood and at a later stage in life,

01:09:09.720 --> 01:09:13.980
[Amit Varma]: you come back in both senses where of course, you start watching Bollywood again and appreciating

01:09:13.980 --> 01:09:15.340
[Amit Varma]: it for what it is.

01:09:15.340 --> 01:09:19.860
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, you've written movingly about how, when your nani passed away, you,

01:09:19.860 --> 01:09:25.100
[Amit Varma]: you sort of regretted not talking to her more, not being with her more, all of those kind

01:09:25.100 --> 01:09:26.100
[Amit Varma]: of things.

01:09:26.100 --> 01:09:30.340
[Amit Varma]: So this is also I think, like at a personal level, and it must be true for so many of

01:09:30.340 --> 01:09:34.540
[Amit Varma]: my listeners, that when you're young, you want to express your personality, you want

01:09:34.540 --> 01:09:37.900
[Amit Varma]: to break away, you want to feel that autonomy.

01:09:37.900 --> 01:09:43.180
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, that often means you are kind of going away from your family, you look at

01:09:43.180 --> 01:09:49.000
[Amit Varma]: them in harsh ways, perhaps often because one doesn't have the maturity to, you know,

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:51.200
[Amit Varma]: see the full picture to see the multitudes.

01:09:51.200 --> 01:09:55.820
[Amit Varma]: And then later on in life, as you become an adult yourself, sometimes you go, you know,

01:09:55.820 --> 01:10:00.500
[Amit Varma]: you go back, sometimes you don't, sometimes your vision sort of deepens.

01:10:00.500 --> 01:10:05.620
[Amit Varma]: So you know, does this make any sense when this connection of the personal and how one

01:10:05.620 --> 01:10:09.100
[Amit Varma]: relates to the art and entertainment one sees?

01:10:09.100 --> 01:10:12.860
[Amit Varma]: And do you think that, and again, I'm thinking aloud, my assumption was your taste is what

01:10:12.860 --> 01:10:13.860
[Amit Varma]: it is.

01:10:13.860 --> 01:10:17.520
[Amit Varma]: But and my taste has changed in different ways over the years, but I would have thought

01:10:17.520 --> 01:10:18.980
[Amit Varma]: it's changed on its own.

01:10:18.980 --> 01:10:22.900
[Amit Varma]: But do you think there is also a way just by thinking about it by consciously thinking

01:10:22.900 --> 01:10:27.060
[Amit Varma]: about why we like the stuff we like and why we don't like the stuff we like, that we can

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:32.100
[Amit Varma]: shape our taste as well that we can make ourselves more appreciative of things we might not otherwise

01:10:32.100 --> 01:10:35.740
[Amit Varma]: have liked, like talking to you, for example, I'm definitely going to go back and revisit

01:10:35.740 --> 01:10:40.140
[Amit Varma]: some of these films you talk about at the very least, look at your essays on these moments

01:10:40.140 --> 01:10:44.740
[Amit Varma]: and kind of try to see through them and who knows, you know, that might kind of make me

01:10:44.740 --> 01:10:47.420
[Amit Varma]: look at them in a different way.

01:10:47.420 --> 01:10:52.500
[Amit Varma]: Do you think there is that possibility or should one tell oneself that don't get ossified?

01:10:52.500 --> 01:10:53.500
[Amit Varma]: You know, keep searching?

01:10:53.500 --> 01:11:00.620
[Guest]: Well, as a, you know, as a critic, as somebody who's writing about cinema and who's so nerdish

01:11:00.620 --> 01:11:07.100
[Guest]: that you know, he's given over a great deal of his life to doing almost nothing but watching

01:11:07.100 --> 01:11:11.460
[Guest]: films and thinking about them and trying to articulate thoughts about them.

01:11:11.460 --> 01:11:16.380
[Guest]: I would say and this is advice that I give to anybody, you know, in classes, anyone who's

01:11:16.380 --> 01:11:22.020
[Guest]: trying to be a critic or a reviewer, the first thing I say is read, read, please read as

01:11:22.020 --> 01:11:26.660
[Guest]: much as you possibly can, watch as many different types of films as you as you possibly can

01:11:26.660 --> 01:11:31.460
[Guest]: without getting, you know, into the, into ideas of what is a good film, what is a bad

01:11:31.460 --> 01:11:36.820
[Guest]: film, you know, don't get into ideas about categories being bad.

01:11:36.820 --> 01:11:40.500
[Guest]: Once you start dealing with individual films, of course, you know, your job is going to

01:11:40.500 --> 01:11:44.140
[Guest]: be to say that that something worked for you, something didn't work for you and then to

01:11:44.140 --> 01:11:48.940
[Guest]: articulate why it didn't, but don't go into categories thinking that this is innately

01:11:48.940 --> 01:11:54.820
[Guest]: bad or this sort of genre or this sort of tone or this sort of mode, or whatever, this

01:11:54.820 --> 01:11:57.060
[Guest]: style of filmmaking is bad.

01:11:57.060 --> 01:11:58.700
[Guest]: That's one piece of advice I give them.

01:11:58.700 --> 01:12:02.660
[Guest]: Now, of course, even while I'm giving it, I know that this is not something you can

01:12:02.660 --> 01:12:04.540
[Guest]: force your brain to do, right?

01:12:04.540 --> 01:12:05.540
[Guest]: And that's what you're saying.

01:12:05.540 --> 01:12:08.060
[Guest]: I mean, I'm sure there's something to what you're saying about what a lot of our tastes

01:12:08.060 --> 01:12:10.580
[Guest]: being hardwired in some contexts.

01:12:10.580 --> 01:12:15.340
[Guest]: I find if you're asking me personally, and you're asking me about cinema, and maybe about

01:12:15.340 --> 01:12:20.580
[Guest]: literature as well, my experience has been that my tastes have not been hardwired, they've

01:12:20.580 --> 01:12:22.220
[Guest]: shifted a lot over time.

01:12:22.220 --> 01:12:27.340
[Guest]: And it's something like as implied earlier, it's something that I'm quietly proud of the

01:12:27.340 --> 01:12:30.980
[Guest]: fact that I seem to have the capacity, I don't know where it comes from, it's not come out

01:12:30.980 --> 01:12:36.700
[Guest]: of some deliberate effort, you know, as far as I know, but I seem to have this capacity

01:12:36.700 --> 01:12:41.260
[Guest]: to appreciate many different types of things, which is pretty useful.

01:12:41.260 --> 01:12:46.540
[Guest]: It's a useful quality to have, if you're writing about books and films.

01:12:46.540 --> 01:12:51.780
[Guest]: That said, of course, I completely get that it might not come naturally to everybody.

01:12:51.780 --> 01:12:57.140
[Guest]: And that therefore, maybe a case can be made that you make some sort of effort, you put

01:12:57.140 --> 01:13:02.660
[Guest]: yourself in this place where, you know, if you're watching films, and you have this innate

01:13:02.660 --> 01:13:08.340
[Guest]: resistance to a certain type of film, you don't like the idea of romantic films, mushy

01:13:08.340 --> 01:13:13.980
[Guest]: romantic films, or you don't like action films or whatever, then if you're trying seriously

01:13:13.980 --> 01:13:19.180
[Guest]: to be a film critic or a film writer, you do have to make a minimum effort, I feel,

01:13:19.180 --> 01:13:25.660
[Guest]: to try and get into that world to try and appreciate the terms of that world.

01:13:25.660 --> 01:13:30.340
[Guest]: Even this can be very difficult for one very simple reason that there are certain genres

01:13:30.340 --> 01:13:33.020
[Guest]: that people can just have a visceral problem with, right?

01:13:33.020 --> 01:13:37.380
[Guest]: A bodily problem with horror, horror is the classic example, you know, especially the

01:13:37.380 --> 01:13:41.940
[Guest]: jump scare sort of horror, I know so many people, so many friends who don't have any

01:13:41.940 --> 01:13:46.420
[Guest]: snobbery or condescension towards horror at all, but who simply cannot watch a horror

01:13:46.420 --> 01:13:50.220
[Guest]: film because it's too much for their nerves, they can't deal with it.

01:13:50.220 --> 01:13:54.420
[Guest]: Now, if somebody like that wants to become a film critic and is then told to go and watch

01:13:54.420 --> 01:13:57.700
[Guest]: a horror film, obviously, it's a less than ideal situation.

01:13:57.700 --> 01:14:02.660
[Guest]: I sometimes have a problem with very loud action films, especially if I'm watching them

01:14:02.660 --> 01:14:08.740
[Guest]: in a theatre with Dolby sound or whatever, and my ears are being assailed, I get headaches

01:14:08.740 --> 01:14:09.740
[Guest]: easily.

01:14:09.740 --> 01:14:17.060
[Guest]: So there's a bodily response to that, which can affect the objectivity, quote-unquote,

01:14:17.060 --> 01:14:20.180
[Guest]: with which you receive this film or write about it.

01:14:20.180 --> 01:14:25.140
[Guest]: This has been a very long and rambling way of approaching what you asked.

01:14:25.140 --> 01:14:31.420
[Guest]: But yeah, I do feel like we probably are hardwired in many contexts.

01:14:31.420 --> 01:14:37.340
[Guest]: In some contexts, maybe including things that we feel very personally engaged with from

01:14:37.340 --> 01:14:43.180
[Guest]: an early age, as I did with cinema and with literature, perhaps one just has sufficient

01:14:43.180 --> 01:14:50.180
[Guest]: time to explore many different types of books, films, and to start appreciating them.

01:14:50.180 --> 01:14:51.180
[Guest]: Maybe it just works that way.

01:14:51.180 --> 01:14:56.780
[Guest]: And that's what we call taste changing over time, or becoming more inclusive.

01:14:56.780 --> 01:14:57.780
[Guest]: I don't know.

01:14:57.780 --> 01:14:58.780
[Guest]: I don't know if that makes any sense.

01:14:58.780 --> 01:15:04.860
[Amit Varma]: No, no, makes a lot of sense and before we go into a break, let's talk a bit about horror.

01:15:04.860 --> 01:15:09.060
[Amit Varma]: Because you've got a beautiful chapter in your book, Popcorn Essays, about your love

01:15:09.060 --> 01:15:10.620
[Amit Varma]: for horror cinema.

01:15:10.620 --> 01:15:14.780
[Amit Varma]: And I was especially struck by this lovely line again, I'll quote you quote, superficial

01:15:14.780 --> 01:15:17.700
[Amit Varma]: details of time and place scarcely matter anyway.

01:15:17.700 --> 01:15:21.660
[Amit Varma]: As in so many great horror films, the setting is really the human soul.

01:15:21.660 --> 01:15:23.940
[Amit Varma]: And it's always nighttime, stop quote.

01:15:23.940 --> 01:15:27.060
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that you know, people who are into high art and high literature and

01:15:27.060 --> 01:15:31.860
[Amit Varma]: of so on, often tend to sort of condescend to the genres like horror and science fiction.

01:15:31.860 --> 01:15:37.420
[Amit Varma]: But I think that many of the finest explorations of what it is to be human actually come from

01:15:37.420 --> 01:15:42.100
[Amit Varma]: within the genres like, like there's a 1980 film I recommend everybody watches, which

01:15:42.100 --> 01:15:46.300
[Amit Varma]: I'd written a column about, I'll post it from the show notes called Cannibal Holocaust.

01:15:46.300 --> 01:15:49.780
[Amit Varma]: And it was directed by this guy called Ruggiero Diodato.

01:15:49.780 --> 01:15:54.460
[Amit Varma]: And Cannibal Holocaust is, it's really one of those found film things where these people

01:15:54.460 --> 01:15:59.340
[Amit Varma]: discover these videotapes, which were shot by these filmmakers who had gone to some remote

01:15:59.340 --> 01:16:02.220
[Amit Varma]: jungles where they were filming cannibals.

01:16:02.220 --> 01:16:06.980
[Amit Varma]: And it almost it served as an allegory of something that didn't exist yet, which is

01:16:06.980 --> 01:16:11.940
[Amit Varma]: this sort of Instagram age where you're documenting everything, everything is a selfie, which,

01:16:11.940 --> 01:16:17.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, I wouldn't say not exist yet, because that innate urge for self documentation and

01:16:17.380 --> 01:16:19.340
[Amit Varma]: the performative urge, I guess, was always there.

01:16:19.340 --> 01:16:22.080
[Amit Varma]: And all of us technologies enabled it in new ways.

01:16:22.080 --> 01:16:25.860
[Amit Varma]: And basically, they keep filming each other, one of them dies, one of them, you know, has

01:16:25.860 --> 01:16:29.860
[Amit Varma]: his vital organs chopped off and burnt and all kinds of nonsense is happening.

01:16:29.860 --> 01:16:34.700
[Amit Varma]: And they're filming everything and eventually they end up filming their own sort of deaths.

01:16:34.700 --> 01:16:39.180
[Amit Varma]: And at one level, it's just a gory horror film at another level, I just found it incredibly

01:16:39.180 --> 01:16:42.940
[Amit Varma]: profound in all these human instincts that it is kind of looking at.

01:16:42.940 --> 01:16:46.520
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is a guy who directed that film, Ruggiero Diodato.

01:16:46.520 --> 01:16:48.020
[Amit Varma]: And this was a 1980 film.

01:16:48.020 --> 01:16:53.700
[Amit Varma]: He went on to act in Hostel 2 by Eli Roth, where in a lovely scene, he plays this sort

01:16:53.700 --> 01:16:59.940
[Amit Varma]: of cannibal client who is, you know, out of a live person, he's carving out a steak as

01:16:59.940 --> 01:17:04.740
[Amit Varma]: it were, while, you know, Bide is playing in the background, a very elegant scene in

01:17:04.740 --> 01:17:09.900
[Amit Varma]: the hostel films also are sort of fascinating looks at addiction and consumerism and all

01:17:09.900 --> 01:17:10.900
[Amit Varma]: of these things.

01:17:10.900 --> 01:17:15.140
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about your journey through horror.

01:17:15.140 --> 01:17:19.380
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, I have, of course, watched way, way less than you and, you know, these are

01:17:19.380 --> 01:17:23.660
[Amit Varma]: just kind of selective impressions, but you've probably, you know, watched everything there

01:17:23.660 --> 01:17:24.660
[Guest]: is in horror.

01:17:24.660 --> 01:17:25.660
[Guest]: No, no, I haven't.

01:17:25.660 --> 01:17:28.660
[Guest]: I haven't come close to watching everything there is in horror.

01:17:28.660 --> 01:17:33.180
[Guest]: I haven't watched so much of the more contemporary stuff or the stuff of the last 20-25 years.

01:17:33.180 --> 01:17:34.180
[Guest]: Where does one begin?

01:17:34.180 --> 01:17:38.620
[Guest]: One thing I can say is that I'm glad that you mentioned the hostel films, which again,

01:17:38.620 --> 01:17:39.620
[Guest]: I haven't seen.

01:17:39.620 --> 01:17:43.740
[Guest]: But from what I know about them, those are fairly mainstream horror films, right?

01:17:43.740 --> 01:17:52.420
[Guest]: Those aren't respectable horror films, which is a new category of film that I've become

01:17:52.420 --> 01:17:53.900
[Guest]: very nervous about.

01:17:53.900 --> 01:17:58.940
[Guest]: Having said that one should not judge categories, I will now say that the respectable horror

01:17:58.940 --> 01:18:04.140
[Guest]: film is this category that I'm very nervous about because what it leads to in my experience

01:18:04.140 --> 01:18:12.620
[Guest]: is a lot of young, woke critics talking about how so-and-so film made by Jordan Peele or

01:18:12.620 --> 01:18:15.820
[Guest]: whoever isn't just a horror film.

01:18:15.820 --> 01:18:18.940
[Guest]: It isn't a mere horror film, it is something more.

01:18:18.940 --> 01:18:24.140
[Guest]: And speaking as someone who loves mere horror films, and who has been endlessly stimulated

01:18:24.140 --> 01:18:28.820
[Guest]: by them, I start getting very suspicious when a film is described as something more than

01:18:28.820 --> 01:18:29.820
[Guest]: a horror film.

01:18:29.820 --> 01:18:37.900
[Guest]: As if horror is something that is innately disrespectful and you have these, you know,

01:18:37.900 --> 01:18:43.060
[Guest]: once a very overt layer of social commentary comes into it, you know, it's like, oh, this

01:18:43.060 --> 01:18:44.060
[Guest]: is not just a horror film.

01:18:44.060 --> 01:18:49.980
[Guest]: This is something that happened, I remember recently in the Indian context with the latest

01:18:49.980 --> 01:18:55.620
[Guest]: of these often tedious anthologies that come out on Netflix, where Dibakar and Anurag and

01:18:55.620 --> 01:18:59.860
[Guest]: Zoya and Karan Johar are making short films.

01:18:59.860 --> 01:19:07.220
[Guest]: So there was the Ghost Stories one, where everybody was raving about Dibakar's film.

01:19:07.220 --> 01:19:10.860
[Guest]: And I saw it, and I liked it moderately.

01:19:10.860 --> 01:19:15.340
[Guest]: And then I started just reading some of the reviews, and all the reviews were just going

01:19:15.340 --> 01:19:22.380
[Guest]: on and on about how, you know, this is a film that just takes horror to a new level, because

01:19:22.380 --> 01:19:28.180
[Guest]: it's got this very, you know, what to my eyes was fairly clearly and explicitly spelt out

01:19:28.180 --> 01:19:33.060
[Guest]: social commentary about the current state of affairs or whatever, you know, the world

01:19:33.060 --> 01:19:35.260
[Guest]: that we're currently living in.

01:19:35.260 --> 01:19:39.300
[Guest]: And it used a broad horror framework to do that, but it just became one of those things

01:19:39.300 --> 01:19:40.620
[Guest]: that everybody was raving about.

01:19:40.620 --> 01:19:45.620
[Guest]: And I was thinking, listen, horror has always had subtexts.

01:19:45.620 --> 01:19:49.900
[Guest]: Horror is a subtext to begin with, you know, you go back and read about the history of

01:19:49.900 --> 01:19:58.220
[Guest]: cinema, the earliest films when pictures first started moving on walls, and the first generation

01:19:58.220 --> 01:20:04.060
[Guest]: of film viewers had to deal with this horrific thing happening in front of them, you know,

01:20:04.060 --> 01:20:05.500
[Guest]: characters moving in front of them.

01:20:05.500 --> 01:20:11.980
[Guest]: And then this horrible, ghastly thing called the cut came along, where there's a cut from

01:20:11.980 --> 01:20:14.660
[Guest]: one scene to a completely unrelated scene.

01:20:14.660 --> 01:20:19.180
[Guest]: And the shock that would have provided to the nervous systems of the first generations

01:20:19.180 --> 01:20:20.180
[Guest]: of viewers.

01:20:20.180 --> 01:20:28.380
[Guest]: Horror is built into cinema's DNA, to start with, you know, it taps into some of our deepest

01:20:28.380 --> 01:20:32.780
[Guest]: fears about technology, about where we can go with it.

01:20:32.780 --> 01:20:37.740
[Guest]: So the subtext is there to begin with, even before you start exploring what the theme

01:20:37.740 --> 01:20:42.500
[Guest]: of a particular film is, even before you start talking about whether, you know, whether Dracula

01:20:42.500 --> 01:20:50.860
[Guest]: has this, or whether Frankenstein has this deep rooted theme about man playing God or

01:20:50.860 --> 01:20:51.860
[Guest]: whatever it is.

01:20:51.860 --> 01:20:56.380
[Guest]: In the context of cinema, horror is just, you know, it really is, I mean, you could

01:20:56.380 --> 01:21:02.620
[Guest]: make the case that it's a synonym for cinema, it's just another word for cinema.

01:21:02.620 --> 01:21:08.260
[Guest]: And I find it a little, for lack of a better word, I find it a bit pretentious when people

01:21:08.260 --> 01:21:15.940
[Guest]: are constantly looking for horror films having these very explicit layers of social commentary

01:21:15.940 --> 01:21:16.940
[Guest]: in them.

01:21:16.940 --> 01:21:22.460
[Guest]: This is not to say that a Jordan Peele film is not a good film in its own right, you know,

01:21:22.460 --> 01:21:23.460
[Guest]: for what it is.

01:21:23.460 --> 01:21:29.100
[Guest]: It's just that I feel like I've got a bit of a mental block against that sort of reaction

01:21:29.100 --> 01:21:33.500
[Guest]: to horror cinema, which is also why, to come back to what I was saying earlier, I'm glad

01:21:33.500 --> 01:21:40.740
[Guest]: to hear you talk about the more lowbrow, quote unquote, films like Hostel or Cannibal Holocaust

01:21:40.740 --> 01:21:41.740
[Guest]: or whatever.

01:21:41.740 --> 01:21:46.220
[Guest]: Again, there's been lots of personal resonance for me now, you know, coming back to the parent

01:21:46.220 --> 01:21:52.660
[Guest]: child theme that I've always found interesting in a lot of the art that I've consumed.

01:21:52.660 --> 01:21:57.260
[Guest]: Psycho is one thing, there's this wonderful film, this French film called Eyes Without

01:21:57.260 --> 01:22:04.500
[Guest]: a Face, which is the English title by Georges Franjou, which is also a 1960 or 61, which

01:22:04.500 --> 01:22:08.620
[Guest]: is pretty gruesome in some ways, though, of course, it's undercut by the fact that it's

01:22:08.620 --> 01:22:14.020
[Guest]: a black and white film about a young woman whose face has been disfigured and her mad

01:22:14.020 --> 01:22:20.260
[Guest]: scientist father who's trying to set her right by finding other young women whose faces can

01:22:20.260 --> 01:22:26.260
[Guest]: be used for the purpose, quite visibly in terms of its subject matter.

01:22:26.260 --> 01:22:31.500
[Guest]: But again, a very moving film in many ways, and if you just look at it in terms of the

01:22:31.500 --> 01:22:36.940
[Guest]: father daughter scenes in it, and the desperation of this man, who is a horror movie monster,

01:22:36.940 --> 01:22:43.700
[Guest]: but is also a tormented father, you know, things like that have always, you know, hit

01:22:43.700 --> 01:22:48.580
[Guest]: me in, you know, in some place that I can't fully articulate.

01:22:48.580 --> 01:22:52.980
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, lots to explore there, which we'll do as the show goes along, you know, how your

01:22:52.980 --> 01:22:56.980
[Amit Varma]: political lens can influence the way you look at art, how young people today perhaps consume

01:22:56.980 --> 01:23:00.180
[Amit Varma]: art and discover art and how they view it all fascinating.

01:23:00.180 --> 01:23:03.660
[Amit Varma]: But before we go in for a break, you know, you were talking about the spectacle of the

01:23:03.660 --> 01:23:06.980
[Amit Varma]: early movie, what's the phenomenon of the cut and all that.

01:23:06.980 --> 01:23:11.980
[Amit Varma]: So I just want to read out this lovely quote by you about the magical quality of films,

01:23:11.980 --> 01:23:16.460
[Amit Varma]: where you write quote, there's a popular story from the earliest days of moving pictures

01:23:16.460 --> 01:23:20.460
[Amit Varma]: about the unprepared viewers of a Lumière brothers short film, who ran out of a Paris

01:23:20.460 --> 01:23:24.900
[Amit Varma]: theater when confronted with the image of a train seemingly coming towards them.

01:23:24.900 --> 01:23:28.580
[Amit Varma]: This is probably apocryphal, but there are other similar less dramatic stories from that

01:23:28.580 --> 01:23:33.300
[Amit Varma]: period and even common sense tells us that the first movie viewers must have experienced

01:23:33.300 --> 01:23:34.980
[Amit Varma]: quite a few shocks to the system.

01:23:34.980 --> 01:23:40.620
[Amit Varma]: Today, even the most casual viewers unconsciously process such aspects of film grammar as cross

01:23:40.620 --> 01:23:42.440
[Amit Varma]: cutting between unrelated scenes.

01:23:42.440 --> 01:23:46.620
[Amit Varma]: But in the earlier days, even basic cutting from one image to another, let alone rapid

01:23:46.620 --> 01:23:51.420
[Amit Varma]: fire splicing must have felt otherworldly, to some it must have been frightening, even

01:23:51.420 --> 01:23:52.420
[Amit Varma]: demonic.

01:23:52.420 --> 01:23:56.540
[Amit Varma]: Was that puffing train the first movie monster, stop quote.

01:23:56.540 --> 01:24:00.780
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, this this also we take cinema for granted, we are not struck by any of it

01:24:00.780 --> 01:24:01.780
[Amit Varma]: as such.

01:24:01.780 --> 01:24:07.500
[Amit Varma]: But this was something that was that even perhaps this view of cinema as something that

01:24:07.500 --> 01:24:12.180
[Amit Varma]: influences people more profoundly than say books or art was something that led to our

01:24:12.180 --> 01:24:16.660
[Amit Varma]: censorship laws, because, you know, back in the 50s or 60s, or whenever the censor board

01:24:16.660 --> 01:24:21.900
[Amit Varma]: was founded, one of the reasons for having much harsher restrictions on cinema, as opposed

01:24:21.900 --> 01:24:28.740
[Amit Varma]: to say books, was that, you know, cinema influences naive people in all these deep ways.

01:24:28.740 --> 01:24:32.420
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, we must, you know, protect them that whole paternalism came from there.

01:24:32.420 --> 01:24:37.060
[Amit Varma]: And thankfully, that, you know, books were not subject to the same thing.

