01:26:01.180 --> 01:26:06.180
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Jai Arjun Singh about films, books, writing, all of those things.

01:26:06.180 --> 01:26:09.660
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about something that we've in fact discussed in the past, because, you know,

01:26:09.660 --> 01:26:13.900
[Amit Varma]: one of the realizations I came to early on, and in a sense, I went through a similar journey

01:26:13.900 --> 01:26:19.940
[Amit Varma]: to yours where, as a kid, I used to look down a little bit on Bollywood, partly because,

01:26:19.940 --> 01:26:25.060
[Amit Varma]: you know, my father was director of the FDII between 86 and 91.

01:26:25.060 --> 01:26:28.060
[Amit Varma]: So I grew up at home just watching world cinema all the time.

01:26:28.060 --> 01:26:31.740
[Amit Varma]: I didn't even know that these were like kind of two separate things.

01:26:31.740 --> 01:26:33.460
[Amit Varma]: I just didn't think of it that way.

01:26:33.460 --> 01:26:36.940
[Amit Varma]: So it was a question of taste, that I liked a certain kind of cinema much more than the

01:26:36.940 --> 01:26:37.940
[Amit Varma]: other.

01:26:37.940 --> 01:26:41.060
[Amit Varma]: And as a young kid, I looked down on one of them as well.

01:26:41.060 --> 01:26:45.580
[Amit Varma]: Now, as one grows older, obviously, I wouldn't say that I'm a full fledged mainstream Hindi

01:26:45.580 --> 01:26:47.580
[Amit Varma]: film lover that I am not.

01:26:47.580 --> 01:26:53.460
[Amit Varma]: But I do recognize that it is a category error in my view, and we'll discuss this and we've

01:26:53.460 --> 01:26:57.100
[Amit Varma]: spoken about this, that I sort of came to the recognition at one point in time that

01:26:57.100 --> 01:27:02.300
[Amit Varma]: it's a category error to judge a Hindi film as it were by the same parameters by which

01:27:02.300 --> 01:27:05.260
[Amit Varma]: I look at a Western film, because they're so completely different, they're trying to

01:27:05.260 --> 01:27:06.780
[Amit Varma]: do completely different things.

01:27:06.780 --> 01:27:09.060
[Amit Varma]: They're almost different art forms.

01:27:09.060 --> 01:27:15.100
[Amit Varma]: So one has to sort of just shift one's frame of reference to enjoy one over the other.

01:27:15.100 --> 01:27:19.180
[Amit Varma]: Now, there's an interesting quote by you, which again, I'll read out, where you indicate

01:27:19.180 --> 01:27:22.340
[Amit Varma]: that this is a bit of a false dichotomy.

01:27:22.340 --> 01:27:27.040
[Amit Varma]: And here's what you say, quote, I don't want to make a facile comparison that goes Hindi

01:27:27.040 --> 01:27:31.700
[Amit Varma]: cinema is equal to loud melodrama, European cinema is equal to understated realism.

01:27:31.700 --> 01:27:33.440
[Amit Varma]: It's much more complex than that.

01:27:33.440 --> 01:27:37.620
[Amit Varma]: Each of these forms has many modes of expression, and cultures and behaviors around the world

01:27:37.620 --> 01:27:39.300
[Amit Varma]: are far from homogenous.

01:27:39.300 --> 01:27:43.380
[Amit Varma]: An Indian film that depicted the melodramatic behavior of someone like my grandmother, or

01:27:43.380 --> 01:27:46.980
[Amit Varma]: many other similar people I knew, could be realistic and truthful.

01:27:46.980 --> 01:27:50.940
[Amit Varma]: But many viewers, even Indian viewers who know this culture well, might instinctively

01:27:50.940 --> 01:27:52.780
[Amit Varma]: denounce it as over the top.

01:27:52.780 --> 01:27:57.180
[Amit Varma]: And much of European cinema, some Italian genres, for example, is loud, goofy or hyper

01:27:57.180 --> 01:28:01.700
[Amit Varma]: dramatic in ways that are comparable to the mainstream Hindi film, stop quote.

01:28:01.700 --> 01:28:04.660
[Amit Varma]: And this point about Italian films is great, because one of my favorite directors growing

01:28:04.660 --> 01:28:06.220
[Amit Varma]: up was Fellini.

01:28:06.220 --> 01:28:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And one of the Fellini films that I really loved, which critics don't talk about in the

01:28:09.380 --> 01:28:14.100
[Amit Varma]: canon, but I really loved it is a film called Amar Kaur, you know, which has all these sort

01:28:14.100 --> 01:28:18.860
[Amit Varma]: of Italian families behaving in really boisterous, dramatic ways.

01:28:18.860 --> 01:28:23.860
[Amit Varma]: And Italians in many ways are like, Italians seem to me to be the European Bengalis in

01:28:23.860 --> 01:28:26.100
[Amit Varma]: some of the melodrama and extreme emotion.

01:28:26.100 --> 01:28:29.780
[Amit Varma]: And of course, one of my favorite films of childhood was Fellini's brilliant Eve with

01:28:29.780 --> 01:28:34.260
[Amit Varma]: a Lonely, a fantastic coming of age film that spoke so much to me.

01:28:34.260 --> 01:28:39.320
[Amit Varma]: But to kind of get back to the subject at hand, that one there is, of course, a difference.

01:28:39.320 --> 01:28:44.440
[Amit Varma]: But what you're also pointing out is that there's no strict boundary between the two.

01:28:44.440 --> 01:28:50.380
[Amit Varma]: How has your thinking on this evolved over these many years, like I presume that you

01:28:50.380 --> 01:28:55.500
[Amit Varma]: shared some of that initial sort of snobbishness and got over it and realized not to make value

01:28:55.500 --> 01:28:57.020
[Amit Varma]: judgments at all.

01:28:57.020 --> 01:28:58.860
[Amit Varma]: But how does one look at it?

01:28:58.860 --> 01:29:02.500
[Amit Varma]: Do you have to sort of court shift, so to say, when you view one kind of cinema over

01:29:02.500 --> 01:29:03.500
[Amit Varma]: the other?

01:29:03.500 --> 01:29:06.500
[Amit Varma]: How does it all work for you?

01:29:06.500 --> 01:29:07.500
[Guest]: Not at a conscious level.

01:29:07.500 --> 01:29:12.380
[Guest]: I mean, I'm sure there must be some sort of mental shift that happens.

01:29:12.380 --> 01:29:18.220
[Guest]: But as of now, I don't think it's conscious at all.

01:29:18.220 --> 01:29:25.460
[Guest]: I find it quite easy at most times to watch a particular sort of film on one day.

01:29:25.460 --> 01:29:31.260
[Guest]: And watch a very different sort of film the next day, without really thinking in terms

01:29:31.260 --> 01:29:32.260
[Guest]: of...

01:29:32.260 --> 01:29:34.500
[Guest]: And I suppose most people don't really do that.

01:29:34.500 --> 01:29:38.980
[Guest]: I mean, how do you consciously make that shift anyway, right?

01:29:38.980 --> 01:29:43.540
[Guest]: It's not like I start the film saying, okay, deep breath, count to 10.

01:29:43.540 --> 01:29:46.340
[Guest]: This is going to be this sort of film.

01:29:46.340 --> 01:29:47.340
[Guest]: It's nothing like that.

01:29:47.340 --> 01:29:53.500
[Guest]: I think it's just a question of receiving whatever film it is, and then seeing if that

01:29:53.500 --> 01:29:57.340
[Guest]: individual film works for you or not.

01:29:57.340 --> 01:30:00.700
[Guest]: And then, of course, if you're doing this professionally, and you have to write a piece

01:30:00.700 --> 01:30:06.580
[Guest]: about it, then the big thing you have to do is to articulate as well as possible, why

01:30:06.580 --> 01:30:09.380
[Guest]: it worked for you, or why it didn't work for you.

01:30:09.380 --> 01:30:14.580
[Guest]: And in the process of that articulation also, I don't usually feel the need to put down

01:30:14.580 --> 01:30:19.620
[Guest]: things like, as you mentioned, I do tend to be defensive in many ways, and some of that

01:30:19.620 --> 01:30:24.660
[Guest]: defensiveness does occasionally come into my writing when I'm writing about a really

01:30:24.660 --> 01:30:30.500
[Guest]: mainstream Hindi film, which I know, tends to be the subject of snobbery from a lot of

01:30:30.500 --> 01:30:34.060
[Guest]: the people around me, that does come in sometimes.

01:30:34.060 --> 01:30:37.180
[Guest]: But generally speaking, I'm not really...

01:30:37.180 --> 01:30:43.940
[Guest]: Even in my writing, I'm not really trying to describe what the assumptions that you

01:30:43.940 --> 01:30:48.700
[Guest]: have to make while watching this particular type of film, or anything like that.

01:30:48.700 --> 01:30:52.700
[Guest]: I just take it as a given that there are many different modes of expression, and that there

01:30:52.700 --> 01:31:02.860
[Guest]: are so many ways of expressing emotion truthfully, and that truthfulness doesn't have to be synonymous

01:31:02.860 --> 01:31:08.740
[Guest]: with understatement, for instance, to take a really obvious example.

01:31:08.740 --> 01:31:10.780
[Guest]: You asked something else before this, right?

01:31:10.780 --> 01:31:13.620
[Guest]: I've gone off on a tangent again, as I do.

01:31:13.620 --> 01:31:19.740
[Amit Varma]: No, it was sort of about your thinking about this dichotomy, and just to kind of, you know,

01:31:19.740 --> 01:31:24.100
[Amit Varma]: double click again, as a film critic, like you said, when you're writing about it, it

01:31:24.100 --> 01:31:30.540
[Amit Varma]: seems to me that there is a certain dissonance, and I'm just thinking aloud, a certain dissonance

01:31:30.540 --> 01:31:35.340
[Amit Varma]: in this in writing about a particular kind of film and another kind of film, where the

01:31:35.340 --> 01:31:41.780
[Amit Varma]: reader would probably expect you to have a similar sense of use a similar bunch of parameters

01:31:41.780 --> 01:31:44.820
[Amit Varma]: or metrics to talk about these films, and actually, you cannot do that.

01:31:44.820 --> 01:31:49.060
[Amit Varma]: Like when you talk about a film like Moonlight, for example, right, which I loved so much,

01:31:49.060 --> 01:31:53.360
[Amit Varma]: I thought it's the best film to win a Best Film Oscar when it did just such a great moving

01:31:53.360 --> 01:31:55.780
[Amit Varma]: film and very understated as well.

01:31:55.780 --> 01:31:56.780
[Amit Varma]: Right?

01:31:56.780 --> 01:32:00.380
[Amit Varma]: Now, if within Moonlight, there was any moment where that understatement breaks, and when

01:32:00.380 --> 01:32:05.260
[Amit Varma]: a character says what he is feeling, it would be a tremendous false note, it would it would

01:32:05.260 --> 01:32:09.660
[Amit Varma]: just mar the sort of the unity of the film and what held it together.

01:32:09.660 --> 01:32:13.740
[Amit Varma]: But so you know, that would become a parameter for that film.

01:32:13.740 --> 01:32:18.020
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, if you're watching a Hindi film, that kind of expression, almost

01:32:18.020 --> 01:32:22.060
[Amit Varma]: a spoon feeding of the audience as it were, would almost be routine and not thought of

01:32:22.060 --> 01:32:23.980
[Amit Varma]: as something that is a problem.

01:32:23.980 --> 01:32:27.820
[Amit Varma]: And at some level, of course, it is how unified is the voice of the film, that that film has

01:32:27.820 --> 01:32:31.540
[Amit Varma]: chosen one particular voice in this film might have chosen another particular voice.

01:32:31.540 --> 01:32:36.020
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, it is almost as if we look at these two different kinds of cinema

01:32:36.020 --> 01:32:41.140
[Amit Varma]: through a different set of values, like I love David Dhawan films, okay, you can judge

01:32:41.140 --> 01:32:43.620
[Amit Varma]: me for it in these times as well.

01:32:43.620 --> 01:32:46.180
[Amit Varma]: So I love David Dhawan films, but I also love Kieslowski.

01:32:46.180 --> 01:32:49.720
[Amit Varma]: But the point is a set of values through which I look at those films and the expectations

01:32:49.720 --> 01:32:54.620
[Amit Varma]: I have are completely different and of course, multitudes and all of that.

01:32:54.620 --> 01:32:57.540
[Amit Varma]: But I guess you could say that the reader also takes that for granted.

01:32:57.540 --> 01:33:00.700
[Amit Varma]: So you can't need to spell any of it out or just for it.

01:33:00.700 --> 01:33:08.580
[Guest]: No, no, what I'm really saying is, I suppose is that there isn't a particular way in which

01:33:08.580 --> 01:33:13.180
[Guest]: I experienced that shift, while, you know, moving from one type of film to another.

01:33:13.180 --> 01:33:14.180
[Guest]: I don't know what that means.

01:33:14.180 --> 01:33:17.260
[Guest]: I don't know what that says about me or my brain or whatever it is.

01:33:17.260 --> 01:33:23.340
[Guest]: But but but but I, and also, since you bring up moonlight, but there's one little point

01:33:23.340 --> 01:33:30.260
[Guest]: which which I think is, you know, might also go some way to might also be a reminder that

01:33:30.260 --> 01:33:33.660
[Guest]: there are so many different ways of loving the same film, right?

01:33:33.660 --> 01:33:35.940
[Guest]: And I know you love Moonlight.

01:33:35.940 --> 01:33:36.940
[Guest]: I loved it as well.

01:33:36.940 --> 01:33:43.820
[Guest]: I saw it on in the hall, but but some of the scenes that worked best for me in that film,

01:33:43.820 --> 01:33:50.180
[Guest]: I actually thought that the background music was, was, was very lush, almost.

01:33:50.180 --> 01:33:53.300
[Guest]: I don't know, you you probably didn't feel that way.

01:33:53.300 --> 01:33:57.820
[Guest]: I felt it was insistent in a very good way.

01:33:57.820 --> 01:34:04.260
[Guest]: I know it served as a sort of I wouldn't use a term like spoon feeding, but but it served

01:34:04.260 --> 01:34:09.020
[Guest]: as some sort of an emotional cue for me, especially in some of the dialogue less scenes like the

01:34:09.020 --> 01:34:13.500
[Guest]: one where the protagonist as you know, the one in the swimming pool, for instance, seems

01:34:13.500 --> 01:34:14.500
[Guest]: like that.

01:34:14.500 --> 01:34:21.340
[Guest]: I felt like my experience of the film was actually enhanced by the use of music, which

01:34:21.340 --> 01:34:24.180
[Guest]: which I didn't think of as particularly subtle music.

01:34:24.180 --> 01:34:26.700
[Guest]: I thought of it as cue providing in a way.

01:34:26.700 --> 01:34:29.860
[Guest]: Now I'm going to assume that you didn't feel the same way at all, even though you love

01:34:29.860 --> 01:34:31.340
[Guest]: the film as well.

01:34:31.340 --> 01:34:34.660
[Amit Varma]: So I you know, I have to say that I didn't notice it at all.

01:34:34.660 --> 01:34:38.300
[Amit Varma]: So number one, the fact that I didn't notice it is a good thing.

01:34:38.300 --> 01:34:41.340
[Amit Varma]: It means that it didn't draw attention to itself and all of that.

01:34:41.340 --> 01:34:46.180
[Amit Varma]: And secondly, I think like I told you, I think some of my views on this have changed slightly

01:34:46.180 --> 01:34:50.700
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that I now realize that all of cinema, every choice you make is in a sense

01:34:50.700 --> 01:34:54.660
[Amit Varma]: manipulating the viewer, whether it is to have a particular kind of music or to not

01:34:54.660 --> 01:34:56.040
[Amit Varma]: have that music.

01:34:56.040 --> 01:35:01.140
[Amit Varma]: So I am a little more open to these sort of things than I used to be once, where once

01:35:01.140 --> 01:35:03.940
[Amit Varma]: I was like, no, I don't want to be manipulated.

01:35:03.940 --> 01:35:08.540
[Amit Varma]: If there is a sad scene, do not play sad violin music, you know, do not play Chennai at this

01:35:08.540 --> 01:35:09.540
[Amit Varma]: time.

01:35:09.540 --> 01:35:14.340
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, in an action scene, you don't need to play action music, just let it happen.

01:35:14.340 --> 01:35:15.700
[Amit Varma]: Now I'm a little more relaxed.

01:35:15.700 --> 01:35:19.440
[Amit Varma]: I understand that in any case, it's a curated experience.

01:35:19.440 --> 01:35:24.740
[Amit Varma]: So you know, unless something is jarring and is detracting from that experience, let me

01:35:24.740 --> 01:35:28.260
[Amit Varma]: just sit back and enjoy the experience without sort of deconstructing it too much.

01:35:28.260 --> 01:35:29.260
[Amit Varma]: But I'm sorry.

01:35:29.260 --> 01:35:30.260
[Guest]: Continue.

01:35:30.260 --> 01:35:31.260
[Guest]: No, that's pretty much all I had to say.

01:35:31.260 --> 01:35:35.300
[Guest]: It was just, you know, that just a reminder, and there's something that, you know, when

01:35:35.300 --> 01:35:39.940
[Guest]: you're thinking in this nerdish way about not just about films, but also about the nuts

01:35:39.940 --> 01:35:45.540
[Guest]: and bolts of film appreciation, film criticism, you do think about these things about how,

01:35:45.540 --> 01:35:50.300
[Guest]: you know, you and I can go together in a post-COVID world, we can go into go into a hall together

01:35:50.300 --> 01:35:55.100
[Guest]: and watch a film together, come out gushing about it saying, dude, that was that was great.

01:35:55.100 --> 01:35:56.460
[Guest]: It was such a great film.

01:35:56.460 --> 01:36:00.540
[Guest]: And then we go and sit down and have coffee somewhere and start talking about the film.

01:36:00.540 --> 01:36:05.060
[Guest]: And then we realized that we liked completely different things in the film.

01:36:05.060 --> 01:36:09.540
[Guest]: And that maybe we disagreed about something very important, you know, the quality of a

01:36:09.540 --> 01:36:13.100
[Guest]: particular performance, maybe, maybe I thought the performance was the best thing in the

01:36:13.100 --> 01:36:15.300
[Guest]: film and made the film for me.

01:36:15.300 --> 01:36:18.740
[Guest]: You had reservations about the performance, but it wasn't anything like a deal breaker

01:36:18.740 --> 01:36:19.740
[Guest]: for you.

01:36:19.740 --> 01:36:22.980
[Guest]: So everything else in the film more than made up for it.

01:36:22.980 --> 01:36:27.500
[Guest]: So at the end of that coffee, we've actually discovered that we've had very different experiences

01:36:27.500 --> 01:36:28.500
[Guest]: of the film.

01:36:28.500 --> 01:36:32.020
[Guest]: But for each of us, it is a five star film.

01:36:32.020 --> 01:36:35.740
[Guest]: So just a little thing that, you know, that these are some of the conversations that come

01:36:35.740 --> 01:36:41.200
[Guest]: up the few occasions that I talk about these things with other movie lovers or with other

01:36:41.200 --> 01:36:45.620
[Guest]: professional film critics, that there's so many ways, it's very reductive to think that,

01:36:45.620 --> 01:36:51.060
[Guest]: oh, you know, person A and person B both love the same film, so their tastes match.

01:36:51.060 --> 01:36:55.620
[Guest]: It's not, it's not necessarily the case, it's that there's so many different ways of liking

01:36:55.620 --> 01:37:01.500
[Guest]: or not liking or being indifferent to a film, or a book or whatever.

01:37:01.500 --> 01:37:03.620
[Amit Varma]: And this leads me to a further thought about the discourse, right?

01:37:03.620 --> 01:37:07.460
[Amit Varma]: If this was to happen, let's say post COVID times, you can go watch a movie together.

01:37:07.460 --> 01:37:12.340
[Amit Varma]: What would be that conversation we would have about the film would further enrich the experience

01:37:12.340 --> 01:37:15.220
[Amit Varma]: of the film if we are receptive and listening to each other?

01:37:15.220 --> 01:37:18.660
[Amit Varma]: Because and you can see the film from my eyes later, and I can go back and I'll probably

01:37:18.660 --> 01:37:23.860
[Amit Varma]: whenever I watch Moonlight again, I'll, you know, I'll be more sort of mindful of these

01:37:23.860 --> 01:37:25.100
[Amit Varma]: things that you speak about.

01:37:25.100 --> 01:37:29.180
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that in much of our discourse, we don't have that receptiveness anymore.

01:37:29.180 --> 01:37:32.940
[Amit Varma]: Much of our discourse is where you take a hardened position, that this is what I feel

01:37:32.940 --> 01:37:37.260
[Amit Varma]: and everyone else who disagrees with me has a character flaw that they are stupid or they

01:37:37.260 --> 01:37:39.060
[Amit Varma]: are evil or they are whatever.

01:37:39.060 --> 01:37:42.620
[Amit Varma]: And so much of our discourse has become like that a little less on cinema.

01:37:42.620 --> 01:37:46.340
[Amit Varma]: But even on cinema, as you pointed out, you've written in the past about, you know, when

01:37:46.340 --> 01:37:49.380
[Amit Varma]: you would write a bad review of something, somebody else would say, how could you not

01:37:49.380 --> 01:37:50.380
[Amit Varma]: like that?

01:37:50.380 --> 01:37:54.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, you weren't being objective, whereas you pointed out objective means, you know,

01:37:54.260 --> 01:37:55.660
[Amit Varma]: you should agree with me.

01:37:55.660 --> 01:38:02.020
[Amit Varma]: So just a kind of a point about the discourse, one of the ways in which you see these two

01:38:02.020 --> 01:38:08.220
[Amit Varma]: words colliding these two, almost these different philosophies, and I'll still speak of it in

01:38:08.220 --> 01:38:09.220
[Amit Varma]: dichotomous terms.

01:38:09.220 --> 01:38:12.900
[Amit Varma]: Although I buy your point that there's an intermingling, is say in a film like Piku.

01:38:12.900 --> 01:38:17.220
[Amit Varma]: Now, you've mentioned Piku in the past in the context of acting where some people, you

01:38:17.220 --> 01:38:20.980
[Amit Varma]: know, appreciated Deepika's, quote unquote, understated performance there and you pointed

01:38:20.980 --> 01:38:23.940
[Amit Varma]: out that no, she's been good in so many other films.

01:38:23.940 --> 01:38:27.620
[Amit Varma]: But it is only you know, why are we applying this particular lens or this particular value

01:38:27.620 --> 01:38:29.260
[Amit Varma]: and saying she's good in this.

01:38:29.260 --> 01:38:35.300
[Amit Varma]: But I also thought of Piku as showcasing these two forms coming together in terms of the

01:38:35.300 --> 01:38:42.340
[Amit Varma]: way Amitabh and Irrfan acted, where I thought Irrfan was sadly, just an incredibly great

01:38:42.340 --> 01:38:44.580
[Amit Varma]: actor by any standard.

01:38:44.580 --> 01:38:48.620
[Amit Varma]: And you know, while Amitabh, like in that film, I thought Irrfan's acting was superb

01:38:48.620 --> 01:38:50.500
[Amit Varma]: and Amitabh was just hamming it up.

01:38:50.500 --> 01:38:54.580
[Amit Varma]: And it was classic Bollywood and you have made these categories of actor and star actor.

01:38:54.580 --> 01:38:58.100
[Amit Varma]: And he's basically just been a star actor all the way through and he's been extremely

01:38:58.100 --> 01:38:59.100
[Amit Varma]: good.

01:38:59.100 --> 01:39:01.420
[Amit Varma]: So no value judgment there, per se.

01:39:01.420 --> 01:39:06.500
[Amit Varma]: But you sort of see these two different schools of acting come together where Irrfan is just

01:39:06.500 --> 01:39:08.340
[Amit Varma]: living, breathing the character.

01:39:08.340 --> 01:39:12.300
[Amit Varma]: And Amitabh is just hamming, it's just, you know, not good acting in my book.

01:39:12.300 --> 01:39:17.580
[Amit Varma]: But that is, of course, through, you know, my sort of biased lens, Amitabh in his own

01:39:17.580 --> 01:39:21.700
[Amit Varma]: context, he's a great, great actor that hardly needs to be elaborated upon.

01:39:21.700 --> 01:39:23.900
[Guest]: Can I interrupt for a second?

01:39:23.900 --> 01:39:24.900
[Guest]: Yeah, sure.

01:39:24.900 --> 01:39:29.020
[Guest]: Probably make a habit of just riffing on what the other is saying.

01:39:29.020 --> 01:39:35.420
[Guest]: I actually wrote another piece once, which you probably haven't read, explaining why

01:39:35.420 --> 01:39:39.020
[Guest]: I was very moved by Bachchan's performance in Pico.

01:39:39.020 --> 01:39:44.140
[Guest]: And in fact, I've spoken about this also recently in a class because I, you know, most of the

01:39:44.140 --> 01:39:49.060
[Guest]: people I know, which of course says something about the circles, again, that I tend to associate

01:39:49.060 --> 01:39:53.940
[Guest]: with, share your view of the Bachchan performance as being an exercise in hamming.

01:39:53.940 --> 01:39:57.620
[Guest]: And of course, a lot of these people, a lot of the people who hold this view also happen

01:39:57.620 --> 01:40:03.980
[Guest]: to be Bengalis, who think that this is a stereotypical depiction of the Bengali.

01:40:03.980 --> 01:40:08.900
[Guest]: Now, of course, I, at risk of being very politically incorrect here, I have to say that speaking

01:40:08.900 --> 01:40:15.140
[Guest]: as a North Indian who has experienced a lot of real world Bengalis as stereotypes, I had

01:40:15.140 --> 01:40:20.420
[Guest]: no trouble at all buying into Bachchan's performance.

01:40:20.420 --> 01:40:24.660
[Guest]: And I think perhaps, you know, a lot of defensive Bengalis are perhaps not the best people to

01:40:24.660 --> 01:40:26.260
[Guest]: be making that judgment.

01:40:26.260 --> 01:40:30.540
[Amit Varma]: But you know, I'm half wrong, but that is not my criticism at all.

01:40:30.540 --> 01:40:31.540
[Guest]: I don't care about that.

01:40:31.540 --> 01:40:32.540
[Guest]: I'm not saying it is.

01:40:32.540 --> 01:40:37.860
[Guest]: But yeah, there are many others who most people I know, in fact, in the, in the, you know,

01:40:37.860 --> 01:40:43.940
[Guest]: the film writers world, the writers world, even if they didn't really, even if they weren't

01:40:43.940 --> 01:40:49.380
[Guest]: bold enough to say it in their reviews, thought Bachchan was not very good in the film, hamming

01:40:49.380 --> 01:40:51.020
[Guest]: etc, etc.

01:40:51.020 --> 01:40:54.820
[Guest]: But this actually leads me to a talking point that might be relevant to something that we

01:40:54.820 --> 01:41:02.020
[Guest]: were discussing earlier as well about how our personal experiences often illuminate

01:41:02.020 --> 01:41:08.780
[Guest]: or help us make sense of certain things or infect how we receive films or performances.

01:41:08.780 --> 01:41:13.620
[Guest]: The reason why Bachchan's performance really worked for me, and, in fact, just sort of,

01:41:13.620 --> 01:41:19.460
[Guest]: you know, moved me in a way that I just, you know, again, had a hard time articulating

01:41:19.460 --> 01:41:22.700
[Guest]: was because there were these little moments in the performance and I'm not even talking

01:41:22.700 --> 01:41:27.340
[Guest]: about the performance in its entirety, but there were these little moments in the performance

01:41:27.340 --> 01:41:32.420
[Guest]: that speaking as someone who has spent a lot of time, either caregiving himself in the

01:41:32.420 --> 01:41:40.580
[Guest]: last few years, or witnessing caregiving in the context of my nanny's final battle with

01:41:40.580 --> 01:41:45.300
[Guest]: cancer and my mother looking after her and my mother who's also a very introverted person

01:41:45.300 --> 01:41:50.060
[Guest]: just putting her life on hold and, and having to deal with this parent who was a completely

01:41:50.060 --> 01:41:55.420
[Guest]: different personality type, who wanted to bully her daughter, but was also very scared

01:41:55.420 --> 01:41:58.460
[Guest]: about her condition and I knew that she was dependent on her daughter.

01:41:58.460 --> 01:42:03.580
[Guest]: So you have that combination of wanting to exercise hegemony as this very extroverted,

01:42:03.580 --> 01:42:10.860
[Guest]: you know, boisterous person, but also being very scared and nervous, that I shouldn't

01:42:10.860 --> 01:42:17.180
[Guest]: say something that will get Mala upset, Mala is my mother, and I saw this look in my nanny's

01:42:17.180 --> 01:42:24.700
[Guest]: eyes so often, you know, in 2007, 2008, 2009, when the cancer period was going on.

01:42:24.700 --> 01:42:30.220
[Guest]: And I saw exactly that same look, you know, in some scenes in Piku where, where Deepika

01:42:30.220 --> 01:42:34.060
[Guest]: just sort of loses it, where the Bachchan character is being, you know, he's being difficult

01:42:34.060 --> 01:42:38.220
[Guest]: and, and the daughter loses it and she starts shouting at him or just sort of say something.

01:42:38.220 --> 01:42:42.620
[Guest]: And then you know, there's you either see him in, in, in a direct shot or in as part

01:42:42.620 --> 01:42:49.340
[Guest]: of a larger scene, the way he's looking at her, just, you know, it just felt so truthful

01:42:49.340 --> 01:42:55.100
[Guest]: to me, it just reminded me exactly of, of that, of that look in my nanny's eyes, looking

01:42:55.100 --> 01:42:59.900
[Guest]: at my mother, and I just felt like this, this guy's captured something about, about this

01:42:59.900 --> 01:43:05.420
[Guest]: personality type being in this situation being, being looked after by a child, and, and, and

01:43:05.420 --> 01:43:09.020
[Guest]: becoming the child who is being looked after by his child.

01:43:09.020 --> 01:43:13.260
[Guest]: So it worked for me, purely in that at that level, I mean, I mean, I'm absolutely fine

01:43:13.260 --> 01:43:16.140
[Guest]: with with people saying that the performance felt hammy or whatever.

01:43:16.140 --> 01:43:19.900
[Guest]: And, and of course, you know, there are so many different ways of judging these things,

01:43:19.900 --> 01:43:23.980
[Guest]: your feelings about a performance will also be again, I'm not talking about you, but but

01:43:23.980 --> 01:43:27.900
[Guest]: some other people's feelings about the performance might be affected by the fact that he won

01:43:27.900 --> 01:43:29.420
[Guest]: a national award for it.

01:43:29.420 --> 01:43:31.300
[Guest]: He was given a national award for it.

01:43:31.300 --> 01:43:35.420
[Guest]: So then people will look at the film with that level of expectation.

01:43:35.420 --> 01:43:39.580
[Guest]: And then they'll say, listen, Irrfan is so much better, and he's, you know, it's such

01:43:39.580 --> 01:43:42.740
[Guest]: a natural, you know, you barely register that he's acting.

01:43:42.740 --> 01:43:46.140
[Guest]: And here's this old man who's just hamming it up in every scene, and he got a national

01:43:46.140 --> 01:43:47.140
[Guest]: award for hamming.

01:43:47.140 --> 01:43:50.780
[Guest]: So people will, will also look at it from that point of view.

01:43:50.780 --> 01:43:53.860
[Guest]: But I had a very personal response to the performance.

01:43:53.860 --> 01:43:57.780
[Guest]: And I enjoyed it for that reason.

01:43:57.780 --> 01:43:59.220
[Amit Varma]: This is kind of fascinating.

01:43:59.220 --> 01:44:02.700
[Amit Varma]: If I ever come across Piku running anywhere on TV, because I don't think I'll go out of

01:44:02.700 --> 01:44:06.700
[Amit Varma]: my way to watch it, but if I come across it running anywhere, I will watch out for this

01:44:06.700 --> 01:44:08.340
[Amit Varma]: no seriously with an open mind.

01:44:08.340 --> 01:44:11.300
[Amit Varma]: There's this delightful quote in one of your pieces, in fact, which I linked from the show

01:44:11.300 --> 01:44:15.660
[Amit Varma]: notes where you quote Subhash Ghai, when he's asked about, you know, Meryl Streep and Susan

01:44:15.660 --> 01:44:18.660
[Amit Varma]: Sarandon, do we have actresses like that in India?

01:44:18.660 --> 01:44:23.780
[Amit Varma]: And he said, quote, can they dance as convincingly as Madhuri Dixit does?

01:44:23.780 --> 01:44:27.460
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote, which is, of course, a lovely way of looking at it.

01:44:27.460 --> 01:44:33.860
[Amit Varma]: But let's let's kind of now go back to talking about the personal journey and and let's sort

01:44:33.860 --> 01:44:39.220
[Amit Varma]: of come to blogging, like one of the reasons blogging was significant for me as a writer,

01:44:39.220 --> 01:44:40.620
[Amit Varma]: it was significant in various ways.

01:44:40.620 --> 01:44:45.220
[Amit Varma]: But like you, I had a conventional journalism job where I wrote conventional pieces in conventional

01:44:45.220 --> 01:44:49.300
[Amit Varma]: formats and blogging was different because of all the, you know, standard reasons you

01:44:49.300 --> 01:44:54.180
[Amit Varma]: and I know that number one, you are not restricted by format, you can do 80 words or 8000 words,

01:44:54.180 --> 01:44:59.220
[Amit Varma]: you don't have to do 800, you're not restricted by, say, the news cycle, you don't have to

01:44:59.220 --> 01:45:02.100
[Amit Varma]: write about what is topical, you can write about anything, you're not constrained by

01:45:02.100 --> 01:45:03.380
[Amit Varma]: house style.

01:45:03.380 --> 01:45:07.580
[Amit Varma]: And in a certain sense, you aren't constrained by anxiety as well, because, you know, one

01:45:07.580 --> 01:45:11.780
[Amit Varma]: of the things that often stops writers or gets in the way is their anxiety of what other

01:45:11.780 --> 01:45:13.540
[Amit Varma]: people think of them.

01:45:13.540 --> 01:45:16.820
[Amit Varma]: My approach initially as a blogger was I'm just blogging, who gives a who's gonna read

01:45:16.820 --> 01:45:21.480
[Amit Varma]: it, you know, and you get into that groove where that self consciousness kind of goes.

01:45:21.480 --> 01:45:25.260
[Amit Varma]: And all of these together came to being something liberating.

01:45:25.260 --> 01:45:30.360
[Amit Varma]: And in my newsletter, I had an essay about this, about form and content.

01:45:30.360 --> 01:45:36.980
[Amit Varma]: And also in the context of, you know, the podcast, where my postulation is that doing

01:45:36.980 --> 01:45:41.260
[Amit Varma]: a three hour podcast, as opposed to a 10 minute podcast means I'm having a completely different

01:45:41.260 --> 01:45:45.580
[Amit Varma]: kind of conversation, I have to delve that much deeper, I have to do that much more research,

01:45:45.580 --> 01:45:49.380
[Amit Varma]: I have to respect the guest that much more, I have to be that much more patient, I have

01:45:49.380 --> 01:45:52.280
[Amit Varma]: to listen, genuinely listen that much more.

01:45:52.280 --> 01:45:56.140
[Amit Varma]: And all of this affects who I am as a person and changes me in subtle ways, especially

01:45:56.140 --> 01:45:58.020
[Amit Varma]: if I'm doing it for a period of years.

01:45:58.020 --> 01:46:02.700
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, in blogging, I think it shaped my writing because throwing away all these

01:46:02.700 --> 01:46:08.760
[Amit Varma]: restrictions and not having to write to the expectations of an editor, or an audience

01:46:08.760 --> 01:46:14.060
[Amit Varma]: just allowed me to branch out in all kinds of different directions and all of that.

01:46:14.060 --> 01:46:18.540
[Amit Varma]: And I think that at the end of that period, when like I wrote 8000 posts over five years,

01:46:18.540 --> 01:46:22.820
[Amit Varma]: I would do five posts a day, as you know, on average, I think my record was 18 posts

01:46:22.820 --> 01:46:23.820
[Amit Varma]: in a day.

01:46:23.820 --> 01:46:27.980
[Amit Varma]: So I was, you know, great writing gym for me getting a lot of writing done without realizing

01:46:27.980 --> 01:46:29.560
[Amit Varma]: it or thinking of it that way.

01:46:29.560 --> 01:46:33.500
[Amit Varma]: But I do feel that it kind of, it changed the work I did, it changed, therefore it changed

01:46:33.500 --> 01:46:36.620
[Amit Varma]: the way I thought, because the imperatives were different, and it changed the person

01:46:36.620 --> 01:46:37.620
[Amit Varma]: I am.

01:46:37.620 --> 01:46:41.780
[Amit Varma]: Like I genuinely think that, if anything, and this is, of course, in a relative sense,

01:46:41.780 --> 01:46:45.620
[Amit Varma]: but the podcast has made me a better person, because I listen more, and I'm more open,

01:46:45.620 --> 01:46:47.320
[Amit Varma]: and I'm more sort of whatever.

01:46:47.320 --> 01:46:50.860
[Amit Varma]: So what did blogging mean to you in that sense?

01:46:50.860 --> 01:46:55.580
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, this is only in hindsight at the time one never knows, but how did it shape

01:46:55.580 --> 01:46:56.580
[Amit Varma]: you?

01:46:56.580 --> 01:46:57.580
[Amit Varma]: How did it shape your writing?

01:46:57.580 --> 01:46:59.980
[Amit Varma]: How did it shape the way you looked at cinema?

01:46:59.980 --> 01:47:03.900
[Amit Varma]: Because before this cinema in our newspapers was cheso word ka review, you have to talk

01:47:03.900 --> 01:47:07.640
[Amit Varma]: about plot, you have to give a verdict, you have to give a star rating, and that's it.

01:47:07.640 --> 01:47:12.860
[Amit Varma]: But now suddenly, you're writing personal essays, you're writing stray observations.

01:47:12.860 --> 01:47:13.860
[Amit Varma]: What was it like?

01:47:13.860 --> 01:47:19.940
[Guest]: No, well, first of all, you're being very kind when you say 600 words in mainstream

01:47:19.940 --> 01:47:24.340
[Guest]: publications, it was closer to 300 or 400.

01:47:24.340 --> 01:47:31.300
[Guest]: I had worked for an India Today tabloid in my first job in journalism, and, and I of

01:47:31.300 --> 01:47:36.020
[Guest]: course, that was a very small 16 page publication.

01:47:36.020 --> 01:47:40.740
[Guest]: But the reviews, I would do book reviews or film reviews were never more than 350-400

01:47:40.740 --> 01:47:41.740
[Guest]: words.

01:47:41.740 --> 01:47:47.220
[Guest]: It was far from the ideal way of doing it, but when you're that young, you will have

01:47:47.220 --> 01:47:52.460
[Guest]: a boss coming up to you in the middle of the many other things you have to do in a day,

01:47:52.460 --> 01:47:57.300
[Guest]: and just sort of tossing a book at you and saying, yeah, it is a 400 page book, and saying

01:47:57.300 --> 01:48:01.420
[Guest]: iska kal review de dena, give the review by tomorrow.

01:48:01.420 --> 01:48:05.060
[Guest]: And that, of course, just just tells you the first message that gives you as a young journalist

01:48:05.060 --> 01:48:08.660
[Guest]: is that reviewing is not taken seriously, it's not something to be taken seriously is

01:48:08.660 --> 01:48:13.860
[Guest]: not considered a form in its own right, it's not considered something that can be good

01:48:13.860 --> 01:48:19.460
[Guest]: writing or good thinking in its own right, it's just something that you just do, anybody

01:48:19.460 --> 01:48:20.460
[Guest]: can do it.

01:48:20.460 --> 01:48:24.780
[Guest]: What's important anyway, is the star rating that you go with your piece, because that's

01:48:24.780 --> 01:48:31.060
[Guest]: what the vast majority of readers, including my mother, by the way, would look at, even

01:48:31.060 --> 01:48:36.300
[Guest]: after after I was writing as, even after I started doing film pieces myself, my mother

01:48:36.300 --> 01:48:42.820
[Guest]: would still be looking at the Times of India piece to see what the star rating was.

01:48:42.820 --> 01:48:47.460
[Guest]: So of course, working purely for mainstream publications as a journalist at that time,

01:48:47.460 --> 01:48:52.620
[Guest]: and possibly even at this time, at the current time, just meant that you're not, you don't

01:48:52.620 --> 01:48:58.620
[Guest]: have the tools to take yourself very seriously as a reviewer, or as a critic, or to think

01:48:58.620 --> 01:49:03.620
[Guest]: of it as something that requires rigor, or think of a review as something that can be

01:49:03.620 --> 01:49:07.020
[Guest]: well written, well articulated, that can be a personal thing.

01:49:07.020 --> 01:49:12.020
[Guest]: And of course, pretty much everything you said about blogging applies to me too, except

01:49:12.020 --> 01:49:19.140
[Guest]: that I might, I don't know if it would be completely truthful to say that I didn't feel

01:49:19.140 --> 01:49:25.140
[Guest]: any peer pressure at all, or any burden of expectations, because I think the time probably

01:49:25.140 --> 01:49:26.140
[Guest]: did arrive.

01:49:26.140 --> 01:49:32.020
[Guest]: I can't really think of any specific cases just now, but a point did arrive when after

01:49:32.020 --> 01:49:38.700
[Guest]: the blog became widely read, you know, during that, that heady period of 2004, 2005, 2006,

01:49:38.700 --> 01:49:43.580
[Guest]: before social media had come along before there was all this clutter on the internet,

01:49:43.580 --> 01:49:45.580
[Guest]: and blogs were still being read quite widely.

01:49:45.580 --> 01:49:49.300
[Guest]: And, and as you might know, one of the reasons why it became possible for me to become a

01:49:49.300 --> 01:49:54.340
[Guest]: freelance writer and an independent writer working from home, working for multiple publications

01:49:54.340 --> 01:49:59.220
[Guest]: was because I was getting job offers from other publications based purely on the blog

01:49:59.220 --> 01:50:04.500
[Guest]: writing, not on my writing in Business Standard where I was working at the time.

01:50:04.500 --> 01:50:10.560
[Guest]: So it was a very heady time and once you became aware that senior editors and different publications

01:50:10.560 --> 01:50:16.820
[Guest]: know Jabberwock, know your blog Jabberwock, and obviously somewhere you start becoming

01:50:16.820 --> 01:50:18.180
[Guest]: a little self conscious.

01:50:18.180 --> 01:50:25.300
[Guest]: I think that did happen to me somewhere, I became a little nervous as well.

01:50:25.300 --> 01:50:27.900
[Guest]: But I don't think it happened to a great degree.

01:50:27.900 --> 01:50:31.980
[Guest]: I don't think it happened, it happened to a crippling degree where the writing became

01:50:31.980 --> 01:50:35.780
[Guest]: a chore or became more difficult to pull off.

01:50:35.780 --> 01:50:40.940
[Guest]: And ultimately, of course, what happened was that to more directly answer your question,

01:50:40.940 --> 01:50:44.860
[Guest]: what it did for me, in addition to what you said yourself about just giving you a space

01:50:44.860 --> 01:50:50.260
[Guest]: where you could write an 80,000 word piece if you wanted to hypothetically, or definitely

01:50:50.260 --> 01:50:57.220
[Guest]: a 1500 word, 2000 word piece on a particular aspect of a book or a film, rather than a

01:50:57.220 --> 01:51:02.420
[Guest]: holistic review, or a holistic structured review of the book or the film, just something

01:51:02.420 --> 01:51:08.340
[Guest]: whimsical, but detailed at the same time, obviously, that the blogging format did that

01:51:08.340 --> 01:51:09.340
[Guest]: for me.

01:51:09.340 --> 01:51:12.700
[Guest]: But also what it did was because at the time, like I said, I was working for Business Standard

01:51:12.700 --> 01:51:17.760
[Guest]: newspaper, I had started doing a few book reviews for them for the edit page.

01:51:17.760 --> 01:51:21.700
[Guest]: But mostly what I was doing at that time was still this very corporate writing, I was doing

01:51:21.700 --> 01:51:25.740
[Guest]: these corporate stories on the watch industry, on the jewelry industry, whatever stuff that

01:51:25.740 --> 01:51:28.380
[Guest]: I wasn't genuinely interested in.

01:51:28.380 --> 01:51:34.020
[Guest]: And because prior to that, the only film reviews or the only book reviews I had written were

01:51:34.020 --> 01:51:39.540
[Guest]: for that tabloid that I mentioned 300 word spaces, 400 word spaces, I perhaps lacked

01:51:39.540 --> 01:51:45.860
[Guest]: the confidence that I could do this, you know, in a in a proper consolidated way in the long

01:51:45.860 --> 01:51:46.860
[Guest]: format.

01:51:46.860 --> 01:51:50.460
[Guest]: And what the blog did for me was especially when when the blog post started getting a

01:51:50.460 --> 01:52:00.300
[Guest]: good response, was that it told me that, yes, I could write a 1500 word piece about a film

01:52:00.300 --> 01:52:03.900
[Guest]: or a film essay that was appreciated by other people.

01:52:03.900 --> 01:52:07.620
[Guest]: And that therefore my sensibility, you know, struck a chord for other people.

01:52:07.620 --> 01:52:12.740
[Guest]: It told me that and that gave me the confidence that I needed to ultimately go on and write

01:52:12.740 --> 01:52:15.540
[Guest]: longer pieces for official publication.

01:52:15.540 --> 01:52:20.500
[Guest]: You if you remember, a little more than 10 years ago, you gave me a column space for

01:52:20.500 --> 01:52:23.860
[Guest]: Yahoo, which again, a lot, you know, what was the sort of space where I could write

01:52:23.860 --> 01:52:24.860
[Guest]: longish pieces.

01:52:24.860 --> 01:52:29.260
[Guest]: Now, again, without the blog having happened a few years before that, I might not have

01:52:29.260 --> 01:52:35.860
[Guest]: had the confidence to to write officially published pieces for payment for writers like

01:52:35.860 --> 01:52:41.340
[Guest]: Amit Verma and Prem Panekar, who I admired, that I might not have had that confidence

01:52:41.340 --> 01:52:44.620
[Guest]: without the validation provided by the blog.

01:52:44.620 --> 01:52:45.700
[Guest]: So that's really it.

01:52:45.700 --> 01:52:54.380
[Guest]: I think, you know, finding one's voice, feeling like it was sustainable to to write

01:52:54.380 --> 01:52:59.860
[Guest]: longish pieces about cinema or literature or whatever, and that it would make some sense

01:52:59.860 --> 01:53:00.860
[Guest]: to someone.

01:53:00.860 --> 01:53:03.300
[Guest]: That's what it was about.

01:53:03.300 --> 01:53:08.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, for my listeners, I used to be a consulting editor at Yahoo briefly, I basically put together

01:53:08.260 --> 01:53:13.260
[Amit Varma]: and ran a column section for them, which included columns by among other people, Jai Arjun Singh.

01:53:13.260 --> 01:53:19.260
[Amit Varma]: And I think you used to alternate with Sanjay Sipahi Malani on books, another sort of fantastic

01:53:19.260 --> 01:53:22.820
[Amit Varma]: writer, the two of you were my sort of art and culture people.

01:53:22.820 --> 01:53:26.460
[Amit Varma]: And we had others for politics and society and this and that.

01:53:26.460 --> 01:53:29.820
[Amit Varma]: No, I'm going back to, you know, the similar process that happened to you where you said

01:53:29.820 --> 01:53:33.460
[Amit Varma]: that people started taking your film writing seriously because of the blog.

01:53:33.460 --> 01:53:36.660
[Amit Varma]: And a similar process happened with me in the sense that look, I was I used to work

01:53:36.660 --> 01:53:38.740
[Amit Varma]: at Cricket Info, I used to write in cricket.

01:53:38.740 --> 01:53:42.340
[Amit Varma]: But because of the blog where I wrote about everything, I got that column in Mint for

01:53:42.340 --> 01:53:46.420
[Amit Varma]: which I won the Bastia Prize, I used to write regularly for the Wall Street Journal back

01:53:46.420 --> 01:53:47.420
[Amit Varma]: in the day.

01:53:47.420 --> 01:53:50.020
[Amit Varma]: So everything kind of came from there, though none of that was intended.

01:53:50.020 --> 01:53:54.420
[Amit Varma]: And the happiest writing I did was actually for the blog itself, because absolutely no

01:53:54.420 --> 01:53:59.020
[Amit Varma]: limitations and the other way in which it helped me and which is why I advise people

01:53:59.020 --> 01:54:02.180
[Amit Varma]: today to start a blog or a newsletter because blogs are kind of dead.

01:54:02.180 --> 01:54:08.940
[Amit Varma]: But something is is that you're writing regularly that iteration matters, you're writing repeatedly,

01:54:08.940 --> 01:54:13.260
[Amit Varma]: hopefully without self-consciousness, and that iteration just matters, not just in making

01:54:13.260 --> 01:54:20.700
[Amit Varma]: you a better writer and polishing the craft, but also it kind of makes you a better thinker.

01:54:20.700 --> 01:54:25.220
[Amit Varma]: Now, my next question is this that at this time, you're writing about films.

01:54:25.220 --> 01:54:29.140
[Amit Varma]: And one aspect of writing about films that we discussed is that it makes you look deeper

01:54:29.140 --> 01:54:34.300
[Amit Varma]: at films, that you no longer have that intuitive or that initial or that visceral reaction

01:54:34.300 --> 01:54:38.220
[Amit Varma]: to a film, you actually have to think about it, figure out what you want to write about

01:54:38.220 --> 01:54:41.760
[Amit Varma]: it, go deeper into that aspect of yourself and all of that.

01:54:41.760 --> 01:54:46.140
[Amit Varma]: But it strikes me that there's another danger and the danger is taking this too far of looking

01:54:46.140 --> 01:54:50.220
[Amit Varma]: for significance where there is none, because you have to have something to write about

01:54:50.220 --> 01:54:53.640
[Amit Varma]: almost a risk of over analysis, as it were.

01:54:53.640 --> 01:54:57.980
[Amit Varma]: And in your self deprecatory way, you've pointed out one example of this in the past, I think

01:54:57.980 --> 01:55:02.900
[Amit Varma]: in a TEDx talk you gave, where you spoke about the scene from Jaane Bhi Do Yaaro, you know,

01:55:02.900 --> 01:55:06.420
[Amit Varma]: where everybody is sort of silhouetted, they go up this building and they're silhouetted

01:55:06.420 --> 01:55:10.100
[Amit Varma]: and in the sky and, you know, these guys are just silhouettes.

01:55:10.100 --> 01:55:15.220
[Amit Varma]: And you spoke about how this sort of seemed to be symbolic of their Kale Karname.

01:55:15.220 --> 01:55:18.340
[Amit Varma]: But when you mentioned it to Kundan Shah, the director, he said, Oh, Jai, you're being

01:55:18.340 --> 01:55:19.340
[Amit Varma]: a critic again.

01:55:19.340 --> 01:55:20.340
[Amit Varma]: Aisa kuch nahi hai.

01:55:20.340 --> 01:55:23.420
[Amit Varma]: You know, and I'm reminded about this, and I try to watch out for it in myself when I

01:55:23.420 --> 01:55:25.600
[Amit Varma]: write about books or films.

01:55:25.600 --> 01:55:28.980
[Amit Varma]: Because critics do tend to do this, like I remember one of my favorite films as a kid

01:55:28.980 --> 01:55:33.820
[Amit Varma]: growing up, because I saw it at that age when it is likely to appeal to people of that age

01:55:33.820 --> 01:55:36.580
[Amit Varma]: was the Peter Weir film, Dead Poets Society.

01:55:36.580 --> 01:55:41.460
[Amit Varma]: And a couple of years later, my dad got one of these foreign film magazines where I read

01:55:41.460 --> 01:55:46.540
[Amit Varma]: someone talking about Dead Poets Society, about having all these homoerotic overtones

01:55:46.540 --> 01:55:52.780
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, which I was completely sure is just way over interpreting what it actually

01:55:52.780 --> 01:55:55.980
[Amit Varma]: was, you know, reading far more into a story than you need to.

01:55:55.980 --> 01:55:58.940
[Amit Varma]: So is this something that you felt that you had to watch out for?

01:55:58.940 --> 01:56:01.020
[Amit Varma]: Do you think you ever crossed the line?

01:56:01.020 --> 01:56:04.700
[Amit Varma]: You know, would you know when you cross the line, because at some level, obviously, everything

01:56:04.700 --> 01:56:05.700
[Amit Varma]: is subjective.

01:56:05.700 --> 01:56:09.740
[Amit Varma]: And you can only speak about how the film affects you and what it means to you.

01:56:09.740 --> 01:56:14.500
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, there is a risk of kind of going too far reading into the film things

01:56:14.500 --> 01:56:19.860
[Amit Varma]: that the director never intended or just weren't there just because you know, that's a fascinating

01:56:19.860 --> 01:56:21.020
[Amit Varma]: narrative for you.

01:56:21.020 --> 01:56:22.620
[Amit Varma]: So is this something you've thought about?

01:56:22.620 --> 01:56:26.500
[Amit Varma]: Do you look back on some of the earlier stuff you've done and say that, hey, no, no, that

01:56:26.500 --> 01:56:27.500
[Amit Varma]: was that that was wrong?

01:56:27.500 --> 01:56:30.500
[Amit Varma]: Or, you know, I overthought that?

01:56:30.500 --> 01:56:33.580
[Guest]: You know, the short answer to that would be no, I don't.

01:56:33.580 --> 01:56:39.780
[Guest]: And I have to say this, what the director in consciously intended or what a novelist

01:56:39.780 --> 01:56:45.260
[Guest]: consciously intended, you know, should be completely irrelevant to a good critic anyway.

01:56:45.260 --> 01:56:49.380
[Guest]: It's not something that I mean, I'm firmly with again, come to another cliche, but, but

01:56:49.380 --> 01:56:54.780
[Guest]: I, you know, firmly believe in D. H. Lawrence's dictum about trusting the artist, trusting

01:56:54.780 --> 01:56:55.780
[Guest]: the tale.

01:56:55.780 --> 01:57:00.780
[Guest]: Now, the thing is, that example you provided, wo jaane bhi toh yaaro by the way, there was

01:57:00.780 --> 01:57:04.780
[Guest]: actually a follow up to it, which I think maybe maybe you don't know about, or maybe

01:57:04.780 --> 01:57:09.420
[Guest]: I don't remember if I put it, it may not have been in the book, but but I think I may have

01:57:09.420 --> 01:57:10.420
[Guest]: written it elsewhere.

01:57:10.420 --> 01:57:17.140
[Guest]: When I spoke with Dinodh Pradhan, the DOP of the film, later, may even have been after

01:57:17.140 --> 01:57:20.940
[Guest]: I did the book, or I can't remember the exact sequence of events.

01:57:20.940 --> 01:57:25.660
[Guest]: He actually told me that, you know, though, of course, the fact that the scene was shot

01:57:25.660 --> 01:57:30.100
[Guest]: in that particular way, that silhouetted way, where the four villains, the four conspirators

01:57:30.100 --> 01:57:34.420
[Guest]: are, you see them in the shadowy sort of way, the fact that it was done was was first and

01:57:34.420 --> 01:57:38.660
[Guest]: foremost, because they had run out of time, and they only had that had the top of that

01:57:38.660 --> 01:57:42.060
[Guest]: building for for a certain amount of time.

01:57:42.060 --> 01:57:45.940
[Guest]: But Dinodh Pradhan also said that, you know, but but you know, when we found ourselves

01:57:45.940 --> 01:57:48.660
[Guest]: with this constraint, I went up to Kundan and said, listen, but you know, this would

01:57:48.660 --> 01:57:54.660
[Guest]: actually make for for quite a nice atmospheric shot, given, given the black deeds that are

01:57:54.660 --> 01:57:57.740
[Guest]: being, you know, being being discussed out here.

01:57:57.740 --> 01:58:01.420
[Guest]: And you know, I did sort of, and he said this, Dinodh said this independently of my having

01:58:01.420 --> 01:58:04.700
[Guest]: brought up anything in terms of interpretation.

01:58:04.700 --> 01:58:06.160
[Guest]: So that is one thing.

01:58:06.160 --> 01:58:10.820
[Guest]: Having said that, even if he hadn't said it, even if Dinodh Pradhan hadn't provided this

01:58:10.820 --> 01:58:16.380
[Guest]: counter narrative to what Kundan provided, and I should also specify that Kundan himself,

01:58:16.380 --> 01:58:22.220
[Guest]: though he he was very snarky with me at various times, snarky in a nice way, in a way that

01:58:22.220 --> 01:58:27.260
[Guest]: a creative person often is with with an impudent young critic who is who is trying to read

01:58:27.260 --> 01:58:31.700
[Guest]: a lot of things and do his work, because creative people do tend to feel be very proprietary

01:58:31.700 --> 01:58:36.860
[Guest]: about what they have done, they tend to feel like, they need to have full control over

01:58:36.860 --> 01:58:37.860
[Guest]: it.

01:58:37.860 --> 01:58:41.980
[Guest]: And therefore, other other other interpretations that they did not consciously intend are a

01:58:41.980 --> 01:58:42.980
[Guest]: problem.

01:58:42.980 --> 01:58:47.220
[Guest]: Everything should just be there many, many creative people are like that.

01:58:47.220 --> 01:58:51.420
[Guest]: Even Kundan, in a more relaxed frame of mind did subsequently say to me, yeah, but you

01:58:51.420 --> 01:58:56.060
[Guest]: know, listen, it's as a critic, it is your job to find your interpretations and to look

01:58:56.060 --> 01:58:57.460
[Guest]: at what is there in the frame.

01:58:57.460 --> 01:59:01.420
[Guest]: Kundan had after all, been at FTII himself as a student, and he would have would have

01:59:01.420 --> 01:59:05.940
[Guest]: picked up on that, you know, watching hundreds and hundreds of films, and we've been taught

01:59:05.940 --> 01:59:08.740
[Guest]: to think about them in personal ways.

01:59:08.740 --> 01:59:15.860
[Guest]: So yeah, so my basic position is, if there is one, is that there is no such thing as

01:59:15.860 --> 01:59:19.700
[Guest]: over analysis, subtextual analysis is great.

01:59:19.700 --> 01:59:23.180
[Guest]: Of course, it's not that simple, because of course, you know, when we're talking about

01:59:23.180 --> 01:59:30.580
[Guest]: over analysis, we are still talking about engaging with what is in the frame of the

01:59:30.580 --> 01:59:33.460
[Guest]: film, if you're talking about a particular scene, or whatever you look at what is in

01:59:33.460 --> 01:59:37.700
[Guest]: the frame, or in the case of a novel, you look at what is on the page, the words that

01:59:37.700 --> 01:59:38.700
[Guest]: have been used there.

01:59:38.700 --> 01:59:45.380
[Guest]: Now, if I were to, hypothetically, I were to watch a film, where you know, just say

01:59:45.380 --> 01:59:52.580
[Guest]: a Hindi film, where a villain played by Ajit in one of those impossibly opulent villain's

01:59:52.580 --> 02:00:02.620
[Guest]: lairs with pink sofas and a pool with a shark swimming in it, waiting to chew up heroes.

02:00:02.620 --> 02:00:06.620
[Guest]: If I were to write about that scene and say, you know, what's happening here is Ajit isn't

02:00:06.620 --> 02:00:07.820
[Guest]: a bad guy.

02:00:07.820 --> 02:00:11.640
[Guest]: But there's an invisible pink unicorn sitting on that pink sofa.

02:00:11.640 --> 02:00:16.460
[Guest]: And he is wired into Ajit and he is making Ajit do all these bad things.

02:00:16.460 --> 02:00:20.020
[Guest]: And of course, you can't see most people can't see the unicorn because he's invisible and

02:00:20.020 --> 02:00:24.220
[Guest]: also because he's, he's a little less pink than that bright thing so far.

02:00:24.220 --> 02:00:28.460
[Guest]: But that is it, that's, you know, the real thing that's happening here is that the unicorn

02:00:28.460 --> 02:00:30.260
[Guest]: is making Ajit do all these bad things.

02:00:30.260 --> 02:00:36.500
[Guest]: Now, if I were to say that, it might still be a fairly entertaining take on the film,

02:00:36.500 --> 02:00:43.220
[Guest]: it might even sort of be a way of overlaying fiction on an existing palimpsest.

02:00:43.220 --> 02:00:45.460
[Guest]: But it probably wouldn't be good criticism, right?

02:00:45.460 --> 02:00:49.620
[Guest]: I think it's safe to say that it wouldn't be valid criticism because you know, you're

02:00:49.620 --> 02:00:53.780
[Guest]: dealing with something that is not palpably in the frame.

02:00:53.780 --> 02:00:57.780
[Guest]: But once you're dealing with things that are actually there, you know, and at whatever

02:00:57.780 --> 02:01:02.300
[Guest]: level because the film is made up of so many different choices, some of which could be

02:01:02.300 --> 02:01:06.980
[Guest]: unconscious choices or subconscious choices or the result of different departments working

02:01:06.980 --> 02:01:11.260
[Guest]: together collaborating, you can have a scene where an actor is doing a particular thing,

02:01:11.260 --> 02:01:15.540
[Guest]: there's a line of dialogue, there's something happening at the level of the of the costume

02:01:15.540 --> 02:01:20.180
[Guest]: design, something happening at the level of the set design, camera movement, shot composition,

02:01:20.180 --> 02:01:21.180
[Guest]: whatever.

02:01:21.180 --> 02:01:25.020
[Guest]: Now, when you're looking at all of that in its entirety, of course, it's fair game for

02:01:25.020 --> 02:01:30.620
[Guest]: a critic to talk about that and to, you know, maybe related to something else that has happened

02:01:30.620 --> 02:01:34.980
[Guest]: in the same film, or something else that has happened in a different work made by the same

02:01:34.980 --> 02:01:37.380
[Guest]: director, or something like that.

02:01:37.380 --> 02:01:38.860
[Guest]: It's, it's completely fair game.

02:01:38.860 --> 02:01:47.180
[Guest]: I don't think it's, as long as you can justify your, you know, whatever you've interpreted,

02:01:47.180 --> 02:01:52.900
[Guest]: in accordance with what is actually there in the scene, after that, it's not to my mind,

02:01:52.900 --> 02:01:58.100
[Guest]: it's not particularly interesting or relevant, what the what the filmmaker himself was consciously

02:01:58.100 --> 02:01:59.100
[Guest]: trying to do.

02:01:59.100 --> 02:02:03.700
[Guest]: I don't think that is something that the critic needs to be concerned with at all.

02:02:03.700 --> 02:02:04.700
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough.

02:02:04.700 --> 02:02:08.820
[Amit Varma]: No, it's, it's, I both kind of agree and disagree, I agree with your basic point.

02:02:08.820 --> 02:02:11.500
[Amit Varma]: But I can see that sometimes overthinking it can become a bad thing.

02:02:11.500 --> 02:02:12.940
[Amit Varma]: For example, let's take the pink sofa.

02:02:12.940 --> 02:02:16.460
[Amit Varma]: Now, I think the pink unicorn is a bit much because you're adding a plot element and all

02:02:16.460 --> 02:02:17.460
[Amit Varma]: of that.

02:02:17.460 --> 02:02:21.180
[Amit Varma]: But one way that scene could be interpreted is that a young critic today could interpret

02:02:21.180 --> 02:02:26.180
[Amit Varma]: it and say that, look, what Ajit is actually doing is that with the pinkness of the sofa,

02:02:26.180 --> 02:02:31.180
[Amit Varma]: by choosing a pink sofa, he's expressing his his repressed feminine side, it's actually

02:02:31.180 --> 02:02:33.860
[Amit Varma]: a little bit metrosexual that he's got a pink sofa.

02:02:33.860 --> 02:02:38.180
[Amit Varma]: And all these heroes who are coming to rescue the heroine, by the act of trying to rescue

02:02:38.180 --> 02:02:43.500
[Amit Varma]: a woman, they are expressing a paternalism and a patriarchal bent of mind and he's feeding

02:02:43.500 --> 02:02:46.180
[Amit Varma]: that toxic masculinity to the sharks in the pool.

02:02:46.180 --> 02:02:47.180
[Amit Varma]: Right?

02:02:47.180 --> 02:02:50.180
[Amit Varma]: Now, all of this is coherent, but it's clearly nonsense.

02:02:50.180 --> 02:02:54.180
[Guest]: Amit, you have a career as an academic critic.

02:02:54.180 --> 02:02:58.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, but the thing is, here is where the director's intent does matter, because none

02:02:58.260 --> 02:02:59.500
[Amit Varma]: of this is intended.

02:02:59.500 --> 02:03:00.500
[Amit Varma]: All of this is coherent.

02:03:00.500 --> 02:03:03.980
[Guest]: That's a point very well made.

02:03:03.980 --> 02:03:09.020
[Guest]: Having said that, I think the safe thing to do is to say that we are all going to be making

02:03:09.020 --> 02:03:16.100
[Guest]: our own value judgments about where the point lies where you perhaps go overboard with analysis

02:03:16.100 --> 02:03:17.100
[Guest]: and interpretation.

02:03:17.100 --> 02:03:20.820
[Guest]: That's a very good example that you just came up with on the fly like that.

02:03:20.820 --> 02:03:27.540
[Guest]: But I also feel like I have read, particularly in the field of academia, and what I would

02:03:27.540 --> 02:03:32.940
[Guest]: consider good academia, which is a very tiny minority of the academia I've read, because

02:03:32.940 --> 02:03:36.660
[Guest]: much of what I've read, you know, especially when it comes to academia around Hindi cinema

02:03:36.660 --> 02:03:41.860
[Guest]: just seems to be tedious above everything else.

02:03:41.860 --> 02:03:50.580
[Guest]: But in what I see as the well expressed, serious minded academic writing, I've actually seen

02:03:50.580 --> 02:03:58.540
[Guest]: things that are not that far from this deliberately exaggerated example that you provided.

02:03:58.540 --> 02:04:01.020
[Guest]: And I've been able to sort of go along with it to some degree.

02:04:01.020 --> 02:04:02.940
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I don't mean to diss all analysis.

02:04:02.940 --> 02:04:07.020
[Amit Varma]: And I'm just saying that there is a danger of overthinking and does one watch out for

02:04:07.020 --> 02:04:08.020
[Amit Varma]: it.

02:04:08.020 --> 02:04:11.820
[Amit Varma]: And you know, this reminded me of a story about myself and it's fairly self deprecatory

02:04:11.820 --> 02:04:13.580
[Amit Varma]: because I end up looking very stupid in it.

02:04:13.580 --> 02:04:17.940
[Amit Varma]: So why not share it, which is that when I was in college in my teens, so this would

02:04:17.940 --> 02:04:22.580
[Amit Varma]: probably be 91, 92, your seminal year, 91, for example, for all we know.

02:04:22.580 --> 02:04:27.300
[Amit Varma]: So I was in Ferguson College in Pune and in our neighbouring college, I think in Gokhale,

02:04:27.300 --> 02:04:32.980
[Amit Varma]: there was an art exhibition and Hussain's works were among those that were put up.

02:04:32.980 --> 02:04:36.620
[Amit Varma]: And I don't remember the occasion at all or why Hussain's works would be put up in a college

02:04:36.620 --> 02:04:38.860
[Amit Varma]: exhibition, but there was something by Hussain there.

02:04:38.860 --> 02:04:41.500
[Amit Varma]: And Hussain himself was around gracing the occasion.

02:04:41.500 --> 02:04:46.500
[Amit Varma]: So I went there with an acquaintance of mine, my neighbor in the hostel, and we were looking

02:04:46.500 --> 02:04:49.260
[Amit Varma]: at a Hussain painting and there was some candle in it.

02:04:49.260 --> 02:04:52.940
[Amit Varma]: So my neighbor looked at me and said, you know what that candle is, I think that represents

02:04:52.940 --> 02:04:54.740
[Amit Varma]: a hope of humanity.

02:04:54.740 --> 02:04:59.460
[Amit Varma]: So I was like, nahi yaar, a great artist like Hussain would never do such cheap symbolism.

02:04:59.460 --> 02:05:03.020
[Amit Varma]: So anyway, then Hussain comes near the painting and somebody, you know, thrusts a mic in his

02:05:03.020 --> 02:05:05.980
[Amit Varma]: face and says, Sir, can you tell us about this painting?

02:05:05.980 --> 02:05:07.820
[Amit Varma]: What is that candle doing there?

02:05:07.820 --> 02:05:13.140
[Amit Varma]: And Hussain says, that's meant to represent the hope of humanity, almost identical words.

02:05:13.140 --> 02:05:17.380
[Amit Varma]: And I just wanted to sink into the ground ki yeh kya ho gaya, but anyway, to sort of

02:05:17.380 --> 02:05:24.260
[Amit Varma]: continue, I'll pick up on one of the things you said, where, and I agree with you in this

02:05:24.260 --> 02:05:28.580
[Amit Varma]: particular thing that you said, where you said that you have to look at a piece of art

02:05:28.580 --> 02:05:32.460
[Amit Varma]: on its own and divorce it of everything else, just look at it by itself, forget what the

02:05:32.460 --> 02:05:35.580
[Amit Varma]: director intended, forget all the things around it.

02:05:35.580 --> 02:05:40.980
[Amit Varma]: Now, this brings me to that political question almost these days of can you separate art

02:05:40.980 --> 02:05:47.100
[Amit Varma]: from the artist, where it is often thought that if, depending on the artist's character,

02:05:47.100 --> 02:05:50.820
[Amit Varma]: you should just totally ignore their art, suddenly your value judgments about their

02:05:50.820 --> 02:05:55.300
[Amit Varma]: art have to be influenced by things that you find out about their personal life.

02:05:55.300 --> 02:06:00.940
[Amit Varma]: So people will use this to, for example, dis Picasso or, you know, not watch Polanski or

02:06:00.940 --> 02:06:03.340
[Amit Varma]: Woody Allen's films and all of that.

02:06:03.340 --> 02:06:07.420
[Amit Varma]: So I'm curious about what you think about this, because my stand to be very clear is

02:06:07.420 --> 02:06:12.320
[Amit Varma]: that my judgment of the art and my judgment of the character of the artist are two completely

02:06:12.320 --> 02:06:13.320
[Amit Varma]: separate things.

02:06:13.320 --> 02:06:17.980
[Amit Varma]: I can love a work of art, and I can absolutely condemn things that the artist might have

02:06:17.980 --> 02:06:23.420
[Amit Varma]: done that they stand completely separately, even though at an emotional level, for example,

02:06:23.420 --> 02:06:28.220
[Amit Varma]: I would never read something by say, Neruda, once one knows about that early rape he committed

02:06:28.220 --> 02:06:30.500
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, you know, and so on and so forth.

02:06:30.500 --> 02:06:34.900
[Amit Varma]: But there are many other cases which are not so clear cut in my mind, like in any case,

02:06:34.900 --> 02:06:37.620
[Amit Varma]: I didn't like Neruda's poetry and all of that.

02:06:37.620 --> 02:06:40.500
[Amit Varma]: But there are cases which are not so clear cut in my mind.

02:06:40.500 --> 02:06:45.180
[Amit Varma]: And my point there is that these judgments, the judgment of the art always has to be independent.

02:06:45.180 --> 02:06:50.060
[Amit Varma]: For example, if I was to give you a book right now, and it's by an anonymous author, say

02:06:50.060 --> 02:06:54.380
[Amit Varma]: a new say, even by Elena Ferrante, are you going to suspend judgment on that work of

02:06:54.380 --> 02:06:57.700
[Amit Varma]: art till you know everything about the character of the artist?

02:06:57.700 --> 02:06:59.820
[Amit Varma]: That is not even possible.

02:06:59.820 --> 02:07:02.860
[Amit Varma]: So what is what is your sort of take on this?

02:07:02.860 --> 02:07:08.300
[Guest]: I'm both glad and a little terrified that you asked this question, because it's, you

02:07:08.300 --> 02:07:14.540
[Guest]: know, it's one of those things that's so complicated that one isn't sure, you know, one will be

02:07:14.540 --> 02:07:18.460
[Guest]: able to articulate all of one's feelings about it in a forum like this.

02:07:18.460 --> 02:07:24.500
[Guest]: First, first of all, let me just say, before I say something slightly controversial sounding,

02:07:24.500 --> 02:07:31.460
[Guest]: let me say that that I completely understand and empathize with anyone who, depending on

02:07:31.460 --> 02:07:35.740
[Guest]: the things on the subjects that resonate most for them, or the things that they feel most

02:07:35.740 --> 02:07:41.980
[Guest]: strongly about, are so triggered by, by what Polanski probably did, or what Woody Allen

02:07:41.980 --> 02:07:46.500
[Guest]: probably did, or what VS Naipaul or whoever probably probably did, that they just cannot

02:07:46.500 --> 02:07:50.940
[Guest]: bring themselves to experience this person's films anymore.

02:07:50.940 --> 02:07:52.780
[Guest]: I completely get that.

02:07:52.780 --> 02:07:54.460
[Guest]: That is a personal decision.

02:07:54.460 --> 02:07:56.940
[Guest]: It's it's it's something that's completely valid.

02:07:56.940 --> 02:07:59.860
[Guest]: I might not be triggered by those things.

02:07:59.860 --> 02:08:05.700
[Guest]: I might be triggered as somebody who's who's more involved with dogs than with most humans

02:08:05.700 --> 02:08:12.300
[Guest]: and homo sapien issues, I, I might get triggered by an artist or filmmaker or a novelist, someone

02:08:12.300 --> 02:08:18.660
[Guest]: who I discovered, at some point has has engaged in severe cruelty to an animal.

02:08:18.660 --> 02:08:25.060
[Guest]: If I if I hear of of a favorite filmmaker or a favorite novelist, engaging in tremendous

02:08:25.060 --> 02:08:30.100
[Guest]: cruelty to an animal, to a dog or something like that, and that might completely put me

02:08:30.100 --> 02:08:32.780
[Guest]: off this person's books or films or whatever.

02:08:32.780 --> 02:08:34.380
[Guest]: So all of us have different triggers.

02:08:34.380 --> 02:08:40.260
[Guest]: And so I completely get that, get that response, even though many people just, many people

02:08:40.260 --> 02:08:44.620
[Guest]: I know just make fun of that response, they know that the idea that you can be triggered

02:08:44.620 --> 02:08:50.740
[Guest]: enough by what some someone has done to just reject the whole body of work or to stop watching

02:08:50.740 --> 02:08:55.100
[Guest]: something or whatever, because, because logically, also, you know, especially when it when it

02:08:55.100 --> 02:09:00.300
[Guest]: comes to film, as you implied as well in your, you know, what you were saying, how does one

02:09:00.300 --> 02:09:04.460
[Guest]: even, no one is ever going to have full knowledge about these things anyway, right?

02:09:04.460 --> 02:09:08.900
[Guest]: A film is a collaborative process, you might have apart from the director or the script

02:09:08.900 --> 02:09:13.100
[Guest]: writer, you might have 20 other people who have played a very prominent role in the making

02:09:13.100 --> 02:09:16.980
[Guest]: of this film, or the or the making of specific scenes within this film.

02:09:16.980 --> 02:09:21.100
[Guest]: And there's a pretty good chance that one or more of those 20 people has done something

02:09:21.100 --> 02:09:25.740
[Guest]: ghastly at some point in their lives and got away with it or whatever or not.

02:09:25.740 --> 02:09:31.620
[Guest]: So as new information keeps coming in, how do you cancel things with hindsight?

02:09:31.620 --> 02:09:36.180
[Guest]: How do you unwatch or unappreciate something that you've already appreciated, you know,

02:09:36.180 --> 02:09:40.580
[Guest]: it requires a certain sort of double think, which, which I find very strange.

02:09:40.580 --> 02:09:45.500
[Guest]: But when it comes to the broad question of the art and the artist, one thought that I

02:09:45.500 --> 02:09:51.580
[Guest]: have, which which I don't really, I feel like I haven't really seen it expressed in most

02:09:51.580 --> 02:09:57.460
[Guest]: of the discourse that I've, that I've experienced about this, what happens is that many of the

02:09:57.460 --> 02:10:02.580
[Guest]: conversations that that that that begin with, can you separate the art from the artist or

02:10:02.580 --> 02:10:08.500
[Guest]: from the person seem to imply that we just have one of two alternatives, you know, one

02:10:08.500 --> 02:10:13.980
[Guest]: alternative is, no, you can't, once you know that the artist has done reprehensible things,

02:10:13.980 --> 02:10:17.340
[Guest]: you reject the art as unsavory or unpalatable.

02:10:17.340 --> 02:10:21.820
[Guest]: The other option is, yes, you can separate the two things, accept the art as something

02:10:21.820 --> 02:10:28.860
[Guest]: that exists on its own terms and might have its own merits and continue to denounce the

02:10:28.860 --> 02:10:31.820
[Guest]: artist as an essentially bad person.

02:10:31.820 --> 02:10:35.620
[Guest]: But the art as something that also just has a life of its own almost independently from

02:10:35.620 --> 02:10:36.620
[Guest]: the artist.

02:10:36.620 --> 02:10:44.020
[Guest]: Now, for me, these positions seem to carry the buried implication that when an artist

02:10:44.020 --> 02:10:49.660
[Guest]: who has done terrible things, creates a book or a film or a song or whatever that is morally

02:10:49.660 --> 02:10:55.660
[Guest]: uplifting or empathetic, or shows positive human values, then it means that this artist

02:10:55.660 --> 02:11:00.500
[Guest]: was being hypocritical, concealing his real self from his audience.

02:11:00.500 --> 02:11:06.140
[Guest]: And I find that view quite problematic, because, you know, the way I see it is, if you were

02:11:06.140 --> 02:11:10.460
[Guest]: to ask, if you were to assume that the allegations about Polanski, for instance, are completely

02:11:10.460 --> 02:11:13.300
[Guest]: true, child rape, whatever.

02:11:13.300 --> 02:11:17.260
[Guest]: And then with that knowledge, you then say, okay, can you separate Polanski, the person

02:11:17.260 --> 02:11:18.620
[Guest]: from his films?

02:11:18.620 --> 02:11:21.900
[Guest]: My answer to that, first of all, would be no, you cannot separate him from his films,

02:11:21.900 --> 02:11:24.700
[Guest]: because his films are deeply personal works.

02:11:24.700 --> 02:11:29.300
[Guest]: You know, everything, even when he's adapting a work like Macbeth, he's putting so much

02:11:29.300 --> 02:11:31.020
[Guest]: of his own life experience into it.

02:11:31.020 --> 02:11:34.780
[Guest]: There are scenes in that which hark back to the Sharon Tate murder.

02:11:34.780 --> 02:11:40.820
[Guest]: There is Polanski's personal life and his personality in almost all his work.

02:11:40.820 --> 02:11:41.820
[Guest]: It's all there.

02:11:41.820 --> 02:11:43.740
[Guest]: How do you separate the two things?

02:11:43.740 --> 02:11:47.500
[Guest]: Now does that necessarily mean that we then just cancel all the films?

02:11:47.500 --> 02:11:51.060
[Guest]: And my answer to that would be no as well.

02:11:51.060 --> 02:11:56.980
[Guest]: Because for me, you know, somebody who's lived a life of 90 years or whatever, again, coming

02:11:56.980 --> 02:12:00.260
[Guest]: back to the we all contain multitudes thing, this is something that I know a lot of people

02:12:00.260 --> 02:12:02.420
[Guest]: will find this idea problematic.

02:12:02.420 --> 02:12:06.180
[Guest]: But you know, if you have one side of your personality that has allowed you to do this

02:12:06.180 --> 02:12:11.380
[Guest]: really terrible thing, you might also have other sides of your personality that have

02:12:11.380 --> 02:12:18.460
[Guest]: allowed you to honestly create great art, which has all these sensitive things going

02:12:18.460 --> 02:12:20.180
[Guest]: on in it.

02:12:20.180 --> 02:12:25.300
[Guest]: And why can't you just accept that maybe these two things represent different sides of the

02:12:25.300 --> 02:12:28.660
[Guest]: person's personality, and then make your call.

02:12:28.660 --> 02:12:33.380
[Guest]: If you decide that, that the bad things he's done are deal breakers for you, then then

02:12:33.380 --> 02:12:37.820
[Guest]: of course, you must, you know, never watch a Polanski film again.

02:12:37.820 --> 02:12:45.020
[Guest]: But I think the question of can you separate the art from the artist is inherently a reductive

02:12:45.020 --> 02:12:46.020
[Guest]: one in some ways.

02:12:46.020 --> 02:12:51.740
[Guest]: Because I don't think that question, you know, the you know, whether you answer yes or no,

02:12:51.740 --> 02:12:54.340
[Guest]: I think there is a third possibility as well.

02:12:54.340 --> 02:12:57.420
[Guest]: There is an in between possibility.

02:12:57.420 --> 02:12:59.540
[Amit Varma]: I think that question needs nuance itself.

02:12:59.540 --> 02:13:03.280
[Amit Varma]: Because just thinking aloud, I think what we're talking about here is not a separation

02:13:03.280 --> 02:13:06.980
[Amit Varma]: of the art from the artist, but a separation of the judgment of the art from a judgment

02:13:06.980 --> 02:13:12.260
[Amit Varma]: of the artist, where one can hold that your judgment of an artist can include that behavior,

02:13:12.260 --> 02:13:15.980
[Amit Varma]: which is just horrendous, and you can think of him as a moral monster.

02:13:15.980 --> 02:13:20.340
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, your judgment of a particular work in which he may have put different aspects

02:13:20.340 --> 02:13:25.740
[Amit Varma]: of his personality or his art or his craft or whatever, you can still look at that work

02:13:25.740 --> 02:13:27.540
[Amit Varma]: and say that it's worth it.

02:13:27.540 --> 02:13:32.180
[Amit Varma]: And I agree with you that this is often personal, it depends on what your triggers are.

02:13:32.180 --> 02:13:37.140
[Amit Varma]: For example, like I said, I can't read Neruda again, I would not read anything by say, Tarun

02:13:37.140 --> 02:13:38.140
[Amit Varma]: Tejpal and M.J.

02:13:38.140 --> 02:13:39.140
[Amit Varma]: Akbar.

02:13:39.140 --> 02:13:43.540
[Amit Varma]: They're both writers of horrendous purple prose anyway, I don't know if there's a connection

02:13:43.540 --> 02:13:47.460
[Amit Varma]: between purple prose and bad character, it is quite possible.

02:13:47.460 --> 02:13:51.700
[Amit Varma]: But for example, one person I do feel conflicted about is someone like Louis CK, like before

02:13:51.700 --> 02:13:56.820
[Amit Varma]: the MeToo allegations against him, surfaced, he was essentially perhaps my favorite modern

02:13:56.820 --> 02:14:00.820
[Amit Varma]: artist, like the TV series he did, Louis, not Lucky Louis, which was an earlier one

02:14:00.820 --> 02:14:02.100
[Amit Varma]: and not so good.

02:14:02.100 --> 02:14:05.940
[Amit Varma]: But a series he did called Louis, I think is an absolute masterpiece, which just gets

02:14:05.940 --> 02:14:09.380
[Amit Varma]: better and better as it goes along through the seasons.

02:14:09.380 --> 02:14:14.920
[Amit Varma]: And part of what makes his art great is the self reflectiveness, where he is basically

02:14:14.920 --> 02:14:17.660
[Amit Varma]: shitting on his earlier self all the time.

02:14:17.660 --> 02:14:22.420
[Amit Varma]: It is like a person has just changed and changed and changed, and he recognizes that he was

02:14:22.420 --> 02:14:23.420
[Amit Varma]: once an asshole.

02:14:23.420 --> 02:14:28.380
[Amit Varma]: And his whole art is about sort of getting to, you know, the crux of the human experience

02:14:28.380 --> 02:14:31.420
[Amit Varma]: through just looking at all the mistakes that he has made.

02:14:31.420 --> 02:14:36.180
[Amit Varma]: And of course, what he was accused of was absolute assholery and really bad behavior,

02:14:36.180 --> 02:14:38.740
[Amit Varma]: but something that happened in the early 2000s.

02:14:38.740 --> 02:14:44.460
[Amit Varma]: So you, you don't know how much he had changed the allegations at one level, while they contained

02:14:44.460 --> 02:14:49.820
[Amit Varma]: assholery, weren't really abrogating consent, he just misused his position of power, asked

02:14:49.820 --> 02:14:53.460
[Amit Varma]: some women whether he could strip in front of them, they said no, he didn't.

02:14:53.460 --> 02:14:55.820
[Amit Varma]: It is still an extremely asshole thing to do.

02:14:55.820 --> 02:14:58.540
[Amit Varma]: And I would not associate with someone like that.

02:14:58.540 --> 02:15:00.940
[Amit Varma]: But do you want to invalidate his later art?

02:15:00.940 --> 02:15:03.660
[Amit Varma]: Do you want to say that people absolutely cannot change?

02:15:03.660 --> 02:15:08.100
[Amit Varma]: So I'm a little conflicted about this, you know, so my feelings about him have become

02:15:08.100 --> 02:15:09.260
[Amit Varma]: very mixed.

02:15:09.260 --> 02:15:13.980
[Amit Varma]: But my feelings about his art remain what they were, because I can't be expected to

02:15:13.980 --> 02:15:19.820
[Amit Varma]: change my ascetic judgment of something, because of something else that I came to know later.

02:15:19.820 --> 02:15:24.300
[Amit Varma]: So I guess at some level, we are making personal judgments about, you know, how much something

02:15:24.300 --> 02:15:26.060
[Amit Varma]: triggers us or affects us.

02:15:26.060 --> 02:15:30.500
[Amit Varma]: And by the way, you mentioned animals, the film I mentioned, Cannibal Holocaust, one

02:15:30.500 --> 02:15:34.860
[Amit Varma]: of the controversies around it was that six dogs were killed live during the film, while

02:15:34.860 --> 02:15:40.540
[Amit Varma]: they were killed, this very elegant, classical-ish music by Riz Otto Lani was being played in

02:15:40.540 --> 02:15:41.540
[Amit Varma]: the background.

02:15:41.540 --> 02:15:45.380
[Amit Varma]: I can totally understand why you would never watch that despite my praise of the film.

02:15:45.380 --> 02:15:47.220
[Amit Varma]: So it's kind of personal.

02:15:47.220 --> 02:15:52.780
[Amit Varma]: But at some level, I think your one's judgment of the art should stand apart from the judgment

02:15:52.780 --> 02:15:53.780
[Amit Varma]: of the artist.

02:15:53.780 --> 02:15:56.460
[Amit Varma]: But yeah, very sort of muddy territory.

02:15:56.460 --> 02:15:57.460
[Amit Varma]: Shall I go on to my next question?

02:15:57.460 --> 02:15:58.460
[Amit Varma]: Or would you like to add to this?

02:15:58.460 --> 02:15:59.460
[Amit Varma]: No, no, no.

02:15:59.460 --> 02:16:04.660
[Guest]: I just wanted to add to that again, you know, that based on what you said, the one thing

02:16:04.660 --> 02:16:09.860
[Guest]: I just like to say again, you know, and this is where self analysis is such a, you know,

02:16:09.860 --> 02:16:10.860
[Guest]: difficult terrain.

02:16:10.860 --> 02:16:13.820
[Guest]: You know, you just, you can just get caught up in it.

02:16:13.820 --> 02:16:18.380
[Guest]: And you know, obviously, it's something that, that all of us, we all egotistical enough

02:16:18.380 --> 02:16:19.420
[Guest]: to want to do it.

02:16:19.420 --> 02:16:22.900
[Guest]: But, but it's so pointless at times, because I really don't know, while you were talking,

02:16:22.900 --> 02:16:28.300
[Guest]: it struck me that I don't really feel that conflicted about my favourite artists.

02:16:28.300 --> 02:16:33.660
[Guest]: If I, if I find out that they've done something really terrible, something that I would disapprove

02:16:33.660 --> 02:16:39.020
[Guest]: of, even to the degree of, of committing crimes that, that in a fairer world than the one

02:16:39.020 --> 02:16:41.820
[Guest]: that we live in, they would be punished for.

02:16:41.820 --> 02:16:47.780
[Guest]: And that ideally, they should have been in jail at a point when they were actually creating

02:16:47.780 --> 02:16:52.140
[Guest]: some of my favourite albums or films or books or whatever.

02:16:52.140 --> 02:16:58.620
[Guest]: Even with that knowledge, I usually find it quite easy to still enjoy the work.

02:16:58.620 --> 02:17:04.740
[Guest]: I don't want, I feel like okay, yes, injustice has been done, or, you know, if it's not a

02:17:04.740 --> 02:17:09.660
[Guest]: you know, not the sort of crime that, that is really punishable, then assholery has been

02:17:09.660 --> 02:17:11.220
[Guest]: indulged in.

02:17:11.220 --> 02:17:12.820
[Guest]: But it doesn't matter that much to me.

02:17:12.820 --> 02:17:17.940
[Guest]: And this applies even to personal heroes now, take someone like Bachchan, there are lots

02:17:17.940 --> 02:17:23.900
[Guest]: of things in his, you know, in his real world personality that I find incredibly irritating,

02:17:23.900 --> 02:17:27.900
[Guest]: including the things that he tweets, these things that I keep hearing, I don't actually

02:17:27.900 --> 02:17:32.300
[Guest]: follow anyone on Twitter, but, but I keep hearing these things or seeing screenshots

02:17:32.300 --> 02:17:37.660
[Guest]: and, and the general sense or sense of this person who no longer has a personality of

02:17:37.660 --> 02:17:44.140
[Guest]: his own, or whatever, he's just sort of just this anodyne thing, none of that has made

02:17:44.140 --> 02:17:50.100
[Guest]: the slightest difference to the thrill that I still feel inside me, if I happen to get

02:17:50.100 --> 02:17:55.340
[Guest]: on to YouTube, and I see a wonderfully performed song sequence like Hai Ke Paan Banaras Wala

02:17:55.340 --> 02:18:02.340
[Guest]: or Jahan Teri Hai Nazar Hai, or O Saati Re from O Kaddar Ka Sikandar, which is, which

02:18:02.340 --> 02:18:07.660
[Guest]: is a favourite film, I'm just watching it and thinking, oh, there on the screen is one

02:18:07.660 --> 02:18:13.860
[Guest]: of my personal heroes, somebody who made my life better at various points in my life.

02:18:13.860 --> 02:18:18.660
[Guest]: The same is true for Sachin Tendulkar, his, his, his innings, you know, came at a time

02:18:18.660 --> 02:18:24.820
[Guest]: in my life when they were, you know, among the, you know, 96, 97, 98, when they were

02:18:24.820 --> 02:18:27.300
[Guest]: among the few good things in my life.

02:18:27.300 --> 02:18:35.060
[Guest]: And I find it perfectly easy to separate that from judgment of, of the, the annoying things

02:18:35.060 --> 02:18:40.660
[Guest]: or the dubious things that one hears about Tendulkar in the current day, for instance.

02:18:40.660 --> 02:18:45.300
[Guest]: So I don't know, maybe, maybe I just sort of find that separation easier to pull off,

02:18:45.300 --> 02:18:51.020
[Guest]: you know, maybe there's something about my reptile brain that just sort of does, does

02:18:51.020 --> 02:18:57.780
[Guest]: that, does those things, because I don't agonize a lot about these, these questions somehow.

02:18:57.780 --> 02:19:00.060
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you absolutely fair enough.

02:19:00.060 --> 02:19:05.300
[Amit Varma]: Now sticking to the, like, some of this art versus artist separation obviously comes about

02:19:05.300 --> 02:19:09.580
[Amit Varma]: because of the politics of our current times, and some of it is great and but some of it

02:19:09.580 --> 02:19:10.580
[Amit Varma]: worries me.

02:19:10.580 --> 02:19:14.220
[Amit Varma]: For example, you have spoken in the past of quote unquote, woke criticism.

02:19:14.220 --> 02:19:19.860
[Amit Varma]: And there is often a sense I get these days that all art is not just being evaluated through

02:19:19.860 --> 02:19:23.580
[Amit Varma]: the prism of that phrase, which both of us have made fun of in the past, how it speaks

02:19:23.580 --> 02:19:28.340
[Amit Varma]: to the human condition, but also through the prism of a certain kind of politics are the

02:19:28.340 --> 02:19:32.540
[Amit Varma]: current are the correct values kind of being depicted here.

02:19:32.540 --> 02:19:36.860
[Amit Varma]: And the point is, it's easy for us to look at something like a Kabir Singh and say that

02:19:36.860 --> 02:19:41.180
[Amit Varma]: oh, that is obviously they're glorifying, you know, a certain kind of toxic masculinity

02:19:41.180 --> 02:19:43.060
[Amit Varma]: and therefore we must condemn it.

02:19:43.060 --> 02:19:44.060
[Amit Varma]: And I agree with that.

02:19:44.060 --> 02:19:45.820
[Amit Varma]: It's, it's, it's just horrendous.

02:19:45.820 --> 02:19:49.140
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, the point is in most art and most good literature and most good

02:19:49.140 --> 02:19:54.340
[Amit Varma]: cinema, you have characters who are conflicted characters who do bad things, you know, characters

02:19:54.340 --> 02:19:59.380
[Amit Varma]: who are not woke, I mean, the whole point of art is that you're depicting humanity as

02:19:59.380 --> 02:20:03.020
[Amit Varma]: it is humanity is imperfect humanity contains multitudes.

02:20:03.020 --> 02:20:07.460
[Amit Varma]: But when you sort of look at that art, say you judge a film because of what its characters

02:20:07.460 --> 02:20:10.220
[Amit Varma]: do, it seems bizarre to me, but I've seen that happen.

02:20:10.220 --> 02:20:16.220
[Amit Varma]: Or you try to talk about what a film's politics is, you know, then it becomes to use a favorite

02:20:16.220 --> 02:20:19.780
[Amit Varma]: phrase of many of these people, it becomes problematic for me, because I just want to

02:20:19.780 --> 02:20:21.700
[Amit Varma]: look at art on its own terms.

02:20:21.700 --> 02:20:26.220
[Amit Varma]: I don't care about what agenda there is, or what agenda you can read into it, where also

02:20:26.220 --> 02:20:28.420
[Amit Varma]: a lot of overthinking can go on.

02:20:28.420 --> 02:20:31.060
[Amit Varma]: So as a critic, what do you feel about this?

02:20:31.060 --> 02:20:36.860
[Guest]: Well, I feel many, many different things about this and when and how many hours do you have?

02:20:36.860 --> 02:20:39.860
[Guest]: Don't answer that.

02:20:39.860 --> 02:20:50.100
[Guest]: Well, I could start controversially by saying that, that I wouldn't even take what you said

02:20:50.100 --> 02:20:54.220
[Guest]: about Kabir Singh as a given, a because I haven't watched the film myself.

02:20:54.220 --> 02:20:58.660
[Guest]: So of course, I'm not going to make up my mind about a film that I haven't watched.

02:20:58.660 --> 02:21:02.780
[Guest]: And that I don't really have, I don't really plan to watch anytime in the near future.

02:21:02.780 --> 02:21:09.180
[Guest]: But I do know, at least three or four people whose judgment I respect a great deal whose

02:21:09.180 --> 02:21:11.540
[Guest]: prisms I respect a great deal.

02:21:11.540 --> 02:21:16.140
[Guest]: One of whom is a woman, which may or may not be important, who did not feel that way about

02:21:16.140 --> 02:21:21.700
[Guest]: the film at all, that the film is a glorification of toxic masculinity, they felt very differently.

02:21:21.700 --> 02:21:25.460
[Guest]: And these are liberal people I'm talking about, broadly liberal people.

02:21:25.460 --> 02:21:31.300
[Guest]: So I'm not making those assumptions about any film at all.

02:21:31.300 --> 02:21:35.900
[Guest]: Having said that, I will express my view on Kabir Singh only after I've seen it and not

02:21:35.900 --> 02:21:36.900
[Guest]: before that.

02:21:36.900 --> 02:21:41.900
[Guest]: There's not an expression of a particular judgment or a non judgment.

02:21:41.900 --> 02:21:46.380
[Guest]: Having said that, I also want to just touch on, again, you've articulated a lot of the

02:21:46.380 --> 02:21:53.740
[Guest]: issues, you know, quite neatly, but I'd also just touch on this thing of, it's not just

02:21:53.740 --> 02:22:00.660
[Guest]: a matter of viewing art for its own sake, or in, it's not just a matter of that, because

02:22:00.660 --> 02:22:04.620
[Guest]: because with that, then of course, you know, you, you also come to things like like the

02:22:04.620 --> 02:22:11.460
[Guest]: films of Lenny Reifenstahl, and I'm not going to say the Birth of a Nation, but but, but

02:22:11.460 --> 02:22:18.980
[Guest]: definitely Lenny Reifenstahl's films, which were, you know, explicitly Nazi propaganda.

02:22:18.980 --> 02:22:23.260
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, those are those are overtly political and politics is what it is.

02:22:23.260 --> 02:22:28.460
[Amit Varma]: So it's fine to condemn those, but I'm obviously not talking about those sort of edge cases.

02:22:28.460 --> 02:22:34.860
[Guest]: What I meant was, they're also in parts, at least they're pretty good, good films in terms

02:22:34.860 --> 02:22:42.100
[Guest]: of the use of the formal cinematic devices, and techniques, you know, in ways to achieve

02:22:42.100 --> 02:22:43.420
[Guest]: a certain effect.

02:22:43.420 --> 02:22:50.020
[Guest]: And many people still continue to point that out while while also, of course, holding forth

02:22:50.020 --> 02:22:51.820
[Guest]: on the problematic aspects.

02:22:51.820 --> 02:22:59.300
[Guest]: But what happens is that, that when a film is looked at only through the prism of a,

02:22:59.300 --> 02:23:07.020
[Guest]: of a very clearly defined ideology, and, and is looked at, from this point of view that,

02:23:07.020 --> 02:23:08.480
[Guest]: what is the film?

02:23:08.480 --> 02:23:10.500
[Guest]: What is the politics of this film?

02:23:10.500 --> 02:23:13.420
[Guest]: What is the politics of this filmmaker or scriptwriter?

02:23:13.420 --> 02:23:18.980
[Guest]: The thing is, these are questions that that very often do not have clear cut answers.

02:23:18.980 --> 02:23:23.220
[Guest]: Sometimes they do, of course, sometimes they do, you know, and there are cases of films

02:23:23.220 --> 02:23:26.460
[Guest]: that are made explicitly as propaganda, as you pointed out.

02:23:26.460 --> 02:23:32.820
[Guest]: But with with a lot of art, including art that seems self evidently to some people as

02:23:32.820 --> 02:23:40.060
[Guest]: as being, you know, being as setting out to fulfill a particular agenda.

02:23:40.060 --> 02:23:45.380
[Guest]: What is really happening is that a director or a novelist or a scriptwriter is trying

02:23:45.380 --> 02:23:47.460
[Guest]: to build a world.

02:23:47.460 --> 02:23:53.540
[Guest]: And in the building of that world, what is happening is that moral judgments, moral or

02:23:53.540 --> 02:23:56.820
[Guest]: ideological positions are being suspended to a great degree.

02:23:56.820 --> 02:24:01.980
[Guest]: And what they are trying to do is to be is to be as true as possible to the characters

02:24:01.980 --> 02:24:02.980
[Guest]: within this world.

02:24:02.980 --> 02:24:11.460
[Guest]: Now, if those characters include people who, who we liberals think are quote unquote problematic,

02:24:11.460 --> 02:24:16.140
[Guest]: then you still will have a situation where a serious novelist or a serious director or

02:24:16.140 --> 02:24:22.840
[Guest]: a scriptwriter, if they are trying to create this work honestly, will be putting themselves

02:24:22.840 --> 02:24:27.940
[Guest]: in the mind space of this character, will be forming certain degrees of empathy for

02:24:27.940 --> 02:24:30.540
[Guest]: this character's actions as well.

02:24:30.540 --> 02:24:36.660
[Guest]: And that, you know, when it is presented in the final film, it can easily seem to someone

02:24:36.660 --> 02:24:41.300
[Guest]: who someone who's looking at the film only through a very specific ideological lens,

02:24:41.300 --> 02:24:46.020
[Guest]: it will seem like glorification, whereas the truth might actually be a little more complex.

02:24:46.020 --> 02:24:50.340
[Guest]: It might just be tied into the process of world building, which is something that that

02:24:50.340 --> 02:24:53.340
[Guest]: that most serious creative people do.

02:24:53.340 --> 02:24:57.580
[Guest]: And, and when you're deep in it, I mean, you've been a novelist yourself, you've done I know

02:24:57.580 --> 02:25:01.020
[Guest]: you've you've written other sorts of fiction as well.

02:25:01.020 --> 02:25:05.760
[Guest]: You know what this is about your when you're dealing with this very difficult business

02:25:05.760 --> 02:25:09.940
[Guest]: of creating a world from the inside out and putting yourself in the heads of different

02:25:09.940 --> 02:25:16.060
[Guest]: sorts of characters, you are not necessarily thinking about moral positions, or about what

02:25:16.060 --> 02:25:22.820
[Guest]: what the takeaway, what the correct takeaway for your reader or your viewer should be.

02:25:22.820 --> 02:25:34.980
[Guest]: And I think a lot of these workish, strictly ideological takes on films only want takeaways,

02:25:34.980 --> 02:25:37.740
[Guest]: they only want a clear cut answer.

02:25:37.740 --> 02:25:44.660
[Guest]: Does this film endorse or does it only depict, does it you know, what what is the politics

02:25:44.660 --> 02:25:49.820
[Guest]: of this particular novelist in creating this character?

02:25:49.820 --> 02:25:53.540
[Guest]: And then those are subjective judgments anyway, but then a lot of the people who make those

02:25:53.540 --> 02:25:59.020
[Guest]: judgments will behave as if they have the final moral word.

02:25:59.020 --> 02:26:04.980
[Guest]: And anybody who, you know, feels differently is morally compromised or just not engaged

02:26:04.980 --> 02:26:06.500
[Guest]: enough or whatever it is.

02:26:06.500 --> 02:26:10.780
[Guest]: So that's, that's one of the most troubling aspects of some of the political conversations

02:26:10.780 --> 02:26:13.580
[Guest]: around cinema and literature these days for me.

02:26:13.580 --> 02:26:17.660
[Guest]: I know speaking speaking as someone who's, you know, I'm on this podcast with you right

02:26:17.660 --> 02:26:21.780
[Guest]: now, saying all these things and what will be a public forum soon.

02:26:21.780 --> 02:26:28.700
[Guest]: Even so, I know that that I feel very constrained if I if I find myself in the presence of someone

02:26:28.700 --> 02:26:34.740
[Guest]: who is just going on and on about how regressive a particular film is, or this character so

02:26:34.740 --> 02:26:39.140
[Guest]: problematic, this film is so regressive, I sometimes feel like it's it's not worth my

02:26:39.140 --> 02:26:42.740
[Guest]: while to argue, I'll just keep quiet.

02:26:42.740 --> 02:26:46.740
[Guest]: And then and then, you know, and maybe just try and change the subject or something.

02:26:46.740 --> 02:26:50.100
[Guest]: And that's a pity because because because that is definitely affecting discourse.

02:26:50.100 --> 02:26:55.020
[Guest]: And I know there are many people like me who feel that, who feel that that that a lot of

02:26:55.020 --> 02:27:03.220
[Guest]: the left liberal slash woke criticism, cultural criticism has just become all about very narrow

02:27:03.220 --> 02:27:09.340
[Guest]: ideological prisms, or narrow ideological definitions, rather than looking at the entirety

02:27:09.340 --> 02:27:15.700
[Guest]: of what a film or a book might be doing, the many contradictions that exist within a particular

02:27:15.700 --> 02:27:16.700
[Guest]: creative work.

02:27:16.700 --> 02:27:23.100
[Guest]: Now, one of your earlier guests on scene and the unseen Parumita Vora has spoken very eloquently

02:27:23.100 --> 02:27:29.420
[Guest]: about this in the context of a lot of Hindi films that get sweepingly described as regressive

02:27:29.420 --> 02:27:35.300
[Guest]: or problematic or toxic, and she's defended them in her writings and in some of her talks

02:27:35.300 --> 02:27:40.340
[Guest]: as well, about how so many of these works are actually far more complex than than many

02:27:40.340 --> 02:27:43.660
[Guest]: people realize there are there are there are different things going on in there.

02:27:43.660 --> 02:27:49.740
[Guest]: You know, you might have one scene or one line of dialogue that that seems really terrible

02:27:49.740 --> 02:27:53.700
[Guest]: and patriarchal and whatever, but there'll be something else, there'll be there'll be

02:27:53.700 --> 02:27:58.420
[Guest]: another impulse in the same scene that will also be working against that, or providing

02:27:58.420 --> 02:27:59.940
[Guest]: a cushion against that.

02:27:59.940 --> 02:28:03.740
[Guest]: And that's how a lot of popular cinema tends to work.

02:28:03.740 --> 02:28:05.340
[Guest]: I don't know if any of this has made sense, but

02:28:05.340 --> 02:28:07.260
[Amit Varma]: No, it makes a lot of sense.

02:28:07.260 --> 02:28:11.660
[Amit Varma]: I mean, just a couple of episodes ago, I had Kavita Krishnan, the feminist on the show.

02:28:11.660 --> 02:28:13.620
[Amit Varma]: I mean, why am I even saying a feminist?

02:28:13.620 --> 02:28:14.620
[Amit Varma]: We are all feminists.

02:28:14.620 --> 02:28:15.620
[Amit Varma]: I would hope.

02:28:15.620 --> 02:28:16.700
[Amit Varma]: I certainly am one.

02:28:16.700 --> 02:28:20.780
[Amit Varma]: But one of the things Kavita spoke about was how people look at Enid Blyton today, where

02:28:20.780 --> 02:28:23.820
[Amit Varma]: they're trying to almost, in hindsight, cancel Enid Blyton.

02:28:23.820 --> 02:28:26.900
[Amit Varma]: And her point was, look, I read Enid Blyton, I loved Enid Blyton.

02:28:26.900 --> 02:28:31.860
[Amit Varma]: And the characters I identified most with and the characters that Enid Blyton, in fact,

02:28:31.860 --> 02:28:35.700
[Amit Varma]: made stand out were the people who are bucking the system, the tomboys, for example, among

02:28:35.700 --> 02:28:40.060
[Amit Varma]: the girls at Mallory Towers, you know, so you got to look a little deeper than the fact

02:28:40.060 --> 02:28:42.300
[Amit Varma]: is that society is regressive.

02:28:42.300 --> 02:28:43.300
[Amit Varma]: People are complex.

02:28:43.300 --> 02:28:47.260
[Amit Varma]: And it's a job of art to capture all of this and not necessarily to pass judgment, otherwise

02:28:47.260 --> 02:28:49.340
[Amit Varma]: you become facile propaganda.

02:28:49.340 --> 02:28:55.340
[Amit Varma]: Now, my thinking is and tell me what you think about this is that there are really two impulses

02:28:55.340 --> 02:28:58.940
[Amit Varma]: or two sort of phenomena that kind of lead to this phenomena.

02:28:58.940 --> 02:29:03.620
[Amit Varma]: One is that on the one hand, it might seem that in the age of social media, all of history

02:29:03.620 --> 02:29:04.700
[Amit Varma]: is available to us.

02:29:04.700 --> 02:29:08.260
[Amit Varma]: You know, unlike you and me, we don't have to scramble to watch movies from the past

02:29:08.260 --> 02:29:13.580
[Amit Varma]: as we used to do in the 1980s, in your case, going to embassy video libraries, borrowing.

02:29:13.580 --> 02:29:17.040
[Amit Varma]: Now it's all on the click of a button legally or otherwise.

02:29:17.040 --> 02:29:21.100
[Amit Varma]: But actually, that's not totally accurate to be in the sense that yes, it is all out

02:29:21.100 --> 02:29:25.460
[Amit Varma]: there, but I think as Jonathan Haidt pointed out in an episode of a podcast I produced

02:29:25.460 --> 02:29:29.620
[Amit Varma]: Brave New World, which is hosted by Vasant Dhar, he spoke to Jonathan Haidt and if I

02:29:29.620 --> 02:29:35.060
[Amit Varma]: remember correctly, it was Haidt only who pointed out that what most people consume

02:29:35.060 --> 02:29:38.980
[Amit Varma]: on social media is what has been produced in the last three days.

02:29:38.980 --> 02:29:42.700
[Amit Varma]: So it's very current, it's bound to the current time, they're not really going too far back

02:29:42.700 --> 02:29:43.700
[Amit Varma]: into the past.

02:29:43.700 --> 02:29:47.620
[Amit Varma]: Now, in your case, your education of cinema, like even when you said that you don't watch

02:29:47.620 --> 02:29:52.740
[Amit Varma]: too many films today, the bottom line is you have put in a lot of time watching films and

02:29:52.740 --> 02:29:55.180
[Amit Varma]: watching films of the past.

02:29:55.180 --> 02:29:58.060
[Amit Varma]: All of it informs the way you look at cinema.

02:29:58.060 --> 02:30:02.340
[Amit Varma]: And that's true of every good film critic, including you know, someone like Bharatwaj

02:30:02.340 --> 02:30:06.460
[Amit Varma]: Rangan comes to mind who was also you know, such a star during the blogging days and a

02:30:06.460 --> 02:30:07.700
[Amit Varma]: fantastic critic.

02:30:07.700 --> 02:30:13.980
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, you have this bedrock of historical exposure, which informs whatever you do, but

02:30:13.980 --> 02:30:19.700
[Amit Varma]: everyone today is kind of stuck in the current moment where everything you're consuming was

02:30:19.700 --> 02:30:22.420
[Amit Varma]: maybe produced in the last three days and all of that.

02:30:22.420 --> 02:30:27.860
[Amit Varma]: And this can sometimes garble your perspective, and you almost in a sense become trapped in

02:30:27.860 --> 02:30:28.860
[Amit Varma]: the present.

02:30:28.860 --> 02:30:30.820
[Amit Varma]: Now, this brings me to the second factor.

02:30:30.820 --> 02:30:34.380
[Amit Varma]: And this is true, especially if you're on social media, where you're even more trapped

02:30:34.380 --> 02:30:39.460
[Amit Varma]: in the present, because everything is off the moment, where in social media, what is

02:30:39.460 --> 02:30:44.260
[Amit Varma]: the imperative for a lot of the people out there, especially the young people, is to

02:30:44.260 --> 02:30:49.220
[Amit Varma]: raise their status within whatever in groups they have chosen within social media.

02:30:49.220 --> 02:30:52.020
[Amit Varma]: The vast silent majority haven't really made such choices.

02:30:52.020 --> 02:30:55.860
[Amit Varma]: And luckily, I think, you know, you spoke about these things that you're saying on my

02:30:55.860 --> 02:30:59.380
[Amit Varma]: podcast in a public forum, but I would imagine that podcast listeners who have gotten this

02:30:59.380 --> 02:31:04.460
[Amit Varma]: far are not the kind of people who outrage on social media anyway, so you and I are safe.

02:31:04.460 --> 02:31:09.180
[Amit Varma]: But social media people form their echo chambers and they need to raise their status within

02:31:09.180 --> 02:31:10.180
[Amit Varma]: those echo chambers.

02:31:10.180 --> 02:31:13.180
[Amit Varma]: They need to posture their purity in different ways.

02:31:13.180 --> 02:31:16.900
[Amit Varma]: They can do it by attacking people on the other side and always attacking people never

02:31:16.900 --> 02:31:18.300
[Amit Varma]: engaging with arguments.

02:31:18.300 --> 02:31:21.940
[Amit Varma]: They can do it by attacking people on their own side for not being pure enough, which

02:31:21.940 --> 02:31:23.980
[Amit Varma]: eventually happens to everybody.

02:31:23.980 --> 02:31:28.940
[Amit Varma]: In fact, most of the people, the vokes cancel, seem to be former vokes, in a sense in current

02:31:28.940 --> 02:31:29.940
[Amit Varma]: times.

02:31:29.940 --> 02:31:32.940
[Amit Varma]: So you know, they're going to come for you eventually, unless you produce absolutely

02:31:32.940 --> 02:31:35.660
[Amit Varma]: nothing and only outrage, in which case you're safe.

02:31:35.660 --> 02:31:40.140
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, these two come together that on the one hand, you don't really have a deep

02:31:40.140 --> 02:31:44.780
[Amit Varma]: understanding of whatever it is you're critiquing, whether it's literature or cinema or whatever.

02:31:44.780 --> 02:31:49.060
[Amit Varma]: And on the other hand, you need to posture all the time and this is easy meat, right?

02:31:49.060 --> 02:31:54.420
[Amit Varma]: You shit on a film, you say that, oh, it is regressive, this character is problematic.

02:31:54.420 --> 02:31:57.900
[Amit Varma]: This director tweeted this when he was 16 years old.

02:31:57.900 --> 02:32:02.660
[Amit Varma]: And there's absolutely no cost to this kind of posturing to you.

02:32:02.660 --> 02:32:07.980
[Amit Varma]: But it has such a harmful effect on the discourse, because these people may be a vocal minority,

02:32:07.980 --> 02:32:13.660
[Amit Varma]: but because they are the vocal ones, the majority of the discourse seems to be like this.

02:32:13.660 --> 02:32:15.580
[Amit Varma]: So you know, do you kind of agree with this?

02:32:15.580 --> 02:32:17.540
[Amit Varma]: Are there things that you would add to this?

02:32:17.540 --> 02:32:21.780
[Amit Varma]: And if this is broadly what the picture is, then do we have hope moving forward?

02:32:21.780 --> 02:32:27.780
[Guest]: I don't know where, as a part time nihilist, I always say there's no hope moving forward.

02:32:27.780 --> 02:32:36.420
[Guest]: But this, no, I agree with pretty much everything, you know, Amit, I don't like using the term

02:32:36.420 --> 02:32:41.380
[Guest]: virtue signaling, because I think it's I think it's a very easy term to use, I'm very tempted

02:32:41.380 --> 02:32:42.380
[Guest]: to do it.

02:32:42.380 --> 02:32:46.060
[Guest]: And I do end up doing it, especially in private conversations.

02:32:46.060 --> 02:32:50.660
[Guest]: But one reason I don't like using it is because of something that you touched on, which is

02:32:50.660 --> 02:32:55.780
[Guest]: that, when, for instance, and I'm not really on Twitter, but on Facebook, as sometimes

02:32:55.780 --> 02:33:02.700
[Guest]: when I go through these phases, where I see a lot of feeds and things, very often I see

02:33:02.700 --> 02:33:08.980
[Guest]: the term virtue signaling being used in a deprecatory way by people who I myself, at

02:33:08.980 --> 02:33:13.020
[Guest]: some point in the past have thought of as virtue signalers.

02:33:13.020 --> 02:33:17.020
[Guest]: And then I wonder, maybe people are thinking that way about me as well in other contexts.

02:33:17.020 --> 02:33:22.020
[Guest]: So you know, so it just becomes one of those loops and you know, and it's even a term like,

02:33:22.020 --> 02:33:26.980
[Guest]: you know, the workster use pejoratively, which is something I like doing, and I like doing

02:33:26.980 --> 02:33:33.260
[Guest]: it in a slightly sort of cheesy way, you know, using the word using the Star Wars terms,

02:33:33.260 --> 02:33:38.460
[Guest]: Wookiees, or Ewoks or whatever, it's, it's fun to do that.

02:33:38.460 --> 02:33:44.740
[Guest]: But but a part of me does feel a bit uncertain and uneasy when when I do it, because I know

02:33:44.740 --> 02:33:48.220
[Guest]: that there are probably contexts in which people can feel they can say the same thing

02:33:48.220 --> 02:33:53.540
[Guest]: about me, as well, based on things that I've definitely things I've written in the past,

02:33:53.540 --> 02:33:58.780
[Guest]: and possibly even now, broadly agree with everything you're saying.

02:33:58.780 --> 02:34:03.020
[Guest]: It does disturb me, though, you know, and now, just to again, perhaps come back a little

02:34:03.020 --> 02:34:07.900
[Guest]: bit to what we were talking about a bit earlier, I was on a conversation once with, you know,

02:34:07.900 --> 02:34:12.580
[Guest]: just just doing this online lecture for somebody.

02:34:12.580 --> 02:34:16.860
[Guest]: And there were these these very engaged young people talking about films and asking for

02:34:16.860 --> 02:34:21.500
[Guest]: recommendations of old films, and it was it was great fun.

02:34:21.500 --> 02:34:25.140
[Guest]: And then subsequently, one of them started following me on Instagram, and I happened

02:34:25.140 --> 02:34:28.260
[Guest]: to go and see the Instagram page.

02:34:28.260 --> 02:34:34.180
[Guest]: And I saw this write up about the Philadelphia story, the 1940 film, The Philadelphia Story,

02:34:34.180 --> 02:34:38.060
[Guest]: which with the Catherine Hepburn and Cary Grant and James Stewart, one of my favorite

02:34:38.060 --> 02:34:44.180
[Guest]: films from that era, and the language used for this film, but it was so patronizing and

02:34:44.180 --> 02:34:54.220
[Guest]: condescending words like nauseating, misogynistic, you know, stuff like that, just based on what

02:34:54.220 --> 02:34:58.780
[Guest]: happens to the to the main female character, Tracy Lord over the course of the story, the

02:34:58.780 --> 02:35:04.900
[Guest]: fact that she sort of that she did in this, this, this young writer's interpretation,

02:35:04.900 --> 02:35:09.100
[Guest]: she's just sort of being manipulated by all the men in her life, and eventually just driven

02:35:09.100 --> 02:35:11.460
[Guest]: to the right man, etc, etc.

02:35:11.460 --> 02:35:15.020
[Guest]: And I was looking at that and thinking, you know, the Philadelphia story of all films

02:35:15.020 --> 02:35:18.820
[Guest]: is being described as nauseous and misogynistic.

02:35:18.820 --> 02:35:24.700
[Guest]: These are strong words, you know, it's incumbent on us to use language with a little more care.

02:35:24.700 --> 02:35:29.700
[Guest]: Because ultimately, what's going to happen is we, you know, words like misogynistic or

02:35:29.700 --> 02:35:36.680
[Guest]: Islamophobia, or Islamophobic or whatever, these should be strong, condemnatory words.

02:35:36.680 --> 02:35:42.500
[Guest]: But what's happening in a lot of the current discourses, they are being used in such casual

02:35:42.500 --> 02:35:46.540
[Guest]: and careless ways, that they'll end up losing their potency to start with.

02:35:46.540 --> 02:35:48.620
[Guest]: For someone like me, they've already lost their potency.

02:35:48.620 --> 02:35:53.060
[Guest]: I see the word misogynistic somewhere written somewhere, my first impulse is to think there's

02:35:53.060 --> 02:35:55.700
[Guest]: just some some workster overreacting to something.

02:35:55.700 --> 02:35:58.260
[Guest]: That's my first response, rightly or wrongly.

02:35:58.260 --> 02:36:05.420
[Guest]: And I find this, again, to use that word problematic, the word that we supposedly dislike.

02:36:05.420 --> 02:36:11.020
[Guest]: But at the same time, I do have a lot of sympathy for for young people who are living in this

02:36:11.020 --> 02:36:17.020
[Guest]: time of so much clutter, so much stuff that's available to them all the time, even someone

02:36:17.020 --> 02:36:23.940
[Guest]: like me, you know, if I, if I, at my age, if I get a recommendation for a for a limited

02:36:23.940 --> 02:36:30.260
[Guest]: series, like like Mayor of East Town, or whatever, which is just seven, seven episodes or something.

02:36:30.260 --> 02:36:34.620
[Guest]: And I get, you know, the motivated enough to watch it because of the recommendations

02:36:34.620 --> 02:36:39.500
[Guest]: and because I like Kate Winslet, or I like the genre or something, I'm still taking seven

02:36:39.500 --> 02:36:40.500
[Guest]: hours of my time out.

02:36:40.500 --> 02:36:44.740
[Guest]: And at the end of it, I'm thinking, wow, you know, even if it was good, I've just spent

02:36:44.740 --> 02:36:47.260
[Guest]: so much of my time doing this.

02:36:47.260 --> 02:36:51.620
[Guest]: This is despite the fact that I'm also aware that there are older things that I need to

02:36:51.620 --> 02:36:56.460
[Guest]: watch or rewatch for columns or for some of my own writing, and I need to find the time

02:36:56.460 --> 02:36:57.460
[Guest]: for that.

02:36:57.460 --> 02:37:01.860
[Guest]: I can only sympathize with with young people who are in this world where, where they're

02:37:01.860 --> 02:37:08.900
[Guest]: binge watching maybe four or five or six series every month, and watching films and so on.

02:37:08.900 --> 02:37:12.860
[Guest]: It's completely understandable that they will end up lacking a sense of history.

02:37:12.860 --> 02:37:16.020
[Guest]: I don't really think they're going to be any easy solutions to this.

02:37:16.020 --> 02:37:20.580
[Guest]: I've been in classes like like I indicated just now, I've been in classes where 20-21

02:37:20.580 --> 02:37:27.820
[Guest]: year olds with utmost sincerity have asked me, how do we find the time to watch all these

02:37:27.820 --> 02:37:30.420
[Guest]: old films that we want to watch?

02:37:30.420 --> 02:37:35.860
[Guest]: And by old films, they mostly mean films that were not made in this millennium, films made

02:37:35.860 --> 02:37:36.860
[Guest]: before 2000.

02:37:36.860 --> 02:37:43.980
[Guest]: I mean, there's a whole generation of movie buffs right now who think that anything pre-Christopher

02:37:43.980 --> 02:37:49.580
[Guest]: Nolan is, is ancient, but they don't have the time to do this and I do have basic sympathy

02:37:49.580 --> 02:37:55.420
[Guest]: for that because all of us have finite time, we are just being inundated with so much information,

02:37:55.420 --> 02:38:00.820
[Guest]: so many things to watch across all the OTT platforms across all the other spaces.

02:38:00.820 --> 02:38:02.060
[Guest]: Even I feel that pressure.

02:38:02.060 --> 02:38:05.060
[Guest]: So I can imagine what it's like for for younger people.

02:38:05.060 --> 02:38:07.820
[Guest]: So so no easy solutions to this.

02:38:07.820 --> 02:38:13.580
[Guest]: I mean, you know, the only thing I could, the only piece of advice I would give anyone

02:38:13.580 --> 02:38:20.380
[Guest]: was to, you know, if you have seven days a week to watch, you know, to spend four or

02:38:20.380 --> 02:38:25.540
[Guest]: five hours per day watching things, just try and, and create a schedule for yourself.

02:38:25.540 --> 02:38:31.580
[Guest]: Tell yourself that that two days a week you will watch something that was made pre-1970

02:38:31.580 --> 02:38:32.580
[Guest]: for instance.

02:38:32.580 --> 02:38:37.260
[Guest]: You know, something that that comes out of a movie recommendation or a criterion recommendation

02:38:37.260 --> 02:38:38.340
[Guest]: or whatever.

02:38:38.340 --> 02:38:41.500
[Guest]: And even that won't be enough because then you know, you'll end up watching American

02:38:41.500 --> 02:38:47.020
[Guest]: films or French films, they might not engage with with old Hindi cinema, which is which

02:38:47.020 --> 02:38:50.940
[Guest]: is something that's that's very difficult for young people to engage with now.

02:38:50.940 --> 02:38:54.620
[Guest]: Because because because everybody's grown away from that tradition of the song and dance

02:38:54.620 --> 02:38:56.620
[Guest]: and the masala.

02:38:56.620 --> 02:39:01.580
[Guest]: It's it's very difficult to start start magically tuning your mind to that sort of thing.

02:39:01.580 --> 02:39:04.420
[Guest]: So so so no easy answers at all.

02:39:04.420 --> 02:39:06.420
[Guest]: There's no hope.

02:39:06.420 --> 02:39:07.420
[Amit Varma]: There's no hope basically.

02:39:07.420 --> 02:39:09.900
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I kind of, I mean, do I kind of agree?

02:39:09.900 --> 02:39:10.900
[Unknown]: I guess I kind of agree.

02:39:10.900 --> 02:39:12.500
[Amit Varma]: But I mean, I don't want to die anyway.

02:39:12.500 --> 02:39:15.900
[Amit Varma]: So if you look at the really long, long term, of course, there's no hope.

02:39:15.900 --> 02:39:16.940
[Amit Varma]: But hope for what?

02:39:16.940 --> 02:39:19.940
[Amit Varma]: The fact that sometimes I have to remind myself that look, I am in my 40s.

02:39:19.940 --> 02:39:23.780
[Amit Varma]: And most of these young people have a different frame of reference entirely.

02:39:23.780 --> 02:39:28.060
[Amit Varma]: Like I think I saw this tweet recently, I think Aakar Patel did it, who's tweeting recently

02:39:28.060 --> 02:39:29.980
[Amit Varma]: is incredibly entertaining.

02:39:29.980 --> 02:39:32.740
[Amit Varma]: And Aakar was referring to some piece of news somewhere.

02:39:32.740 --> 02:39:37.420
[Amit Varma]: And he said, Oh, bloody, you know, basically, Oh, bloody, but he's spelted Oh, bloody.

02:39:37.420 --> 02:39:39.540
[Amit Varma]: So below that someone commented Oh, bloody.

02:39:39.540 --> 02:39:41.780
[Amit Varma]: And below that someone commented life goes on.

02:39:41.780 --> 02:39:44.420
[Amit Varma]: And I'm like, only someone of my generation actually gets this.

02:39:44.420 --> 02:39:48.420
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the moment I saw the reply, Oh, bloody, I was tempted to type life goes on till I

02:39:48.420 --> 02:39:52.100
[Amit Varma]: saw someone's already done it reference, of course, to the famous Beatles song.

02:39:52.100 --> 02:39:55.100
[Guest]: Please, please tell me you tweeted, bruh.

02:39:55.100 --> 02:39:56.100
[Guest]: No.

02:39:56.100 --> 02:39:58.540
[Amit Varma]: No, I didn't tweet, bruh.

02:39:58.540 --> 02:40:01.500
[Amit Varma]: That's something you got to remind yourself that these people have a very different frame

02:40:01.500 --> 02:40:07.420
[Amit Varma]: of reference that, you know, that they may not have sort of heard or watched or read

02:40:07.420 --> 02:40:10.220
[Amit Varma]: all of this stuff from the past.

02:40:10.220 --> 02:40:14.900
[Amit Varma]: And but what has now happened is and I don't think that this sort of a lot of these shallow

02:40:14.900 --> 02:40:18.580
[Amit Varma]: expressions from people who haven't engaged with cinema, but will nevertheless pass judgment

02:40:18.580 --> 02:40:20.380
[Amit Varma]: on it on the basis of the politics.

02:40:20.380 --> 02:40:25.460
[Amit Varma]: I don't think that worries me in one particular context, which is I don't think less people

02:40:25.460 --> 02:40:26.660
[Amit Varma]: are serious about cinema.

02:40:26.660 --> 02:40:30.900
[Amit Varma]: If anything, I think there are more serious film watchers now than ever before, because

02:40:30.900 --> 02:40:35.780
[Amit Varma]: you have the means to engage deeply with cinema and all of that.

02:40:35.780 --> 02:40:38.620
[Amit Varma]: So I don't think that that is necessarily an issue.

02:40:38.620 --> 02:40:42.900
[Amit Varma]: But what is necessarily an issue is that a lot of the shallow posturing is just dominating

02:40:42.900 --> 02:40:44.260
[Amit Varma]: the discourse out there.

02:40:44.260 --> 02:40:49.700
[Amit Varma]: So to a newcomer who would earlier 15 years ago, perhaps have discovered a movie through

02:40:49.700 --> 02:40:53.940
[Amit Varma]: reading something that you wrote on your blog, will now not want to watch the movie because

02:40:53.940 --> 02:40:57.780
[Amit Varma]: somebody else has called it toxic or misogynistic or whatever.

02:40:57.780 --> 02:41:01.700
[Amit Varma]: And that pollution of the discourse in general worries me.

02:41:01.700 --> 02:41:06.140
[Amit Varma]: But you know, moving aside from this sort of political angle, which is what it is, one

02:41:06.140 --> 02:41:10.460
[Amit Varma]: of the good things that's definitely happened is in terms of form, like it strikes me that

02:41:10.460 --> 02:41:14.940
[Amit Varma]: in the same way that you and I, we were talking about how in our writing, we were liberated

02:41:14.940 --> 02:41:20.540
[Amit Varma]: by blogging, because that form remove many of these constraints that we otherwise have.

02:41:20.540 --> 02:41:26.860
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that there has been a sort of a revolution of form within the audiovisual

02:41:26.860 --> 02:41:31.500
[Amit Varma]: medium in the last two or three decades as well, which, you know, for me, most significantly,

02:41:31.500 --> 02:41:34.940
[Amit Varma]: when HBO brought out the wire, that for me is a turning point.

02:41:34.940 --> 02:41:38.540
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, there were great shows before it, I mean, Kieslowski made Decalogue for

02:41:38.540 --> 02:41:39.540
[Amit Varma]: Polish television.

02:41:39.540 --> 02:41:43.860
[Amit Varma]: So that is, of course, a pinnacle of a series like this.

02:41:43.860 --> 02:41:49.300
[Amit Varma]: But for me, what was so incredibly exciting about the wire is in particular that that

02:41:49.300 --> 02:41:55.380
[Amit Varma]: show is that it allowed its creators to take on an almost novelistic sweep.

02:41:55.380 --> 02:41:59.500
[Amit Varma]: Like before that, I would think of each film as a sort of if I had to compare it to literature,

02:41:59.500 --> 02:42:02.060
[Amit Varma]: I would say it's really a short story of sorts.

02:42:02.060 --> 02:42:05.860
[Amit Varma]: It's one kind of narrative, you have two or three hours is a limit to how deep you can

02:42:05.860 --> 02:42:06.860
[Amit Varma]: go.

02:42:06.860 --> 02:42:07.860
[Amit Varma]: That's what it is.

02:42:07.860 --> 02:42:11.180
[Amit Varma]: What the wire really did was, it didn't have one main character, it had a whole bunch of

02:42:11.180 --> 02:42:13.260
[Amit Varma]: characters with tremendous depth.

02:42:13.260 --> 02:42:15.520
[Amit Varma]: It had that sweep, it had that range.

02:42:15.520 --> 02:42:20.700
[Amit Varma]: And what we now have because of the OTT revolution that, you know, Netflix kind of kickstarted

02:42:20.700 --> 02:42:26.300
[Amit Varma]: or really got going with House of Cards in the subsequent decade is that you have this

02:42:26.300 --> 02:42:27.300
[Amit Varma]: form.

02:42:27.300 --> 02:42:32.740
[Amit Varma]: So in a lot of terms, your audiovisual storytelling can now really expand and go places.

02:42:32.740 --> 02:42:37.460
[Amit Varma]: So number one, do you think this is significant because I don't know what the term cinema

02:42:37.460 --> 02:42:38.460
[Amit Varma]: even means.

02:42:38.460 --> 02:42:42.140
[Amit Varma]: So I'm using the general catch all term audiovisual storytelling, but it just seems to me that

02:42:42.140 --> 02:42:48.140
[Amit Varma]: this has way more scope today than it ever did in the same way as, for example, printed

02:42:48.140 --> 02:42:52.780
[Amit Varma]: books would have enabled longer forms of literature, which might not otherwise have been the case.

02:42:52.780 --> 02:42:57.740
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand there is this, but on the other hand, you also have the means of production

02:42:57.740 --> 02:43:03.420
[Amit Varma]: becoming much, much cheaper, which is why you have people on YouTube and TikTok expressing

02:43:03.420 --> 02:43:04.940
[Amit Varma]: themselves doing brave new things.

02:43:04.940 --> 02:43:10.260
[Amit Varma]: Like I don't know if you watch the vlogs of Casey Neistat, who is a YouTube creator, who's

02:43:10.260 --> 02:43:11.540
[Amit Varma]: doing very cinematic things.

02:43:11.540 --> 02:43:15.340
[Amit Varma]: At one point he would post a vlog a day and they would all be basically short films of

02:43:15.340 --> 02:43:19.300
[Amit Varma]: him doing interesting things, but made in a very cinematic way, creating a language

02:43:19.300 --> 02:43:20.300
[Amit Varma]: of his own.

02:43:20.300 --> 02:43:21.300
[Amit Varma]: Very influential.

02:43:21.300 --> 02:43:26.900
[Amit Varma]: And similarly in TikTok, you know, which like a lot of the stuff that becomes popular is

02:43:26.900 --> 02:43:30.940
[Amit Varma]: just wisecrack based stuff or funny stuff or memetic stuff.

02:43:30.940 --> 02:43:35.820
[Amit Varma]: But there was also a lot of other deeper stuff that was going on there, which was absolutely

02:43:35.820 --> 02:43:36.820
[Amit Varma]: mind blowing.

02:43:36.820 --> 02:43:41.240
[Amit Varma]: And it's hopefully still going on in the rest of the world, though sadly India banned it.

02:43:41.240 --> 02:43:46.060
[Amit Varma]: So the two separate questions, one, do you see that this expansion of form as something

02:43:46.060 --> 02:43:50.300
[Amit Varma]: that has led to a golden age of cinema, which I believe we are in, there's a lot of crap

02:43:50.300 --> 02:43:54.460
[Amit Varma]: around, but I believe that, you know, and could be the selection bias based on what

02:43:54.460 --> 02:43:58.900
[Amit Varma]: I get to see now, as opposed to what I got to see, say, 20 years earlier.

02:43:58.900 --> 02:44:01.380
[Amit Varma]: But you know, would you broadly agree with that?

02:44:01.380 --> 02:44:07.660
[Amit Varma]: And then do you see, is there a sense of excitement also about these new forms of filmmaking that

02:44:07.660 --> 02:44:09.300
[Amit Varma]: is being enabled by technology?

02:44:09.300 --> 02:44:15.620
[Guest]: No, again, I agree with pretty much everything you've said, even though I haven't experienced

02:44:15.620 --> 02:44:20.260
[Guest]: a lot of this stuff, you know, TikTok, for instance, is something that I haven't experienced.

02:44:20.260 --> 02:44:25.460
[Guest]: I know about your regard for a lot of what has been done there.

02:44:25.460 --> 02:44:31.820
[Guest]: And also, I find myself just in principle, I find myself quite irritated by some of the

02:44:31.820 --> 02:44:38.460
[Guest]: snobbery that was aimed at TikTok, especially when it was done by people who had this means

02:44:38.460 --> 02:44:43.820
[Guest]: of expressing their creativity, if they had had certain forms of creativity, and a lot

02:44:43.820 --> 02:44:48.300
[Guest]: of people from, you know, from another class who were sort of looking down on it and just

02:44:48.300 --> 02:44:52.780
[Guest]: being very condescending and saying some appallingly classist things about it.

02:44:52.780 --> 02:44:57.900
[Guest]: So that's why in principle, I agree with that completely, despite not having really experienced

02:44:57.900 --> 02:44:59.780
[Guest]: as much TikTok as you have.

02:44:59.780 --> 02:45:04.420
[Guest]: Likewise, for the for these shows, you know, I haven't seen The Wire, I haven't seen so

02:45:04.420 --> 02:45:08.900
[Guest]: many of these iconic shows, I haven't even watched Breaking Bad, for instance, there

02:45:08.900 --> 02:45:13.260
[Guest]: are so many shows that you'd be astonished to learn that I haven't watched and, and I

02:45:13.260 --> 02:45:17.700
[Guest]: don't think I'm going to end up doing it because my mind just recoils at the idea of taking

02:45:17.700 --> 02:45:19.860
[Guest]: out 30-40 hours for something like this.

02:45:19.860 --> 02:45:22.660
[Guest]: I don't know if I'll be able to do it now.

02:45:22.660 --> 02:45:28.180
[Guest]: But but again, in principle, and also based on my limited engagement with these things,

02:45:28.180 --> 02:45:33.140
[Guest]: because there are some series that I've watched, including a few of the Indian series, which

02:45:33.140 --> 02:45:37.380
[Guest]: which I had been asked to specifically review, which I keep getting told are not as good

02:45:37.380 --> 02:45:43.580
[Guest]: or as polished as the best international series, but, but I liked a lot of stuff about stuff

02:45:43.580 --> 02:45:48.580
[Guest]: in them. And I have great respect for the format.

02:45:48.580 --> 02:45:58.220
[Guest]: So you know, for the way in which in the hands of a good showrunner, a good scriptwriter,

02:45:58.220 --> 02:46:04.780
[Guest]: it's possible to just create this long narrative arc, to just sort of plan it out, you know,

02:46:04.780 --> 02:46:10.260
[Guest]: right from the start, and to have this trajectory where, where something that has been done

02:46:10.260 --> 02:46:15.420
[Guest]: in episode one or episode two, makes complete sense only, you know, perhaps in season two

02:46:15.420 --> 02:46:19.820
[Guest]: or season three, you know, it's been planned out that well beforehand.

02:46:19.820 --> 02:46:24.060
[Guest]: And that's something that's that, that you can only admire, you know, I often find myself

02:46:24.060 --> 02:46:29.340
[Guest]: wishing that that Alan Moore had been 30 or 40 years younger, because I think he would

02:46:29.340 --> 02:46:34.340
[Guest]: have been a fabulous showrunner for, for, you know, and I'm not just saying this because

02:46:34.340 --> 02:46:42.340
[Guest]: there's actually been a series of Watchmen. But I just think about, you know, the, what,

02:46:42.340 --> 02:46:46.780
[Guest]: what someone like Alan Moore, a younger version of Alan Moore would have done with something

02:46:46.780 --> 02:46:51.900
[Guest]: like From Hell or Watchmen or something, you know, you know, just creating this absolutely

02:46:51.900 --> 02:46:56.740
[Guest]: brilliant series, because because he did that so much in his actual writing and in the,

02:46:56.740 --> 02:47:02.340
[Guest]: in the, in the directions that he gave his artists for panel creation, back in the 80s

02:47:02.340 --> 02:47:08.220
[Guest]: and 90s. So, so I'm a big, so yeah, so in principle, I'm a big fan of this sort of thing.

02:47:08.220 --> 02:47:13.380
[Guest]: I was a late convert to it, because there was a time I think maybe seven, eight, nine

02:47:13.380 --> 02:47:18.900
[Guest]: years ago, when when people were raving about, about how there's this golden age of television

02:47:18.900 --> 02:47:25.180
[Guest]: and how so much of what we have on television is brilliantly cinematic, it's as it's better

02:47:25.180 --> 02:47:28.700
[Guest]: than most of what you see in cinema halls.

02:47:28.700 --> 02:47:35.540
[Guest]: At that point, I said, really, I mean, it's, how is it going to be cinematic? It'll probably

02:47:35.540 --> 02:47:39.700
[Guest]: just be pictures of people talking, right? It'll be because I still have that stereotyped

02:47:39.700 --> 02:47:45.500
[Guest]: idea of what, what a TV show look like, say, back in the 70s or 80s. You know, I'm talking

02:47:45.500 --> 02:47:49.740
[Guest]: about international shows. So, of course, I was pleasantly surprised by what I did end

02:47:49.740 --> 02:47:56.820
[Guest]: up watching eventually. And I completely get that this is a very exciting time. I do tend

02:47:56.820 --> 02:48:03.980
[Guest]: to be slightly resistant to the talk of golden ages, partly because of the recency biases

02:48:03.980 --> 02:48:08.580
[Guest]: and things that we have, partly because because I'm so old in my head that I find it very

02:48:08.580 --> 02:48:16.180
[Guest]: difficult to think of anything other than 1940s Hollywood, as as the golden age of cinema,

02:48:16.180 --> 02:48:23.060
[Guest]: or even or even the 1920s, when when the silent film was heading towards his great apotheosis,

02:48:23.060 --> 02:48:30.660
[Guest]: and then was unfortunately destroyed by the coming of sound. So, so I'm, I'm that vintage.

02:48:30.660 --> 02:48:35.740
[Guest]: But But again, in principle, yes, I have no trouble with with with anyone referring to

02:48:35.740 --> 02:48:43.020
[Guest]: the current moment as a golden age, in terms of web series, TV, in particular, OTT.

02:48:43.020 --> 02:48:49.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, so now I've come to know that, you know, given that you live in that era,

02:48:49.260 --> 02:48:53.700
[Amit Varma]: the Philadelphia story for you must be something made by young whippersnappers. But it's so

02:48:53.700 --> 02:48:58.060
[Amit Varma]: fascinating that we can kind of inhabit not just different characters, but different eras

02:48:58.060 --> 02:49:01.900
[Amit Varma]: in this way and immerse ourselves in different worlds. I mean, that's the beauty of cinema,

02:49:01.900 --> 02:49:06.740
[Amit Varma]: literature, art, all of that. Now, so we've already chatted for around three hours, and

02:49:06.740 --> 02:49:10.740
[Amit Varma]: we haven't even spoken about books, I wanted to speak to you about writing and your writing

02:49:10.740 --> 02:49:14.780
[Amit Varma]: process we haven't even gotten there. And I wanted to chat with you about Hindi cinema

02:49:14.780 --> 02:49:19.500
[Amit Varma]: and Rishikesh Mukherjee as well, which we will save for a future episode. So I will

02:49:19.500 --> 02:49:24.340
[Amit Varma]: extract that promise from you now that we'll talk again. But before we end this particular

02:49:24.340 --> 02:49:29.820
[Amit Varma]: episode, normally, I kind of end my episodes by asking my guests to recommend books that

02:49:29.820 --> 02:49:34.740
[Amit Varma]: they love. But in your case, it's going to be both books and films that you know, and

02:49:34.740 --> 02:49:40.700
[Amit Varma]: I don't want a best of list. That's an insane expectation. But just, you know, off the top

02:49:40.700 --> 02:49:46.820
[Amit Varma]: of your head, five books or films that you feel you would like to share with the world.

02:49:46.820 --> 02:49:52.700
[Guest]: Five books, five films, my God. I was oddly enough, I wasn't prepared for this moment

02:49:52.700 --> 02:49:55.820
[Guest]: in the podcast, even though it's such an obvious one.

02:49:55.820 --> 02:50:00.140
[Amit Varma]: Or three of each or whatever comes to mind. I don't want it to be like a formal thing

02:50:00.140 --> 02:50:01.140
[Amit Varma]: ki arey yeh...

02:50:01.140 --> 02:50:02.140
[Guest]: How about 300 of each?

02:50:02.140 --> 02:50:03.140
[Guest]: Done.

02:50:03.140 --> 02:50:09.620
[Guest]: I'll take the easy way out by recommending one Rishikesh Mukherjee film that no one seems

02:50:09.620 --> 02:50:16.500
[Guest]: to have heard of, including possibly Rishita himself. But it really is it is honestly,

02:50:16.500 --> 02:50:21.040
[Guest]: one of my absolute favorites. I feel very defensively about it because it's the sort

02:50:21.040 --> 02:50:26.220
[Guest]: of film that just you know, even those who do discover it, unfortunately, it's available

02:50:26.220 --> 02:50:31.940
[Guest]: only in a very ordinary print online on YouTube. It hasn't been restored or anything. It's

02:50:31.940 --> 02:50:36.900
[Guest]: a 1965 film called Bibi Aur Makaan. And Amit, in fact, I actually think this might be a

02:50:36.900 --> 02:50:43.220
[Guest]: film that might even be worth your while to watch, or to at least try and watch some of.

02:50:43.220 --> 02:50:47.540
[Guest]: Because I think you will at the very least agree with me that it's a very interesting

02:50:47.540 --> 02:50:53.260
[Guest]: Hindi film for its time for what it does with the musical form. It was produced by Hemant

02:50:53.260 --> 02:50:59.260
[Guest]: Kumar, who was of course the great music director. And it was Gulzar's first collaboration as

02:50:59.260 --> 02:51:05.580
[Guest]: a lyricist with Rishikesh Mukherjee. And it's this film that's basically almost operatic

02:51:05.580 --> 02:51:11.740
[Guest]: in terms of how it tells this fairly lowbrow comedy story of friends who are forced into

02:51:11.740 --> 02:51:17.980
[Guest]: a cross-dressing shenanigan because they can't get accommodation. So two of them have to

02:51:17.980 --> 02:51:24.780
[Guest]: pretend to be wives of the other two. But it just uses musical sequences so interestingly,

02:51:24.780 --> 02:51:30.940
[Guest]: as you know, as part of the narrative, as things that take the narrative forward. Sequences

02:51:30.940 --> 02:51:36.980
[Guest]: that actually require the actors to be really acting, performing, requires a certain degree

02:51:36.980 --> 02:51:43.060
[Guest]: of orchestration in terms of how the movements are done and so on. It's an example of, it's

02:51:43.060 --> 02:51:48.700
[Guest]: definitely a counterpoint to the idea that many people have that a lot of Hindi cinema

02:51:48.700 --> 02:51:54.260
[Guest]: just used musical sequences as a standalone, which was completely divorced from the main

02:51:54.260 --> 02:51:59.060
[Guest]: narrative. So it's a film that I have a lot of love for. It's also the Rishikesh Mukherjee

02:51:59.060 --> 02:52:03.860
[Guest]: comedy that that's a direct precursor to the later well-known comedies like Golmaal and

02:52:03.860 --> 02:52:10.540
[Guest]: Chhupke Chhupke. Other films, well, Psycho, of course, I've already spoken about. I'm

02:52:10.540 --> 02:52:15.380
[Guest]: not going to get into all that. I'm not going to say Jaane Bhi Do Yaro either because that's

02:52:15.380 --> 02:52:19.740
[Guest]: that's that's just too obvious. And because I've, I'm probably fed up of the film by now,

02:52:19.740 --> 02:52:23.180
[Guest]: I don't think I could watch it again after having watched it those dozens of times for

02:52:23.180 --> 02:52:30.820
[Guest]: the for the book that I did on it. But there are lots of noir films of the 1940s, again,

02:52:30.820 --> 02:52:36.820
[Guest]: coming back to 1940s Hollywood that I have a lot of time for and a lot of love for. One

02:52:36.820 --> 02:52:43.900
[Guest]: of them, of course, is the Billy Wilder film called An Ace in the Hole, also known as The

02:52:43.900 --> 02:52:52.820
[Guest]: Big Carnival, which seems like extremely resistant as I am to things like relevance or topicality.

02:52:52.820 --> 02:52:57.900
[Guest]: It feels like a very relevant film for the current day as well. It's 70 years old and

02:52:57.900 --> 02:53:03.580
[Guest]: it has Kirk Douglas as this this reporter who tries to exploit a very tragic situation

02:53:03.580 --> 02:53:09.380
[Guest]: involving a man who's been trapped in a cave. And it feels like something that's that's

02:53:09.380 --> 02:53:13.900
[Guest]: very pertinent to the media carnivals of the current day as well. And of course, there

02:53:13.900 --> 02:53:18.180
[Guest]: was a Hindi film from a few years ago called Peepli Live, which which also explored similar

02:53:18.180 --> 02:53:24.260
[Guest]: terrain, a media carnival built around an inherently tragic and personal situation.

02:53:24.260 --> 02:53:32.620
[Guest]: Well, those are three books. I grew up with a tremendous love for Enid Blyton's Faraway

02:53:32.620 --> 02:53:40.500
[Guest]: Tree series. I think a lot of the trio of books that that made up these stories about

02:53:40.500 --> 02:53:46.860
[Guest]: about this little brother and sister who moved to the countryside and then, you know, find

02:53:46.860 --> 02:53:53.220
[Guest]: themselves being taken to all these magical lands at the top of a magical tree deep in

02:53:53.220 --> 02:53:59.300
[Guest]: the woods. It's also one of those books that first opened my eyes to the possibilities

02:53:59.300 --> 02:54:09.500
[Guest]: of of how writing can literally take you to uncharted places or to new lands or to places

02:54:09.500 --> 02:54:21.220
[Guest]: that otherwise can exist only in your fantasies. As someone who's been a huge Mahabharat fan

02:54:21.220 --> 02:54:27.820
[Guest]: for the longest time, one book that I love is Shivaji Sawant's Samrityunjay, which was

02:54:27.820 --> 02:54:36.180
[Guest]: written in Marathi. It's been translated in English by P. Lal and Nandini Noppani. I've

02:54:36.180 --> 02:54:39.740
[Guest]: read the English version and I've also read a great deal of the Hindi version. The Hindi

02:54:39.740 --> 02:54:45.180
[Guest]: translation is the only book that I've read a lot of in the only novel that I've read

02:54:45.180 --> 02:54:50.220
[Guest]: a lot of in Hindi. And it also ties in a little bit with some of the stuff you were talking

02:54:50.220 --> 02:54:53.220
[Guest]: about earlier, because because because this is a book that centered around the character

02:54:53.220 --> 02:54:59.580
[Guest]: of Kald, who was one of my personal heroes growing up, one of those tragic figures, those

02:54:59.580 --> 02:55:05.020
[Guest]: anti-hero figures that that I felt a tremendous affinity to, perhaps as a melancholy child

02:55:05.020 --> 02:55:14.820
[Guest]: myself. And what I love about what Shivaji Sawant did with this book is, is how he again

02:55:14.820 --> 02:55:18.860
[Guest]: tying in with some of the things we were talking about earlier about the problematic behavior

02:55:18.860 --> 02:55:25.820
[Guest]: of people and so on, how he puts us in the mind space of a very conflicted and tormented

02:55:25.820 --> 02:55:30.980
[Guest]: character at precisely the point when that character is doing some morally very questionable

02:55:30.980 --> 02:55:37.060
[Guest]: things. So, for instance, during the humiliation of Draupadi in the Swayamvar, after the dice

02:55:37.060 --> 02:55:43.580
[Guest]: came, Kald's part in that, in that process, there's this brilliant 20-page passage in

02:55:43.580 --> 02:55:48.500
[Guest]: this book, which counts among the finest bits of literature I've read anywhere, where in

02:55:48.500 --> 02:55:54.980
[Guest]: Kald's voice, in his first person voice, Shivaji Sawant just gives us this man who goes from

02:55:54.980 --> 02:55:59.620
[Guest]: a point where he actually wants to be the savior. He wants to be the chivalrous hero

02:55:59.620 --> 02:56:06.740
[Guest]: to this woman who's in distress. He goes from there, over, you know, a series of things

02:56:06.740 --> 02:56:10.980
[Guest]: that happen, you know, the way his mind is working in this very fevered way, the way

02:56:10.980 --> 02:56:16.580
[Guest]: he's responding to the things that are happening around him. He goes from there to actually

02:56:16.580 --> 02:56:22.180
[Guest]: saying some of the cruelest and most savage things to her in her moment of distress. And

02:56:22.180 --> 02:56:27.740
[Guest]: the way that's done is just an eye opener for what literature can achieve in terms of

02:56:27.740 --> 02:56:32.500
[Guest]: putting us in the mind space of a problematic character or somebody who's doing something

02:56:32.500 --> 02:56:40.620
[Guest]: problematic and making us empathize and perhaps seeing that we too are capable of such behavior,

02:56:40.620 --> 02:56:45.620
[Guest]: you know, in the right context or the wrong context or whatever it is. I love that book

02:56:45.620 --> 02:56:55.900
[Guest]: for that reason. I'm a big fan of Kazuo Ishiguro's confounding novel, The Unconsoled, which is

02:56:55.900 --> 02:57:01.180
[Amit Varma]: his longest book. Which you've described memorably as a book that spends 500 pages going from

02:57:01.180 --> 02:57:07.780
[Amit Varma]: point A to point A. Did I do that? Where? That's your description. See, you don't even

02:57:07.780 --> 02:57:13.500
[Guest]: know what you've written. That's a pretty good description. I should start plagiarizing

02:57:13.500 --> 02:57:20.020
[Guest]: myself now at some point. But no, so again, that's among Ishiguro's first 506 novels.

02:57:20.020 --> 02:57:27.140
[Guest]: This was easily the least read, I think, and the one that I think was possibly the only

02:57:27.140 --> 02:57:31.820
[Guest]: one of his first six books that wasn't shortlisted for the Booker Prize. I'm not sure if I got

02:57:31.820 --> 02:57:38.160
[Guest]: that right. But it was definitely a book that confounded a lot of people for very good reason.

02:57:38.160 --> 02:57:45.980
[Guest]: But I loved it because it was one of my first introductions in literature to the truly surrealistic

02:57:45.980 --> 02:57:55.180
[Guest]: narrative, to what surrealism means on the page, in terms of creating this world that

02:57:55.180 --> 02:58:02.180
[Guest]: is both seemingly real and completely exaggerated at the same time. Directions mean nothing,

02:58:02.180 --> 02:58:05.980
[Guest]: where geography means nothing, time means nothing, everything is stretched out. I'd

02:58:05.980 --> 02:58:13.900
[Guest]: encountered the equivalence for these things in the films of Buñuel, for instance, or

02:58:13.900 --> 02:58:19.260
[Guest]: in some of the paintings that I knew of Salvador Dali, The Persistence of Time, The Persistence

02:58:19.260 --> 02:58:24.620
[Guest]: of Time, with the melting clocks. But I think this may have been the first time that I really

02:58:24.620 --> 02:58:30.940
[Guest]: experienced its equivalent in a novel. And I was blown away by it all the more so because

02:58:30.940 --> 02:58:37.100
[Guest]: I opened that book with no idea of what it was going to be like. I just thought it would

02:58:37.100 --> 02:58:42.420
[Guest]: be a regular narrative story. And then I found myself having to figure the book out in the

02:58:42.420 --> 02:58:46.620
[Guest]: process of reading it and figure out what this writer is trying to do. And it was a

02:58:46.620 --> 02:58:50.340
[Guest]: fascinating experience. That's it, three of each?

02:58:50.340 --> 02:58:56.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, three of each. You're done. And in fact, when I read The Unconsoled, it gave me so

02:58:56.380 --> 02:58:59.780
[Amit Varma]: much joy and delight. And I'm really glad I didn't have to write about the book because

02:58:59.780 --> 02:59:02.980
[Amit Varma]: then I would have had to work so hard trying to articulate why it gave me that joy and

02:59:02.980 --> 02:59:06.860
[Amit Varma]: delight. Because you're right, it's just a confounded book that way. And you mentioned

02:59:06.860 --> 02:59:11.820
[Amit Varma]: Buñuel's, you know, some of his surrealistic work. And I especially am a big fan of the

02:59:11.820 --> 02:59:15.940
[Amit Varma]: last three films he made in the 70s, all of which were co-written with Jean-Claude Carrière,

02:59:15.940 --> 02:59:19.580
[Amit Varma]: who I think died a few months ago. You know, The Discrete Charm of the Bourgeoisie, which

02:59:19.580 --> 02:59:23.780
[Amit Varma]: is about a bunch of people who are sitting down to a meal, but they never actually eat

02:59:23.780 --> 02:59:28.460
[Amit Varma]: anything. It's just they keep sitting down and the meal never happens. Then in 74, he

02:59:28.460 --> 02:59:32.540
[Amit Varma]: made The Phantom of Liberty, which is again a delightful and confounding film, where you

02:59:32.540 --> 02:59:38.300
[Amit Varma]: know, he'll start with the camera on a set of characters in a scene. And, you know, one

02:59:38.300 --> 02:59:41.980
[Amit Varma]: of them seems to be the main guy, but then it'll follow some random person he meets and

02:59:41.980 --> 02:59:46.460
[Amit Varma]: do another scene with that guy, and so on. And it's all disconnected. It's not even connected

02:59:46.460 --> 02:59:51.020
[Amit Varma]: segments. It's all kind of disconnected, like, you know, passing the ball kind of thing.

02:59:51.020 --> 02:59:56.260
[Amit Varma]: And then finally, in 77, he made that Obscure Object of Desire, which included two actresses

02:59:56.260 --> 03:00:00.900
[Amit Varma]: playing the same woman, thus, you know, adding to her mystique and all of that. So those

03:00:00.900 --> 03:00:05.580
[Amit Varma]: three films of Buñuel, which were made when he was in the 70s, if I remember correctly,

03:00:05.580 --> 03:00:08.380
[Amit Varma]: and just in the 1970s, were...

03:00:08.380 --> 03:00:13.380
[Guest]: So The Phantom of Liberty is a great favourite of mine as well. And Jean-Claude Carrier actually,

03:00:13.380 --> 03:00:17.780
[Guest]: I spoke with Jean-Claude Carrier about it many years ago, around 15 years ago or something.

03:00:17.780 --> 03:00:23.820
[Guest]: And he told me that the idea for that film just came from a little conversation he and

03:00:23.820 --> 03:00:27.980
[Guest]: Buñuel were having where they were saying, let's, why don't we do something that completely

03:00:27.980 --> 03:00:31.540
[Guest]: defies the laws of narrative. So you know, so you have this, let's imagine the scene

03:00:31.540 --> 03:00:37.900
[Guest]: where a husband and a wife are arguing ferociously about something. And we don't know exactly

03:00:37.900 --> 03:00:43.820
[Guest]: what they're arguing about. But we know that their argument pivots on the contents of a

03:00:43.820 --> 03:00:47.980
[Guest]: letter that is shortly to be delivered to their house. We figured this out from their

03:00:47.980 --> 03:00:54.300
[Guest]: conversation. And they are fighting in this very abstract way, and there are tears and

03:00:54.300 --> 03:00:59.540
[Guest]: recriminations. And then there's a knock on the door. And one of them opens the door and

03:00:59.540 --> 03:01:03.380
[Guest]: the postman is standing there with the letter, hands the letter over to them. They start

03:01:03.380 --> 03:01:08.900
[Guest]: to open the letter, the camera follows the postman out the door. And, and, and, you know,

03:01:08.900 --> 03:01:16.020
[Guest]: to see what what he's up to next. And it's, yeah, it's a lovely film. So yeah, so, so

03:01:16.020 --> 03:01:21.780
[Guest]: the unconsoled, as you can imagine, was also made me feel the same, you know, somewhat

03:01:21.780 --> 03:01:25.820
[Guest]: similar to watching some of those Buñuel films.

03:01:25.820 --> 03:01:32.340
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so I mean, you know, I think lots of dope people, you know, all the films and books

03:01:32.340 --> 03:01:35.900
[Amit Varma]: and everything that we mentioned, we'll link it from the show notes. Jai, thank you so

